ation page 1]</ref>{{,}}<ref>[http://www12.statcan.ca/english/Profil01/CP01/Details/Page.cfm?Lang=F&Geo1=CSD&Code1=1314014&Geo2=PR&Code2=13&Data=Count&SearchText=Campbellton&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=13&B1=Population&Custom=/ Profils des communaut\u00e9s de 2001 - Campbellton - Population Statistique Canada]</ref>\n|}\n\n==Arts and culture==\n[[Image:Riverside park campbellton.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Riverside Park - Campbellton.]]\nThe Restigouche Caledonian Society has been in Campbellton since 1898, the society was formed for the purpose of offering relief and assistance to distressed Scotsmen. The First President of the society was also The First Mayor of Campbellton [[John McAlister]]. To display the history of the city and the battle of the Restigouche, Riverside Park is home to two cannons used in the battle; one with three fleurs-de-lys on the barrel and the other with what appears to be stylized anchors. These are French naval guns from a five gun battery erected during the battle at Battery Point on the Quebec side of the river. When the Busteed family received a land grant at Battery Point, circa 1790, they found at least three cannons at the old battery site. One cannon was built into the fireplace of their home, called Bordeaux House, and two others were given to relatives across the river at Athol House in Atholville. For many years the two cannons outside Athol House were fired on ceremonial occasions. After Athol House burned, the guns lay on the riverbank until donated to the City of Campbellton in 1898. The park also features two monuments donated to the City displaying the names of local soldiers who died in battle during World War I and World War II.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.unb.ca/nbmhp/counties/Restigouche.html |title=Restigouche County  |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070824155528/https://www.unb.ca/nbmhp/counties/Restigouche.html |archivedate=August 24, 2007 |website=New Brunswick Military Heritage Project}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Restigouche Gallery]] is local gallery and functions as a centre in the cultural program of the region. It has been host to major exhibitions from the N.B. Museum on a travelling basis in hopes that the gallery will eventually join the [[Atlantic Provinces Art Circuit]] as a participatory member. The gallery displays a tricultural permanent exhibition highlighting the cultural strength of the region bringing to the forefront Campbellton's diverse roots through its heritage [[Listuguj Mi'gmaq First Nation|Mi'gmaqs]], [[Scottish people|Scottish]] and the French & [[Acadians]] heritage.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://restigouchegallery.ca/ |title=Restigouche Gallery |accessdate=August 21, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Events===\nThe City hosts multiple annual special events which include Sno-Fest in February,<ref>{{cite web |title=Special Events: Campbellton Sno-Fest |url=http://www.campbellton.org/camp2/SpecialEventsSnofest.asp |publisher=City of Campbellton |accessdate=August 21, 2019}}</ref> Salmon Fest which runs from late June to early July,<ref>{{cite web |title=Campbellton Salmon Festival |url=http://www.campbellton.org/camp2/SpecialEventsSalmon.asp |publisher=City of Campbellton |accessdate=August 21, 2019}}</ref> the Bluegrass Festival which takes place in September,<ref>{{cite web |title=Campbellton Bluegrass Festival |url=http://www.campbellton.org/camp2/SpecialEventsbluegrass.asp |publisher=City of Campbellton |accessdate=August 21, 2019}}</ref> and the Harvest Festival in the fall.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.campbellton.org/camp2/SpecialEventsharvest.asp |title=Campbellton Harvest Festival |publisher=City of Campbellton |accessdate=August 21, 2019}}</ref> Other efforts to increase tourism include an 8.5 metre (27.88&nbsp;ft) salmon statue made of stainless steel. Restigouche Sam, as the statue was christened, was donated to the city to honour Campbellton's historical connection with the \"salmon-rich\" Restigouche River. Several murals have also been created to beautify the city.\n\nIn 2017, Campbellton celebrated the 50th Anniversaries for both the Salmon Festival as well as its Centennial Library.\n\n==Sports==\n\nThe [[Memorial Civic Center|Memorial Civic Centre]] is the most important sporting infrastructure in the city. The Memorial Civic Centre opened in downtown Campbellton on the bank of the Restigouche River in 1992, following a fire to the 1950s era Memorial Arena located on Arran Street. Its 3,500 seat multi-purpose arena with Olympic size ice surface is home to the [[Maritime Junior Hockey League]]'s Junior A [[ice hockey]] team, the [[Campbellton Tigers]]. The complex is equipped to accommodate sporting events, entertainment, commercial functions and trade shows on a local, regional or national basis.\n\n*The 2003 [[Canada Winter Games]] took place in the facility and [[Sidney Crosby]] was present to represent his native [[Nova Scotia]] in the sport of [[ice hockey]].\n*In 2006, the city was host to the [[Acadian Games]].\n*In 2009, [[CBC Television|CBC]]'s [[Hockey Day in Canada]] was broadcast from Campbellton, where [[Ron MacLean]] and [[Don Cherry]] did their segment of [[Coach's Corner]] at the Memorial Civic Centre.\n\nCampbellton has an 18-hole golf course, the Restigouche Golf Club which was founded in 1923 and overlooks the [[Restigouche River]].\n\n===Campbellton Tigers===\nFrom 1967\u201368 to 1989\u201390, the [[Hardy Cup]] was awarded to the Intermediate \"A\" and later Senior \"AA\" champion of Canada. The Tigers won more championships than any other team with three titles, in 1972, 1977 and 1988. In fact, only the [[Charlottetown Islanders]] won the cup more than once with two titles. The Tigers won the Col. J. Bourque Trophy as Eastern Canada Champions a record 4 times. The Eastern Canada champions faced the Western Canada champions for the Hardy Cup for the title of  Champions of Canada. The 1972 and 1977 teams were inducted into the [[New Brunswick Sports Hall of Fame]] as part of the Campbellton hockey dynasty of the 1970s.<ref>{{cite web |title=Honoured Members - C |url=http://www.honouredmembers.com/name/?letter_order=18&submit=Submit |publisher=New Brunswick Sports Hall of Fame |accessdate=August 21, 2019}}</ref> [[Gerry Ouellette]], former member of the [[Boston Bruins]], coached all three championship teams and the fourth team in 1978 which lost in the finals. Ouellette was a player-coach for the first title in 1972.\n\n'''1971\u20131972'''\nThe 1972 Campbellton Tigers defeated the [[Rosetown Red Wings]] 3 games to 2 in the best of five finals which were held in [[Rosetown, Saskatchewan]]. The team was inducted into the New Brunswick Sports Hall of Fame in 1998, and included [[Gord Gallant]] and [[Peter Maher (hockey announcer)|Peter Maher]].\n\n'''1976\u20131977'''\nThe 1977 Campbellton Tigers defeated the [[Warroad Lakers]] of [[Warroad, Minnesota]] 3 games to 1 in the best of five finals which were held in Campbellton, New Brunswick. The Tigers had a record of 49 wins, 5 losses and 1 tie during the regular season and a record of 24 wins and 1 loss in the playoffs. The team was inducted into the New Brunswick Sports Hall of Fame in 2002.\n\n==Education==\n{{Main|List of schools in New Brunswick}}\n[[File:Le Galion des Appalaches - Campbellton, New Brunswick.jpg|thumb|320x320px|Le Galion des Appalaches is the region's newest school. It opened in 2018]]\nCampbellton is home to two high schools: one catering to the francophone community ([[Polyvalente Roland-P\u00e9pin]])<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dsfne.ca/ecole/polyvalente-roland-pepin-campbellton/|title=Polyvalente Roland-P\u00e9pin Campbellton NB|last=|first=|date=|website=District Scolaire Francophone Nord-Est|access-date=April 19, 2019}}</ref> and the other to the English community ([[Sugarloaf Senior High School]]). The other grade schools are Lord Beaverbrook School and [[Campbellton Middle School]] for English students, however they will soon be replaced with a new Regional Anglophone School, upon which construction was supposed to commence in 2019, but was delayed by at least one year by the provincial government in December 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://asd-n.nbed.nb.ca/schools|title=Anglophone School District - North {{!}} Schools|last=|first=|date=|website=Anglophone School District - North|access-date=April 19, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://da.tj.news/viewer?opub=The_Tribune&date=20181214&page=1|title=Telegraph Journal Digital Archives - The Tribune {{!}} Dec. 14, 2018: Page 1|last=|first=|date=December 14, 2018|work=The Tribune|access-date=April 19, 2019}}</ref> A new francophone K-8 School, [[Le Galion des Appalaches]], was completed and opened in early 2018, combining the students who had previously gone to older schools in [[Atholville, New Brunswick|Atholville]] and Campbellton.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www2.gnb.ca/content/gnb/en/departments/education/news/news_release.2018.04.0443.html|title=Official opening of Le Galion des Appalaches School|last=|first=|date=|website=Government of New Brunswick|access-date=April 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\nEnglish schools are served by [[Anglophone North School District]], while francophone schools are part of the [[Francophone Nord-Est School District|District scolaire francophone Nord-Est]] (Francophone Nord-Est School District).\n\nThe [[New Brunswick Community College]] CCNB has a campus in Campbellton which provides instruction in various trades, including woodworking, office administration, social services and health sciences.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ccnb.ca/le-ccnb/nos-campus/campus-de-campbellton.aspx|title=CCNB - Le Campus de Campbellton|last=|first=|date=|website=Coll\u00e8ge Communautaire du Nouveau-Brunswick|access-date=April 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Transportation==\n[[File:Gare de Campbellton 04.jpg|thumb|300x300px|The Via Rail Station in Campbellton]]\nThe [[Campbellton railway station]] is served by Via-Rail's train [[Ocean (train)|\"The Ocean\"]] which travels the [[Montreal]]-[[Halifax Regional Municipality|Halifax]] route three times a week.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://da.tj.news/viewer?opub=The_Northern_Light&date=20181113&page=11|title=Telegraph Journal Digital Archives - The Northern Light {{!}} Nov. 13, 2018: Page 11|last=|first=|date=November 13, 2018|work=The Northern Light|access-date=April 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\nMajor bus services include [[Maritime Bus]] in Campbellton, and [[Orl\u00e9ans Express]] across the river in [[Pointe-\u00e0-la-Croix, Quebec|Pointe-\u00e0-la-Croix]]. The Maritime Bus terminal is located at the Irving/Circle K gas station on Roseberry Street, near Sobeys, while the Orl\u00e9ans Express terminal is at the Lord Gaz Bar (Crevier), on Interprovincial Boulevard.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://maritimebus.com/locations/locations-new-brunswick/campbellton/|title=Maritime Bus Locations - Campbellton NB|last=|first=|date=|website=Maritime Bus|access-date=April 19, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.orleansexpress.com/en/bus-pointe-a-la-croix/|title=Bus to Pointe-\u00e0-la-Croix|last=|first=|date=|website=Orl\u00e9ans Express|access-date=April 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThere is also a summertime tour bus which makes its way downtown. Multiple taxi companies provide the City and outskirts with taxi service 24 hours a day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yellowpages.ca/search/si/1/Taxis/Campbellton%2C+NB/rci-Campbellton%2C+NB|title=Taxis in Campbellton, NB|last=|first=|date=|website=Yellow Pages|access-date=April 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe [[J. C. Van Horne Bridge]] connects Campbellton to the province of [[Quebec]]. [[New Brunswick Route 11|Route 11]] provides a major highway connection to other major centres in the northern part of the province such as [[Bathurst, New Brunswick|Bathurst]] and [[Miramichi, New Brunswick|Miramichi]], as well as providing a link to [[Moncton]], and the [[New Brunswick Route 2|Trans-Canada Highway]]. Travelling west, this highway becomes [[New Brunswick Route 17|Route 17]] at the [[Tide Head]] - [[Matap\u00e9dia, Quebec|Matap\u00e9dia]] exit, which is the only highway which connects the North Shore to the northwestern part of the province.\n\nCampbellton is served by [[Charlo Airport]], about 20 minutes away by car, which offers direct scheduled flights to [[Halifax Stanfield International Airport|Halifax]] and [[Wabush Airport|Wabush]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.palairlines.ca/en/fly-pal/where-we-fly/|title=Where We Fly {{!}} The Route We Take|last=|first=|date=|website=PAL Airlines|access-date=April 19, 2019}}</ref> The city is also located within just over an hour's drive of [[Bathurst Airport (New Brunswick)|Bathurst Airport]], which has daily [[Air Canada]] flights to [[Montr\u00e9al\u2013Pierre Elliott Trudeau International Airport|Montreal]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.google.ca/maps/dir/Campbellton,+NB/Regional+Bathurst+Airport,+Route+180,+South+Tetagouche,+NB/@47.8121653,-66.3647179,100312m/data=!3m1!1e3!4m14!4m13!1m5!1m1!1s0x4c98212884a647d5:0x34093d62d392e8e2!2m2!1d-66.6722057!2d48.007399!1m5!1m1!1s0x4c98919259be487d:0x35fbc1952f6fd963!2m2!1d-65.7434886!2d47.6307404!3e0|title=Google Maps {{!}} Get Directions - Campbellton NB to Regional Bathurst Airport|last=|first=|date=|website=Google Maps|access-date=April 19, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aircanada.com/ca/en/aco/home.html?ef_id=EAIaIQobChMIzs_Gx7_b4QIVkYuzCh3bbAGcEAAYASAAEgJJL_D_BwE:G:s&s_kwcid=AL!5182!3!291262319519!e!!g!!air%20canada&gclid=EAIaIQobChMIzs_Gx7_b4QIVkYuzCh3bbAGcEAAYASAAEgJJL_D_BwE&gclsrc=aw.ds#/faredriven:0|title=Departing Flight Bathurst, New Brunswick (ZBF) to Montr\u00e9al (YUL) Friday, April 19th, 2019|last=|first=|date=|website=Air Canada|access-date=April 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Health care==\n{{Main|List of hospitals in New Brunswick}}\nThe city is serviced by 2 health care facilities, Campbellton Regional Hospital and the Restigouche Hospital Centre, which houses a psychiatric care facility.<ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/new-brunswick/kyle-edmund-scott-dies-in-renous-prison-1.2808896 cbc.ca: \"Kyle Edmund Scott dies in Renous prison\"], 22 Oct 2014</ref> Campbellton benefits from the 100 bed Campbellton Nursing Home Inc. and many special care homes and personal care centers.\n\n==Climate==\nCampbellton has a cold, wet and snowy [[humid continental climate]] with vast seasonal temperature differences, although summers are somewhat moderated by its proximity to the cold waters of the [[Gulf of Saint Lawrence]]. Moderation is nearly non-existent in winter, as prevailing wind from the interior cause temperatures to often plummet below {{convert|-20|C|F}}.\n\n{{Weather box\n|location = Campbellton\n|metric first = yes\n|single line = yes\n|Jan record high C = 12.5\n|Feb record high C = 14.5\n|Mar record high C = 19.4\n|Apr record high C = 29.4\n|May record high C = 32.8\n|Jun record high C = 33.5\n|Jul record high C = 35.6\n|Aug record high C = 34.4\n|Sep record high C = 32.8\n|Oct record high C = 26.7\n|Nov record high C = 19.5\n|Dec record high C = 13.9\n|Jan high C = \u22128.8\n|Feb high C = \u22126.9\n|Mar high C = \u22120.2\n|Apr high C = 6.9\n|May high C = 15.4\n|Jun high C = 21.1\n|Jul high C = 23.5\n|Aug high C = 22.4\n|Sep high C = 16.4\n|Oct high C = 9.5\n|Nov high C = 1.8\n|Dec high C = \u22125.5\n|year high C = 9.7\n|Jan low C = \u221220.1\n|Feb low C = \u221219.2\n|Mar low C = \u221211.9\n|Apr low C = \u22123.8\n|May low C = 2\n|Jun low C = 7.6\n|Jul low C = 10.7\n|Aug low C = 9.7\n|Sep low C = 4.8\n|Oct low C = 0\n|Nov low C = \u22125.9\n|Dec low C = \u221215.1\n|year low C = \u22120.4\n|Jan record low C = \u221242.8\n|Feb record low C = \u221241.7\n|Mar record low C = \u221236.5\n|Apr record low C = \u221228\n|May record low C = \u221212.8\n|Jun record low C = \u22126\n|Jul record low C = \u22120.6\n|Aug record low C = \u22122\n|Sep record low C = \u22127.8\n|Oct record low C = \u221214\n|Nov record low C = \u221227.2\n|Dec record low C = \u221240\n|precipitation colour = green\n|Jan precipitation mm = 73\n|Feb precipitation mm = 55\n|Mar precipitation mm = 69\n|Apr precipitation mm = 70\n|May precipitation mm = 83\n|Jun precipitation mm = 91\n|Jul precipitation mm = 121\n|Aug precipitation mm = 109\n|Sep precipitation mm = 92\n|Oct precipitation mm = 91\n|Nov precipitation mm = 85\n|Dec precipitation mm = 87\n|year precipitation mm = 1026\n|source 1 = [[The Weather Network]]<ref name=\"climate\">[[The Weather Network]]\n[http://www.theweathernetwork.com/statistics/CL7051200/canb0018 Statistics: Campbellton, New Brunswick]. Retrieved 02 December 2011.</ref>\n|date=December 2011}}\n\n==Media==\n{{Main|Media in Campbellton, New Brunswick}}\n\n==Other services==\n\nThe city has an [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police|RCMP]] station on Arran St, which serves as the regional headquarters of ''District 9'' comprising [[Restigouche County, New Brunswick|Restigouche County]] and the Western part of [[Gloucester County, New Brunswick|Gloucester County]].\n\nThe Campbellton Fire Station is located at 33 Roseberry Street. The Department is composed of a Fire Chief, 7 full-time  Firefighters, and 29 paid on call Firefighters.\n\nCampbellton is home to a New Brunswick Provincial Court located in the City Centre downtown on Water St. All judges of this court have jurisdiction throughout the province and the Campbellton court possesses a satellite location in [[Saint-Quentin, New Brunswick|St-Quentin]]. Court of Queen's Bench sittings for the Judicial District of Campbellton are held in this court.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.gnb.ca/cour/04CQB/locations-e.asp |title=gnb.ca: Court of Queen's Bench - Locations |access-date=2011-12-11 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160713181343/http://www.gnb.ca/cour/04CQB/locations-e.asp |archive-date=2016-07-13 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Restigouche Regional Service Commission]], which is located at 68A Water Street,<ref>[http://commission2.ca/public/Contacts.php commission2.ca: Restigouche Regional Service Commission - CONTACTS]</ref> is governed by a board of 12 (largely ex-officio) directors,<ref>[http://commission2.ca/public/Members.php commission2.ca: Members]</ref> and provides the following services to all municipalities and rural Communities within the County:<ref>[http://commission2.ca/public/Services.php commission2.ca: SERVICES]</ref>\n* Local and Regional Planning, such as zoning By-Laws<ref>[http://commission2.ca/public/rplan/test/ByLaws.php commission2.ca: Maps & By-Laws]</ref>\n* Solid Waste Management\n* Regional Policing Collaboration\n* Regional Emergency Measures Planning\n* Regional Sport, Recreational, and Cultural Infrastructure Planning and Cost-Sharing\n* Service arrangements\n* Collaboration on regional issues\n* Services to First Nations Communities\n\nThere are numerous law firms, lawyers and attorneys in the city offering a fair amount of professional services to clients.  There are also two Chartered Professional Accounting offices in the city meeting the needs of the business community.\n\n==Notable people==\n{{Main|List of people from Campbellton, New Brunswick}}\n*[[Ren\u00e9 L\u00e9vesque]], the founder of the [[Parti Qu\u00e9b\u00e9cois]] political party and the 23rd [[Premier of Quebec]].\n*[[Brenda Best]], an award-winning singer/songwriter.\n*[[Patsy Gallant]], popular singer and musical theatre actress.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Canada}}\n*[[List of communities in New Brunswick]]\n*[[Listuguj Mi'gmaq First Nation]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"cp2011\">[http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2011/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=1314014&Geo2=CD&Code2=1314&Data=Count&SearchText=campbel&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&Custom=&TABID=1 2011 Statistics Canada Census Profile: Campbellton, New Brunswick]</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commonscat|Campbellton}}\n*{{official|http://www.campbellton.org/}}\n\n{{Geographic Location (8-way)\n | Centre =    Campbellton\n | North =     ''[[Restigouche River]]''<br />{{flagicon|QC}} [[Pointe-\u00e0-la-Croix, Quebec]]\n | Northeast = \n | East =      [[McLeods, New Brunswick|McLeods]]\n | Southeast = [[Lac-des-Lys, New Brunswick|Lac-des-Lys]]\n | South =     [[Val-d'Amour, New Brunswick|Val-d'Amour]]\n | Southwest = \n | West =      [[Atholville, New Brunswick|Atholville]]\n | Northwest = ''[[Restigouche River]]''<br />{{flagicon|QC}} [[Listuguj Mi'gmaq First Nation|Listuguj Mi'gmaq First Nation (Quebec)]]\n}}\n\n{{coord|48|00|18|N|66|40|23|W|name=Campbellton, New Brunswick|display=title|region:CA-NB_type:city(7384)_scale:100000}}\n\n{{Subdivisions of New Brunswick|towns=yes|villages=yes|counties=yes|state=expanded}}\n\n[[Category:Campbellton, New Brunswick| ]]\n[[Category:Cities in New Brunswick]]\n[[Category:Populated coastal places in Canada]]\n", "name_user": "1980fast", "label": "safe", "comment": "Caption punctuation adjustment, per WP:CAPFRAG", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Campbellton,_New_Brunswick"}
{"title_page": "For-profit higher education in the United States", "text_new": "{{short description|Consists of higher education educational institutions operated by profit-seeking businesses}}\n{{Use American English|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Education in the U.S.}}\n'''For-profit higher education in the United States''' has typically consisted of [[higher education]] [[educational institution]]s operated by [[Profit (economics)|profit]]-seeking [[business]]es.  However, with the blurring of public and private over the last four decades,\n<ref>{{cite book |last1=Mettler |first1=Suzanne |title=Degrees of Inequality: How the Politics of Higher Education Sabotaged the American Dream |date=2014 |publisher=Basic Books |location=New York, NY |isbn=978-0-465-04496-2 |pages=120-122 |edition=1st |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KJzSDQAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=degrees+of+inequality+mettler&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjtxOjXncfoAhWSl3IEHeU7CLMQ6AEwAHoECAAQAg#v=onepage&q=degrees%20of%20inequality%20mettler&f=false |accessdate=1 April 2020 |ref=Google Books}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite book |last1=Roth |first1=Gary |title=The Educated Underclass: Students and the Promise of Social Mobility |date=2019 |publisher=Pluto Press |location=London |isbn=9780745339221 |pages=68\u201369 |edition=1st}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/ccap/2012/01/26/are-state-universities-being-privatized/#5042a3741db5 |title = Are State Universities Being Privatized?}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.edsurge.com/news/2019-05-30-is-there-still-a-meaningful-difference-between-for-profit-and-public-higher-ed |title = Is There Still a Meaningful Difference Between For-Profit and Public Higher Ed? - EdSurge News|date = May 30, 2019}}</ref> for-profit higher education also includes for-profit mechanisms such as [[Financial endowment|endowment]] money managers,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nonprofitquarterly.org/large-university-endowments-and-investment-fees-under-fire/|title=Large University Endowments and Investment Fees Under Fire|date=August 21, 2015|website=Non Profit News &#124; Nonprofit Quarterly}}</ref> for-profit fees for service,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/digital-learning/article/2017/10/25/opms-fee-service-growing-revenue-share-models-dominate|title=OPMs: Fee for service is growing, but revenue-share models dominate &#124; Inside Higher Ed|website=www.insidehighered.com}}</ref> for-profit marketing, enrollment services and lead generation,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2014/09/15/lead-generation-more-information-and-fewer-leads|title=Lead generation with more information and fewer leads|website=www.insidehighered.com}}</ref>\nprivatized campus services,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailycal.org/2019/03/10/uc-santa-cruz-student-parents-protest-shift-to-privatized-child-care-services/|title=UC Santa Cruz student-parents protest shift to privatized child care services|first=Sabina |last=Mahavni |date=March 11, 2019|website=The Daily Californian}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailynebraskan.com/news/colleges-experience-mixed-results-in-health-center-outsourcing/article_652e77b4-091c-11e2-95a6-001a4bcf6878.html|title=Colleges experience mixed results in health center outsourcing|first=Conor|last=Dunn|website=The Daily Nebraskan}}</ref> for-profit [[online program manager]]s (OPMs),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/digital-learning/blogs/technology-and-learning/opms-are-losing-battle-hearts-and-minds|title=OPMs Are Losing the Battle for Hearts and Minds &#124; Inside Higher Ed|website=www.insidehighered.com}}</ref><ref>https://www.insidehighered.com/digital-learning/article/2018/06/04/shakeout-coming-online-program-management-companies,</ref> privatized housing,<ref>https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-06-07/texas-a-m-and-oklahoma-luxury-dorms-stumble-amid-sticker-shock</ref> private student loans, student loan servicers, and [[Human Capital Contract]]s, also known as [[income share agreement]]s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.edsurge.com/news/2018-08-21-income-share-agreement-providers-want-to-woo-higher-ed-but-will-it-work|title=Income-Share Agreement Providers Want to Woo Higher Ed. But Will It Work? - EdSurge News|date=August 21, 2018|website=EdSurge}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.edsurge.com/news/2019-04-05-wall-street-wants-in-on-income-share-agreements | title=Wall Street Wants in on Income-Share Agreements - EdSurge News| date=April 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==For-profit colleges==\n\nFor-profit colleges have frequently offered career-oriented curricula including [[Cooking school|culinary arts]], business and technology (including [[coding bootcamp]]s), and health care. These institutions have a long history in the US, and grew rapidly from 1972 to 2009, until their current enrollment and revenue declines.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2017/12/20/national-enrollments-decline-sixth-straight-year-slower-rate |title = National enrollments decline for sixth straight year, but at slower rate}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://nces.ed.gov/programs/coe/indicator_cha.asp |title = The Condition of Education - Postsecondary Education - Postsecondary Students - Undergraduate Enrollment - Indicator May (2019)}}</ref> Approximately 40 percent of all for-profit college campuses have closed since 2010.<ref name=\"theintercept.com\">{{Cite web | url=https://theintercept.com/2019/04/12/betsy-devos-for-profit-colleges/ |title = Betsy DeVos Quietly Making It Easier for Dying For-Profit Schools to Rip off a Few More Students on the Way Out|date = April 12, 2019}}</ref>\nFor-profit colleges received less government scrutiny by the Republican-controlled Senate after 2014, but were recognized as a problem by the US House Subcommittee on Labor, Health and Human Services, Education and Related Agencies in 2019.<ref name=courthousenews>{{Cite web | url=https://www.courthousenews.com/house-panel-takes-up-oversight-of-for-profit-schools |title = House Panel Takes up Oversight of For-Profit Schools|date = March 12, 2019}}</ref> Significant business failures and closings from 2015 to 2019 include [[Corinthian Colleges]], [[ITT Technical Institute]], [[Education Management Corporation]], and [[Education Corporation of America]].<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://campustechnology.com/articles/2019/03/01/murray-wants-higher-ed-act-reauthorization-to-tackle-affordability.aspx | title=Murray Wants Higher ed Act Reauthorization to Tackle Affordability -}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2019/03/01/senator-patty-murray-says-higher-education-legislation-must-focus-college | title=Senator Patty Murray says higher education legislation must focus on college affordability}}</ref> The [[Dream Center]]'s collapse in 2018-2019 also included schools that had historically been for-profit institutions.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{Cite journal | url=https://www.chronicle.com/article/The-Nightmarish-End-of-the/245855 |title = The Nightmarish End of the Dream Center's Higher-Ed Empire|journal = The Chronicle of Higher Education|date = March 9, 2019}}</ref><ref>https://nonprofitquarterly.org/2015/02/26/blurred-lines-structural-movements-of-universities-between-for-profit-nonprofit-and-other-hybrids/</ref>Since 2015, [[student loan debt]] groups, including the [[Debt Collective]] and I Am Ai, have provided advocacy and support for students and former students of failing schools.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/><ref name=\"theguardian.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/money/2014/sep/17/occupy-activists-student-debt-corinthian-colleges|title=Occupy activists abolish $3.85m in Corinthian Colleges students' loan debt|first=Jana|last=Kasperkevic|date=September 17, 2014|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref>\n\n==Blurring between for-profit and non-profit==\n\nPublic colleges and universities have increasingly relied on for-profit businesses for a number of products and services, including food service. For example, Sodexo and Aramark are two major for-profit food servicers. As for-profit colleges face declining enrollment, there has been a blurring between for-profit and non-profit colleges.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2015/02/23/nonprofit-university-becomes-benefit-corporation-further-blurring-profit-divide|title=Nonprofit university becomes a 'benefit corporation,' further blurring for-profit divide|website=www.insidehighered.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cappsonline.org/higher-ed-for-profit-or-not-the-lines-are-blurring/|title=Higher Ed: For Profit or Not? The Lines Are Blurring \u2026 \u2013 CAPPS}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/digital-learning/article/2019/01/09/purdue-prepares-online-expansion-support-newly-acquired-profit|title=Purdue prepares online expansion with support from newly acquired for-profit &#124; Inside Higher Ed|website=www.insidehighered.com}}</ref> For-profit Online Program Managers (OPMs) include [[2U (company)|2U]], [[Academic Partnerships]], [[Bisk Education(company)|Bisk Education]], [[Noodle Partners]], [[Pearson Education]] (Embanet), and [[Wiley (publisher)]](Education Solutions).\n<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/education/archive/2016/06/for-profit-companies-nonprofit-colleges/485930/|title=How Five Companies Are Gaining Millions in Profit Off Education at Nonprofit Schools|first=Derek|last=Newton|date=June 7, 2016|website=The Atlantic}}</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceC\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/digital-learning/article/2018/06/04/shakeout-coming-online-program-management-companies|title=Is a shakeout coming for online program management companies? &#124; Inside Higher Ed|website=www.insidehighered.com}}</ref> In 2018, there were more than two dozen OPMs.<ref name=\"ReferenceC\"/> Human capital contracts, also known as [[Income Share Agreement]]s (ISAs) may also be seen as for-profit vehicles.<ref>http://www.aei.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/Students-Future-as-Investments.pdf</ref>\n\n==History of for-profit higher education==\n\n===Origins===\nFor-profit colleges in the US have their origins in the Colonial Era.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=B0UGX-10hrcC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Higher+ed.+inc.#v=onepage&q=Higher%20ed.%20inc.&f=false|title=Higher Ed, Inc.|accessdate=June 14, 2015|isbn=9780801874475|last1=Ruch|first1=Richard S.|date=August 11, 2003}}</ref><ref name=\"jhu\">{{cite web|url=https://jhupbooks.press.jhu.edu/content/diploma-mills|publisher=jhupbooks.press.jhu.edu|title=Diploma Mills|accessdate=February 18, 2017}}</ref>According to AJ Angulo, 19th century for-profit colleges offering practical skills expanded across the United States, meeting a demand for practical job training. In the 1830s and 1840s, proprietary business schools in Boston, Brooklyn, and Philadelphia offered penmanship and accounting classes. The expansion continued in the 1850s and 1860s, to Chicago, New Orleans, Memphis, and San Jose. Angulo estimated that there were 2,000 for-profit colleges with more than 240,000 students during the period, if fly-by-night schools were included.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.processhistory.org/angulo-for-profit-colleges/|title=For-Profit Colleges in American History|date=June 20, 2017}}</ref> The [[Bryant & Stratton]] Chain School grew to about 50 schools by 1864.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ohiohistorycentral.org/w/Bryant_%26_Stratton_Chain_of_Business_Schools|title=Bryant & Stratton Chain of Business Schools - Ohio History Central|website=ohiohistorycentral.org}}</ref>The decline of proprietary colleges was aided by the [[Smith-Hughes Act]] of 1917. Also known as the National Vocational Education Act, this legislation funded public vocational education.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.google.com/search?q=isbn:1475826079|title=isbn:1475826079 - Google Search|website=www.google.com}}</ref>\n\n===Growth: (1940s to 2009)===\nIn the 1940s, \"fly-by-night commercial vocational 'schools' sprang up to collect veterans' tuition grants\" due to the newly created [[GI Bill]]'s lax requirements and limited oversight to prevent such abuses.<ref name=\"prospect\">{{cite web|url=http://prospect.org/article/delivering-young-families-resonance-gi-bill|publisher=prospect.org|title=Delivering for Young Families: The Resonance of the GI Bill|accessdate=February 18, 2017}}</ref>For-profit colleges grew significantly from 1972 to 1976, after the [[Higher Education Act of 1965]], part of [[President Lyndon Johnson]]'s \"[[Great Society]]\" of progressive reforms, was amended so that for-profit colleges could receive US government funds, to include [[Pell Grants]] and federal student loans.<ref name=\"digilib.gmu.edu\"/><ref name=\"scholarship.law.duke.edu\">{{cite web|url=http://scholarship.law.duke.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=3355&context=dlj |format=PDF |title=SUBPRIME EDUCATION: FOR-PROFIT COLLEGES AND THE PROBLEM WITH TITLE IV FEDERAL STUDENT AID |publisher=Scholarship.law.duke.edu |accessdate=July 4, 2015}}</ref> From 1974 to 1986, for-profit colleges share of Pell Grants rose from 7 percent to 21 percent, even though for-profit colleges only enrolled 5 percent of all higher education students.<ref name=\"books.google.com\"/> In the 1980s, public higher education was also becoming increasingly privatized. In the late 1980s, Secretary of Education [[William Bennett]] hired an outside firm, Pelavin and Associates, to investigate the problems with for-profit higher education. The investigators found widespread abuses across the industry.<ref name=\"books.google.com\"/>  \n\nFrom 1989 to the mid-1990s, Stephen Blair, a former Department of Education official, led for-profit college industry's lobbying campaign in Washington, DC. Blair gathered funds to combat the Pelavin report. Blair recruited politicians [[Bob Beckel]], Patty Sullivan, and [[Haley Barbour]] to sell their cause to Democrats and Republicans.<ref name=\"books.google.com\"/> In 1992, the Higher Education Act was amended to include the 85\u201315 rule, which limited federal funding to 85 percent of a school's funding. Supporters of the 85\u201315 rule argued that the measure was necessary to stem fraudulent and abusive practices at for-profit colleges, and that it might restore some market incentive to education.<ref name=\"congressionalresearch\">{{cite web|url=http://congressionalresearch.com/RL32182/document.php?study=Institutional+Eligibility+and+the+Higher+Education+Act+Legislative+History+of+the+90%20percent2F10+Rule+and+Its+Current+Status|publisher=congressionalresearch.com|title=Institutional Eligibility and the Higher Education Act: Legislative History of the 90/10 Rule and Its Current Status|accessdate=February 18, 2017}}</ref> At the time, former Career College Association lobbyist Patty Sullivan estimated that 35 or 40 percent of for-profit colleges engaged in fraud.<ref name=\"books.google.com\"/> In 1993, the 85\u201315 rule was shelved after complaints were made to the Department of Education.<ref name=\"edweek\">{{cite web|url=http://www.edweek.org/ew/articles/1993/12/08/14aid.h13.html|title=Planned Higher-Ed. Rules Shelved After Complaints |work=Education Week|accessdate=February 18, 2017}}</ref> In 1994, the US House of Representatives voted to allow a one-year delay in regulations scheduled to halt federal student aid for many trade schools. Tony Calandro, vice president of government affairs for the [[Career College Association]] (CCA), said that enforcement of the 85\u201315 rule would have forced 30 percent of the nation's 4,000 private trade schools to close.<ref name=\"nytimes\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/06/30/us/trade-schools-win-reprieve-on-aid-cutoff.html|title=Trade Schools Win Reprieve on Aid Cutoff |work=New York Times|accessdate=February 18, 2017}}</ref>From the late 1980s to the mid-1990s, Senator [[Sam Nunn]] led for more scrutiny of for-profit colleges. The General Accounting Office also found that 135 for-profit colleges contributed to 54% of all student loan defaults. According to the US Department of Education, the number of for-profit colleges rose from about 200 in 1986 to nearly 1,000 in 2007.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=nVM3tUhQeqUC&pg=PA68&dq=for-profot+colleges+and+universities#v=onepage&q=for-profot%20colleges%20and%20universities&f=false|title=For-Profit Colleges and Universities|accessdate=June 14, 2015|isbn=9781579225285|last1=Hentschke|first1=Guilbert C.|last2=Lechuga|first2=Vicente M.|last3=Tierney|first3=William G.|date=March 12, 2012}}</ref> \n\nFrom 1990 to 2009, for-profit colleges gained significant ground over public colleges, growing to 11.8 percent of all undergraduates.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2010/08/26/enroll|title=3 Million and Counting|work=Inside Higher Ed|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref> For-profit college enrollment grew between 1998 and 2009, after the 1998 reauthorization of the Higher Education Act resulted in more deregulation. Secretary of Education [[Richard W. Riley]] appointed former Career College's Association President Stephen J. Blair as the Liaison for Proprietary Institutions.<ref name=\"ed2\">{{cite web|url=https://ifap.ed.gov/eannouncements/doc0984_bodyoftext.htm|publisher=ifap.ed.gov|title=eannouncements/doc0984_bodyoftext|accessdate=February 18, 2017}}</ref> The industry also grew in the wake of state budget cuts, stagnation, and austerity in higher education funding that grew more visible in the 1980s and 1990s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news.cornell.edu/stories/2014/04/suzanne-mettler-sees-higher-ed-caste-system|title=Suzanne Mettler sees higher ed 'caste system' |work=Cornell Chronicle|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref> In the wake of deregulation and the growth of for-profit colleges, [[initial public offerings]] of [[Devry]], [[ITT Educational Services]], [[Apollo Education Group]], [[Corinthian Colleges]], and [[Career Education Corporation]] occurred between 1991 and 1998. For-profit colleges had become \"the darlings of Wall Street.\"<ref name=\"books.google.com\"/> Also the advent of the [[Internet]] in the 1990s has helped increase enrollment as many of the for-profit colleges were pioneers in [[online education]].<ref name=\"books.google.com\"/> In 2005, Department of Education Inspector General John B. Higgins reported that 74% of all institutional fraud investigations were for-profit colleges.<ref name=\"books.google.com\"/> The ''Los Angeles Times'' briefly described the role of Wall Street money in the growth of for-profit colleges.<ref name=\"latimes\">{{cite web|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2003/sep/15/business/fi-corinthian15|work=Los Angeles Times|title=Operating Career College Lucrative Vocation for CEO |accessdate=February 18, 2017|date=September 15, 2003}}</ref> Increased capitalization of for-profit colleges occurred after banks such as [[Goldman Sachs]] and [[Wells Fargo]] and investment firms and hedge funds such as [[Blum Capital Partners]] and [[Warburg Pincus]] became large institutional investors in this industry.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/10/14/goldman-sachs-for-profit-college_n_997409.html|title=With Goldman's Foray Into Higher Education, A Predatory Pursuit Of Students And Revenues|work=The Huffington Post|accessdate=June 14, 2015|date=October 14, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"huffingtonpost\">{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/davidhalperin/who-owns-the-awful-corint_b_4101323.html|title=Who Owns The Awful Corinthian Colleges? Wells Fargo, Marc Morial, Pension Funds|work=The Huffington Post|accessdate=June 14, 2015|date=October 15, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sandiegoreader.com/weblogs/news-ticker/2012/jul/14/bridgepoint-huge-profits-but-possibly-no-future/#|title=Bridgepoint: Huge Profits, but Possibly No Future|publisher=Sandiegoreader.com|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"educationdive.com\">{{Cite web | url=https://www.educationdive.com/news/private-equitys-role-in-the-rise-and-fall-of-for-profit-colleges/554077/ |title = Private equity's role in the rise \u2014 and fall \u2014 of for-profit colleges}}</ref> Private equity in for-profit education has been associated with higher costs to students and declining outcomes: less spent on education, more [[student loan debt]] and lower student loan repayment rates, lower graduation rates, and lower earnings for graduates.<ref name=\"educationdive.com\"/>\n\n====2009\u20132016====\nIn the 2009\u20132010 academic year, for-profit higher education corporations received $32 billion in [[Title IV]] funding\u2014more than 20% of all federal aid.<ref name=\"scholarship.law.duke.edu\"/> For-profit colleges get approximately 70% of their funds from Title IV programs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://projectonstudentdebt.org/files/pub/90-10_Q_and_A_Oct_2013_Update.pdf |title=Search |publisher=Projectonstudentdebt.org|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref> However, some colleges got more than 80% of their funds from Title IV.<ref name=\"help.senate.gov\"/> In 2010, as America's largest university, [[University of Phoenix]], had an enrollment of 470,000 students and annual revenues approaching $5 billion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://investors.apollo.edu/phoenix.zhtml?c=79624&p=irol-reportsannual|title=Annual Reports &#124; Apollo Education Group}}</ref>\n\n===Decline in enrollment, revenues, and employees (2010\u2013present)===\n\n{| class=\"For-profit enrollment in US higher education (National Center for Education Statistics)\"\n|-\n! Fall/Year !!!!!! Enrollment !!!!Revenues!!!! Employees!!!! \n|-\n| 2010   |||||| 2,430,657||||29,603,059,000|||| 295,476\n|-\n| 2011   |||||| 2,368,440 ||||33,889,758,000|||| 288,882\n|-\n| 2012   |||||| 2,174,457 |||| 32,196111,000 |||| 295,887\n|-\n| 2013   ||||||2,000,883||||29,643,714,000 |||| 258,098\n|-\n| 2014   ||||||1,883,199 ||||27,310,167,000 |||| 241,134\n|-\n| 2015   ||||||1,629,393||||24,007,022,000 |||| 214,656\n|-\n| 2016   ||||||1,437,452||||20,804,128,000|||| 191,083\n|-\n| 2017   ||||||1,345,633||||19,446,382,000|||| 176,441\n|}\n\nUnder the Obama administration (2009\u20132017), for-profit colleges received greater scrutiny and negative attention from the US government. State Attorneys General, the media, and scholars also investigated these schools.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Armour|first1=Stephanie|last2=Zibel|first2=Alan|title=For-Profit College Probe Expands|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052702303819704579318872286744010|accessdate=January 15, 2015|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|date=January 13, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"theatlantic.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/education/archive/2014/04/how-higher-ed-contributes-to-inequality/360407/|title=How Higher Ed Contributes to Inequality|work=The Atlantic|accessdate=June 14, 2015|date=April 9, 2014}}</ref> For-profit school enrollment reached its peak in 2009 and showed major declines by 2011.<ref name=\"ed3\">{{cite web|url=http://nces.ed.gov/programs/coe/indicator_cha.asp|publisher=nces.ed.gov|title=The Condition of Education - Participation in Education - Postsecondary - Undergraduate Enrollment - Indicator May (2016)|accessdate=February 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Fain|first1=Paul|title=More Selective For-Profits|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2011/11/11/enrollments-tumble-profit-colleges|work=[[Inside Higher Ed]]|accessdate=January 15, 2015|date=November 11, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2014/05/15/new-data-show-slowing-national-enrollment-decline|title=New data show slowing national enrollment decline |work=Inside Higher Ed|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.educationdive.com/news/how-might-these-6-for-profit-institutions-fare-in-2015/346788/|title=How might these 6 for-profit institutions fare in 2015?|date=December 31, 2014|work=Education Dive|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref> Two companies, [[Corinthian Colleges]] (which included [[Heald College]], [[Everest College]], and [[Wyotech]]) and [[Education Management Corporation]] (which included the [[Art Institutes]], [[Argosy University]], and [[South University]]) faced enrollment declines and major financial trouble in 2014 and 2015;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/ed/2014/12/24/370979991/an-update-on-for-profit-colleges|title=An Update On For-Profit Colleges|date=December 24, 2014|publisher=NPR|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref> Corinthian Colleges and Education Management are out of business (closed). [[University of Phoenix]], a subsidiary of [[Apollo Global Management]], has also seen a 70% drop in enrollment since its peak.{{citation needed|date=October 2019}}\n\nAccording to the 2012 Harkin Report and ''[[The New York Times]]'', students at for-profit colleges made up \"13 percent of the nation's college enrollment, but account for about 47 percent of the defaults on loans. About 96 percent of students at for-profit schools take out loans, compared with about 13 percent at community colleges and 48 percent at four-year public universities.\"<ref name=\"nytimes2\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/07/30/education/harkin-report-condemns-for-profit-colleges.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0 |title=Harkin Report Condemns For-Profit Colleges |access-date=February 18, 2017 |newspaper=The New York Times |date=July 29, 2012 |last1=Lewin |first1=Tamar}}</ref><ref name=\"help.senate.gov\">{{cite web|url=http://www.help.senate.gov/imo/media/for_profit_report/PartI-PartIII-SelectedAppendixes.pdf |title=For Profit Higher Education: The Failure to Safeguard the Federal Investment and Ensure Student Success |publisher=Help.senate.gov |accessdate=July 4, 2015}}</ref> [[Gary Trudeau]] satirized for-profit education in his comic strip ''[[Doonesbury]]'', by showing corruption at a fictionalized school, [[Walden College]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.insidehighered.com/blogs/technology-and-learning/doonesbury-profit-higher-ed |title=Doonesbury on For-Profit Higher ed |work=Inside Higher Ed}}</ref>\n\nA 2014 report by The Institute for College Access and Success showed that the likelihood of a student defaulting was three times more likely at a for-profit college than a 4-year public or non-profit college and almost four times more likely than a community college.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://ticas.org/content/pub/despite-lower-rates-more-650000-defaulted-federal-student-loans-0 |title=Despite Lower Rates, More Than 650,000 Defaulted on Federal Student Loans &#124; The Institute For College Access and Success |publisher=Ticas.org |date=September 24, 2014 |accessdate=July 4, 2015}}</ref> The [[United States Department of Veterans Affairs|Department of Veterans Affairs]] reported that veterans using the [[GI Bill]] for education submitted more complaints about for-profit colleges, particularly [[University of Phoenix]], [[ITT Technical Institute]], [[Devry University]], and [[Colorado Technical University]], than their public or private non-profit counterparts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.benefits.va.gov/GIBILL/docs/Overview_GI+Bill_Feedback+System_CY14.pdf|title=404 - Page Not Found - Veterans Benefits Administration|website=www.benefits.va.gov}}</ref> In September 2014, on his TV show ''Last Week Tonight'', [[John Oliver]] discussed [[student debt]] and for-profit colleges, calling them \"a first-class education in the depths of human depravity.\"<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/09/08/john-oliver-student-debt_n_5784266.html | title=John Oliver on For-Profit Schools: 'A First-Class Education in the Depths of Human Depravity'| date=September 8, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, [[Corinthian Colleges]] filed for bankruptcy and all of its [[Heald College]] campuses were closed.<ref name=\"latimes2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-corinthian-shutdown-20150427-story.html|work=Los Angeles Times|title=Corinthian closing its last schools; 10,000 California students displaced |accessdate=February 18, 2017|date=April 27, 2015}}</ref> In 2016, all [[Westwood College]] campuses were closed.<ref name=\"insidehighered.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/quicktakes/2016/01/29/profit-westwood-college-announces-closing|work=Inside Higher Ed|title=For-Profit Westwood College Announces Closing|accessdate=February 18, 2017}}</ref> [[Le Cordon Bleu]] was also in the process of closing all of its campuses.<ref name=\"insidehighered2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/quicktakes/2015/12/17/career-ed-closing-down-le-cordon-bleu-operations|work=Inside Higher Ed|title=Career Ed Closing Down Le Cordon Bleu Operations|accessdate=February 18, 2017}}</ref> [[ITT Technical Institute]]<ref name=\"insidehighered3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/quicktakes/2015/10/19/itt-tech-suspends-enrollment-several-campuses|work=Inside Higher Ed|title=ITT Tech Suspends Enrollment at Several Campuses|accessdate=February 18, 2017}}</ref> and [[Devry]]<ref name=\"chicagotribune\">{{cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/business/ct-devry-closings-0425-biz-20150424-story.html|title=DeVry to close some out-of-state campuses |work=Chicago Tribune|accessdate=February 18, 2017}}</ref> also closed multiple campuses. In November 2015, the CBS drama [[The Good Wife]], addressed students at Colosseum University, a fictionalized for-profit college that used deceptive recruiting tactics. The episode included mention of accreditation and the 90\u201310 rule.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2015/11/03/good-wife-tackles-profit-colleges-and-student-debt |title='The Good Wife' tackles for-profit colleges and student debt|work=Inside Higher Ed}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' reported that more than 180 for-profit college campuses had closed between 2014 and 2016.<ref name=\"wsj\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/obama-empties-innovative-classrooms-1466635226|work=The Wall Street Journal|author=Finley, Alyssa|title=Obama Empties Innovative Classrooms|date=June 22, 2016|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20160625094259/http://www.wsj.com/articles/obama-empties-innovative-classrooms-1466635226|archivedate=June 25, 2016|accessdate=February 18, 2017}}</ref> For-profit college enrollment dropped about 15% in 2016, a 165,000 decline.<ref name=\"hechingerreport2\">{{cite web|url=http://hechingerreport.org/college-university-enrollment-fifth-straight-year/|title=College and university enrollment is down for fifth straight year |work=The Hechinger Report|accessdate=February 18, 2017|date=December 19, 2016}}</ref> Enrollment at University of Phoenix chain fell 22%, which was a 70% loss since 2010. [[DeVry University]] reported a 23% decline in 2016. Hondros College, a nursing school chain, dropped 14%.<ref name=\"chicagotribune2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/business/ct-for-profit-colleges-enrollment-slide-20160922-story.html|title=Amid scrutiny, for-profit colleges see enrollment slide |work=Chicago Tribune|accessdate=February 18, 2017}}</ref> In June 2016, Education Management announced that it was planning to close all 25 [[Brown Mackie College]] campuses. In September 2016, [[ITT Technical Institute]] closed all of its campuses. In September 2016, the [[US Department of Education]] stripped [[ACICS]] of its accreditation powers. Research by [[United States Department of the Treasury|Treasury Department]] economist Nicholas Turner and [[George Washington University]] economist Stephanie Riegg Cellini found that students who attended for-profit colleges would have been better off not going to college at all, or attending a [[community college]] (which are non-profit); put differently, the for-profit colleges left students worse off than they were when they started. The [[National Bureau of Economic Research]] paper was based on an analysis of 567,000 students who attended for-profit colleges from 2006 to 2008. More than 80% carried [[student loan debt]].<ref name=\"washingtonpost\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/wonk/wp/2016/05/31/a-popular-college-investment-promised-students-a-career-but-didnt-pay-off/|title=A popular college investment promised students a career, but didn't pay off |work=The Washington Post|accessdate=February 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====2017\u20132019====\nIn 2017, the advocacy group the [[Debt Collective]] created its own, unofficial \"Defense to Repayment App\" that allows former students of schools accused of fraud to pursue debt cancellation.<ref name=\"herokuapp\">{{cite web|url=https://debt-is.herokuapp.com/defense-to-repayment|publisher=debt-is.herokuapp.com|title=The Debt Collective|accessdate=February 18, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131074022/http://debt-is.herokuapp.com/defense-to-repayment|archive-date=January 31, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> The applications generated through the Debt Collective's online form were cited by the Department of Education in a Federal Register notice, which said that \"a need for a clearer process for potential claimants\" arose due to the submission of over 1000 defense to repayment claims by \"a building debt activism movement\".<ref name=\"ed\">{{cite web|url=https://studentaid.ed.gov/sa/repay-loans/forgiveness-cancellation#closed-school|publisher=studentaid.ed.gov|title=Forgiveness, Cancellation, and Discharge &#124; Federal Student Aid|accessdate=February 18, 2017}}</ref> In October 2017, [[Strayer University]] and [[Capella University]] agreed to merge as Strategic Education,<ref name=\"insidehighered.com1\"/> officially completing the merger in August 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.startribune.com/capella-and-strayer-complete-1-2-billion-merger-take-new-name-as-strategic-education/489752481/|title=Capella and Strayer complete merger, shares soar nearly 12 percent on strong Q2 results|website=Star Tribune}}</ref> Since 2017, the [[Donald Trump administration]] and Secretary of Education [[Betsy DeVos]] have accused the government of regulatory overreach and have loosened regulations.<ref name=\"consumerist.com\">{{cite web|url=https://consumerist.com/2017/08/17/education-secretary-betsy-devos-will-allow-for-profit-schools-to-continue-offering-programs-that-dont-meet-standards/|title=Education Secretary Betsy DeVos Will Allow For-Profit Schools To Continue Offering Programs That Don't Meet Standards|date=August 17, 2017|website=Consumerist.com|access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref> Donald Trump once opened a for profit college, the [[Trump University]]. It came under investigation for criminal activity, faced multiple lawsuits, and failed within five years.\n\nIn 2017 and 2018, all [[Le Cordon Bleu]] schools were in the process of closing.<ref name=\"sec2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1046568/000156459016027351/ceco-10q_20160930.htm|publisher=sec.gov|title=ceco-10q_20160930.htm|accessdate=February 18, 2017}}</ref> At least 19 Art Institutes were also expected to close.<ref name=\"wtae\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wtae.com/article/many-art-institute-employees-laid-off-in-pittsburgh/7479864|publisher=wtae.com|title=Many Art Institute employees laid off in Pittsburgh|date=May 5, 2016|accessdate=February 18, 2017}}</ref> Education Management Corporation sold its remaining schools to the non-profit Dream Foundation and [[Purdue University]] proposed purchasing Kaplan University.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/mollyhensleyclancy/for-1-purdue-university-will-acquire-a-massive-for-profit|title=Here's Why Purdue University Is Buying A Massive For-Profit College For $1|website=Buzzfeed|access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref> Atalem sold its declining DeVry University and the Keller School of Management to Cogswell Education, a division of Palm Ventures.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/mollyhensleyclancy/devry-university-will-be-sold-to-a-tiny-college-company|title=Troubled DeVry University Gets Sold Off For A Pittance|first=Molly|last=Hensley-Clancy|website=BuzzFeed|access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref> In 2018, the [[National Center for Education Statistics]] reported that the 12-year [[student loan default]] rate for-profit colleges was 52 percent.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/business/ct-biz-for-profit-college-loan-default0-20171005-story.html|title=More than half of students at for-profit colleges defaulted on loans, study finds|first=Maria|last=Danilova|website=ChicagoTribune.com|access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref> The 12-year student loan default rate for [[African Americans]] going to for-profit colleges was reported to be 65.7 percent.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-10-11/black-americans-twice-as-likely-as-whites-to-default-on-student-debt|title=Black Americans Twice as Likely as Whites to Default on Student Debt|date=October 11, 2017|access-date=January 1, 2018|publisher=Bloomberg}}</ref> In 2018, the documentary Fail State chronicled the boom and bust of for-profit colleges, highlighting the abuses that led to their downfall.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.texasobserver.org/fail-state-delves-shadowy-world-profit-colleges/|title='Fail State' Delves into the Shadowy World of For-Profit Colleges|author=|date=October 27, 2017|website=Texas Observer}}</ref> In June 2018, Inside Higher Education published \"A Tipping Point for OPM?\" which stated that most experts thought a \"shakeout\" would be occurring among Online Program Managers.<ref name=\"ReferenceC\"/> On August 10, 2018, US Education Secretary Betsy Devos scrapped a rule issued by the US Department of Education in 2010 which would have forced for-profit colleges to prove that the students they enroll are able to attain \"gainful employment.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/grade-point/wp/2018/08/10/trumps-education-department-moves-to-rescind-rule-aimed-at-for-profit-schools/|title=Trump's Education Department moves to rescind rule aimed at for-profit schools|website=Washington Post}}</ref><ref name=july2019>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/10/us/politics/betsy-devos-for-profit-colleges.html|title=DeVos Ends Obama-Era Safeguards Aimed at Abuses by For-Profit Colleges|first=Erica L.|last=Green|date=August 10, 2018|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/08/10/politics/devos-obama-for-profit-college-rule/index.html|title=Betsy DeVos' rollback of Obama's for-profit college rules is almost complete|first=Katie|last=Lobosco|website=CNN}}</ref> The gainful employment policy will expire on July 1, 2019.<ref name=july2019 /><ref>https://www.10news.com/newsy/betsy-devos-wants-to-end-rules-meant-to-curb-abuse-by-some-colleges</ref> In the 30-day period before its expiration, however, the Department of Education will gather public input.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/nation/devos-proposes-rollback-of-for-profit-college-rule|title=DeVos proposes rollback of for-profit college rule|date=August 10, 2018|website=PBS NewsHour}}</ref> In September 2018, [[Education Corporation of America]] announced that they would be closing 26 campuses, which included several [[Virginia College]] campuses.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2018/09/12/profit-chain-will-close-dozens-campuses|title=For-profit chain will close dozens of campuses|website=www.insidehighered.com}}</ref> The school closed all of its schools by the end of the year.<ref name=\"usatoday.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/education/2019/03/26/how-to-choose-a-college-argosy-university-college-closing/3211480002/|title=A college closed, leaving thousands without a degree. How to keep it from happening to you|first=Chris|last=Quintana|website=USA TODAY}}</ref> In November 2018, the US Department of Education restored [[Accrediting Council for Independent Colleges and Schools]] (ACICS) as a higher education accreditor. The organization had lost its authority during the Obama administration.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2018/11/26/devos-restores-authority-profit-accreditor|title=DeVos restores authority of for-profit accreditor|website=www.insidehighered.com}}</ref>\n\nFrom December 2018 to March 2019, [[Dream Center]] Education Holdings began closing and selling off schools. DCEH was the parent company of the [[Art Institutes]], [[Argosy University]], and [[South University]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/07/business/argosy-college-art-insititutes-south-university.html|title=A College Chain Crumbles, and Millions in Student Loan Cash Disappears|first1=Stacy|last1=Cowley|first2=Erica L.|last2=Green|date=March 7, 2019|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> The [[National Student Clearinghouse]] reported that their for-profit college enrollment numbers for Fall 2018 had declined 15.1 percent from Fall 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.studentclearinghouse.org/nscblog/fall-2018-overall-postsecondary-enrollments-decreased-1-7-percent-from-last-fall/|title=Fall 2018 Overall Postsecondary Enrollments Decreased 1.7 Percent from Last Fall|first=N. S. C.|last=Blog|date=December 13, 2018}}</ref> In 2019, Argosy University closed all of its campuses. ''[[USA Today]]'' articles in March 2019 portrayed the collapse of the school as part of a trend, highlighting the losses of other for-profit colleges: [[Brown Mackie College]] (2017), [[Le Cordon Bleu]] (2017), [[Brightwood College]] (2018), [[Vatterott College]] (2018), and [[Virginia College]] (2018).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/education/2019/03/26/for-profit-college-closing-argosy-university/3271813002/|title=Trouble at for-profit colleges in 5 graphs: Here's what's happening|first=Lindsay|last=Huth|website=USA TODAY}}</ref><ref name=\"usatoday.com\" /> In a 2019 Brookings Institution report, students taking online courses at for-profit colleges were attracted to the programs for their ease of enrollment and help obtaining financial aid, but \"disappointed with the poor quality of education.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.educationdive.com/news/for-profit-online-students-drawn-by-convenience-but-left-disappointed/551721/|title=For-profit online students drawn by convenience but left 'disappointed'|website=Education Dive}}</ref><ref>https://www.brookings.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/The-Failings-of-Online-For-profit-Colleges.pdf</ref> On March 16, 2019, [[National American University]] announced that ground campuses would be closed, except for Ellsworth Air Force Base and King's Bay Naval Submarine Base.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rapidcityjournal.com/news/local/nau-closing-rapid-city-other-campuses/article_617c7935-3b52-51b9-bbb1-b2a5a9b76874.html|title=NAU closing Rapid City, other campuses|first=Arielle Zionts Journal|last=staff|website=Rapid City Journal Media Group}}</ref> In April 2019, [[2U (company)|2U]] purchased Trilogy, a [[coding bootcamp]] provider, for $750 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2019/04/09/2u-buy-boot-camp-provider-trilogy-750-million|title=2U to buy boot-camp provider Trilogy for $750 million|website=www.insidehighered.com}}</ref> On April 12, 2019, Betsy DeVos was criticized for allowing five failing for-profit colleges to avoid posting a letter of credit.<ref name=\"theintercept.com\" /> On April 14, 2019, NBC News Investigates reported on for-profit colleges that target veterans. The online version mentioned [[Full Sail University]], [[Ashford University]], [[Colorado Technical University]], and [[University of Phoenix]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/politics-news/veterans-could-be-first-pay-devos-rolls-back-profit-college-n985891|title=Veterans could be first to pay as DeVos rolls back for-profit college oversight|website=NBC News}}</ref> In 2019, Accreditor WASC approved Ashford University's conversion to a non-profit. Its parent company, Zovio, however, continued to be a publicly traded for-profit college company.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Busta |first1=Hallie |title=Accreditor approves Ashford U's nonprofit conversion |url=https://www.educationdive.com/news/accreditor-approves-ashford-us-nonprofit-conversion/558781/ |website=Education Dive |accessdate=July 16, 2019}}</ref> In July 2019, 2U shares dropped more than 50 percent when it lowered its growth expectations.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Millward |first1=Wade Tyler |title=2U Stock Tumbles 54% After Company Lowers Growth Expectations for 2019 |url=https://www.edsurge.com/news/2019-07-31-2u-stock-tumbles-after-online-degree-company-lowers-growth-expectations-for-2019 |website=edsurge.com |accessdate=August 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==List of for-profit corporations and their brands==\n{{See also|List of for-profit universities and colleges}}\n\nAccording to the [[National Center for Education Statistics]], there were approximately 3,200 for-profit institutions in the US in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nces.ed.gov/pubs2016/2016112.pdf |title=Postsecondary Institutions and Cost of Attendance in 2015-16; Degrees and Other Awards Conferred, 2014\u201315; and 12-Month Enrollment, 2014\u201315 |author1=Scott A. Ginder |author2=Janice E. Kelly-Reid |author3=Farrah B. Man |date=July 2016 |access-date= February 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\nMany for-profit institutions are subsidiaries of larger companies. The following is a list of for-profit companies in the higher education sector:\n* [[Adtalem Global Education]] (owner of Chamberlain Nursing, Ross University Medical School, Ross University School of Veterinary Medicine) \n* [[Ancora Education]] (owner of Arizona Automotive Institute, Berks Technical Institute, Edge Tech Academy, International Schools, McCann School of Business & Technology, [[Miller-Motte Technical College]], [[Platt College (Oklahoma)|Platt College]], and South Texas Vocational Technical Institute)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ancoraeducation.com/our-brands|title=Our Brands :: Ancora Education|website=www.ancoraeducation.com}}</ref>\n* [[Apollo Education Group]] (a subsidiary of [[Apollo Global Management]] and parent company of [[University of Phoenix]])\n* [[American Public Education]] (owner of [[American Public University]] and [[American Military University]])\n* [[Career Education Corporation]] (includes [[Colorado Technical University]] and [[American Intercontinental University]])\n* [[Center for Excellence in Higher Education]] (includes [[CollegeAmerica]], [[Stevens-Henager College]], [[California College San Diego]], and [[Independence University]])\n* [[Connections Academy]] (a subsidiary of [[Pearson Education]])\n* [[Education Affiliates]] (includes [[Fortis College]] and Fortis Institutes)\n* [[Global University Systems]]\n* [[Graham Holdings]] (subsidiary Kaplan Higher Education is the servicer of [[Purdue University Global]])\n* [[International Education Corporation]] owns [[UEI College]], [[United Education Institute]], [[Florida Career College]] and [[US Colleges]].\n* [[JLL Partners]] (owner of [[Education Affiliates]] and [[Ross Medical Education Center]]) \n* [[K12 (company)|K12]]\n* [[Laureate Education]] (owner of [[Walden University]] and OPM for [[University of Miami]])\n* [[Lincoln Group of Schools]]\n* [[Linden Education Group]]\n* [[Nemo Investor Aggregator]] owner of [[Cortiva Institute brand]]\n*Ochsner Health System: Ochsner Clinical School\n* [[Palm Ventures]] (owner of [[DeVry University]])\n* [[Premier Education Group]] (owner of American College for Medical Careers, Branford Hall Career Institute, Harris Casel Institute, [[Harris School of Business]], Salter College, The Salter School, Salter School of Nursing, Seacoast Career Schools)\n* [[Quad Partners]] (owns [[Beckfield College]], [[Blue Cliff College]], [[Pacific College of Oriental Medicine]], [[Swedish Institute]], and [[Trillium College]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.quadpartners.com/portfolio/|title=Portfolio of Our Investments in Education &#124; Private Equity Investors}}</ref>\n* [[Strategic Education]] (merged [[Strayer]] and [[Capella University]])<ref name=\"insidehighered.com1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2017/10/30/strayer-and-capella-two-publicly-traded-profit-providers-merge|title=Strayer and Capella, two publicly traded for-profit providers, to merge|website=InsideHigherEd.com|access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[TA Associates]] (owner of [[Full Sail University]])\n* [[Universal Technical Institute]]\n* [[Zovio]] (Owner of [[Ashford University]] and [[Fullstack Academy]], contract with [[University of San Diego]] for cybersecurity bootcamp)\n\n[[Laureate Education]]<ref name=\"bloomberg\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2014-01-06/clinton-pitches-kkr-backed-college-chain-amid-controversy|title=Clinton Pitches KKR-Backed College Chain Amid Controversy|author=Mina Kimes|date=February 4, 2014|work=Bloomberg.com|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref> and [[Apollo Education Group]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.apollo.edu/about/our-history|title=Our History - Apollo Education Group|publisher=Apollo.edu|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref> have become powerful international education corporations. Apollo Education Group is now part of Apollo Global Management. Laureate, the largest US-based for-profit higher educator, was once reported to have more than one million students worldwide, in North America, Latin America, Europe, the Middle East, Africa, and Asia Pacific.<ref name=\"sec\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/912766/000104746916013340/a2227130zs-1a.htm|publisher=sec.gov|title=Archives/edgar/data/912766/000104746916013340/a2227130zs-1a|accessdate=February 18, 2017}}</ref> Former President of the United States [[Bill Clinton]] was an honorary Chancellor of the for-profit enterprise.\n\n==For-profit marketing, enrollment and lead generators==\nFor-profit colleges use lead generation companies to target potential students and to take their personal information.<ref>https://www.ftc.gov/system/files/documents/public_comments/2015/10/00016-98214.pdf</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/military-branded-websites_b_9131742|title=Military-Branded Websites Push Veterans to Troubled For-Profit Colleges|date=February 1, 2016|website=HuffPost}}</ref> However, as competition has heated up in US higher education, traditional schools have also employed them.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/views/2016/04/18/too-much-being-spent-higher-education-marketing-assault-essay|title=Too much is being spent on a higher education marketing assault (essay) &#124; Inside Higher Ed|website=www.insidehighered.com}}</ref> Lead generators use multiple strategies to find and enroll students. There are hundreds of sites on the internet that gather information for schools.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.noodle.com/articles/list-of-lead-generation-sites|title=Noodle|website=www.noodle.com}}</ref> Two of the most notable lead generators are QuinStreet and Education Dynamics.\n\n==For-profit online program managers (OPMs)==\n[[Online program manager]]s (OPMs) play a significant role in online education.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.montanakaimin.com/news/over-half-of-online-tuition-could-go-to-private-company/article_5c75ac14-5b0e-11e9-a1c9-9747a7a1d138.html|title=Over half of online tuition could go to private company|first=Cameron Kia Weix / Montana|last=Kaimin|website=Montana Kaimin}}</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceC\"/> However,the industry is feeling a great deal of economic pressure.<ref>{{cite web |last1=McKenzie |first1=Lindsay |title=A Reckoning for 2U, and OPMs? |url=http://www.insidehighered.com/digital-learning/article/2019/08/01/bad-day-2u-highlights-vulnerability-online-program-management |website=insidehighered.com |accessdate=August 3, 2019}}</ref> The largest OPM's are: 2U, Academic Partnerships, Bisk Education, Pearson Learning and Wiley Education Solutions. <ref>{{cite web |last1=Schwartz |first1=Natalie |title=Democratic congressional inquiry targets OPMs |url=https://www.educationdive.com/news/congressional-inquiry-targets-online-program-managers/571275/ |website=www.educationdive.com |accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===List of for-profit online program managers and the schools they service===\n* [[2U (company)|2U]] (services programs at [[American University]], [[Baylor University]], [[George Washington University]], [[Harvard University]], [[Pepperdine University]], [[Rice University]], [[Syracuse University]], [[University of California, Berkeley]], [[University of North Carolina]], [[University of Southern California]], and [[Washington University]].<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://2u.com/partners/ | title=Our Partners &#124; 2U}}</ref>\n* [[Academic Partnerships]] (servicer of [[University of Texas at Arlington]] and [[Florida International University]])\n* [[Bisk Education(company)|Bisk]] ([[University Alliance (US)]] is a division of Bisk, servicing [[Villanova University]], [[University of Notre Dame]]\u2019s Mendoza College of Business, [[Michigan State University]], [[Florida Institute of Technology]], [[Jacksonville University]], [[University of South Florida]], and [[New England College]]. \n* [[Cintas]] serves [[Arizona State University]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Wilen |first1=Holden |title=Former Laureate CEO Doug Becker launches another education startup |url=https://www.bizjournals.com/baltimore/news/2019/08/27/former-laureate-ceo-doug-becker-launches-another.html?ana=yahoo&yptr=yahoo |website=bizjournals.com |accessdate=September 12, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Collegis Education]]\n* [[Grand Canyon Education]] serves [[Grand Canyon University]].\n* [[HotChalk]]\n* [[iDesign]]\n* [[InStride]] (OPM for Arizona State University)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/blogs/digital-tweed/introducing-instride-asu%E2%80%99s-profit-preferred-provider-strategy-growing-online|title=Introducing InStride, ASU's For-Profit, Preferred Provider Strategy for Growing Online Enrollments &#124; Inside Higher Ed|website=www.insidehighered.com}}</ref>\n* [[Kaplan Higher Education]] (servicer of [[Purdue University Global]] and the [[Purdue University]] system)\n* [[Laureate Education]] serves University of Miami graduate programs.\n* [[Noodle Partners]] servicing University of Michigan (Ross and Nursing), Harvard (Kennedy School), University of Pittsburgh (Health Informatics and Physical Therapy), Boston College, Tulane, University of Virginia, Southern Methodist University, New York University, Virginia Commonwealth University, and University of Tennessee.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kim |first1=Joshua |title=Getting My Head Around Noodle Partners |url=http://www.insidehighered.com/blogs/technology-and-learning/getting-my-head-around-noodle-partners |website=Inside Higher Education |accessdate=November 11, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Pearson Education]] (Embanet) partner schools include [[University of Southern California]], [[Vanderbilt University]] School of Nursing, [[Wake Forest University]], [[Brandeis University]], [[Wake Forest University]], [[Case Western Reserve]], [[George Washington University]], [[Boston University]], [[Pepperdine University]], [[University of Florida]], [[Northeastern University]], [[Howard University]], [[Washington State University]], [[University of San Francisco]], [[Ohio University]], [[University of Arizona]], [[New Jersey Institute of Technology]], [[University of Alabama, Birmingham]], [[University of Cincinnati]], [[University of Illinois, Chicago]], [[Marysville University]], [[Kent State University]], and [[Portland State University]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Our Partners |website=http://ec.cratco.com/our-partners/our-academic-partners |publisher=Pearson |accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Wiley (publisher)]](Education Solutions) servicing Northern Illinois University,<ref>https://seekingalpha.com/article/4269667-john-wiley-and-sons-inc-jw-ceo-brian-napack-q4-2019-results-earnings-call-transcript?part=single</ref> Michigan State University<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://seekingalpha.com/news/3444852-wiley-in-deal-michigan-state-for-online-programs|title=Wiley in deal with Michigan State for online programs|first=Jason|last=Aycock|date=March 21, 2019|website=Seeking Alpha}}</ref>\n\n==Coding bootcamps==\nIn 2019, [[coding bootcamp]]s remain popular. However, there may already be an oversupply of graduates and some coding bootcamps have already closed.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/24/technology/coding-boot-camps-close.html |title = As Coding Boot Camps Close, the Field Faces a Reality Check|newspaper = The New York Times|date = August 24, 2017|last1 = Lohr|first1 = Steve}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"cnbc.com\">{{Cite web | url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/04/08/suzy-welch-the-only-2-reasons-you-should-learn-to-code.html |title = Suzy Welch: The only 2 reasons you should drop everything and learn to code|date = April 9, 2019}}</ref>\n<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://techcrunch.com/2018/10/04/as-some-pricey-coding-camps-fade-away-codecademy-barrels-ahead-with-affordable-paid-offerings-and-a-new-mobile-app/ |title = As some pricey coding camps fade away, Codecademy barrels ahead with affordable paid offerings and a new mobile app}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=http://hackeducation.com/2017/07/22/bootcamp-bust |title = Why Are Coding Bootcamps Going Out of Business?|date = July 22, 2017}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"cnbc.com\"/>\n\n==Student loan servicers==\nFor-profit student loan servicers have included [[Sallie Mae]], [[Navient]], and [[Nelnet]].\n\n==Politics and political lobbying==\nPolitics and lobbying play a significant part in the history of US for-profit school growth.<ref name=\"republicreport\">{{cite web|url=https://www.republicreport.org/2016/friends-in-high-places-who-endorses-americas-troubled-for-profit-colleges/|publisher=republicreport.org|title=Friends In High Places: Who Endorses America's Troubled For-Profit Colleges? &#8211; Republic Report|accessdate=February 18, 2017|date=June 21, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"books.google.com\">{{cite book|title=Diploma Mills: How For-Profit Colleges Stiffed Students, Taxpayers, and the American Dream|author=Angulo, A.J.|date=2016|publisher=Johns Hopkins University Press|isbn=9781421420073|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Q8qnCwAAQBAJ&pg=PR4|accessdate=February 18, 2017}}</ref> The for-profit education industry has spent more than $40 million on lobbying from 2007 to 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/08/30/for-profit-colleges-lobbying_n_1842507.html|title=For-Profit Colleges Spending Millions On Lobbying, Nearly $40 Million Since 2007|work=The Huffington Post|accessdate=June 14, 2015|date=August 30, 2012}}</ref> and $36 million since 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.opensecrets.org/industries/lobbying.php?cycle=2014&ind=H5300 |title=For-profit Education: Lobbying, 2014 |publisher=OpenSecrets.org |date= |accessdate=July 2, 2015}}</ref> For-profit education lobbying grew from $83,000 in 1990 to approximately $4.5 million in its peak year of 2012.<ref name=\"opensecrets\">{{cite web|url=https://www.opensecrets.org/industries/totals.php?cycle=2016&ind=H5300|publisher=opensecrets.org|title=For-profit Education: Long-Term Contribution Trends &#124; OpenSecrets|accessdate=February 18, 2017}}</ref>The most significant industry lobby is Career Education Colleges and Universities (CECU), previously known as The [[Association of Private Sector Colleges and Universities]] (ASPCU). Before 2010, the organization was known as the [[Career College Association]].<ref name=\"hechingerreport\">{{cite web|url=http://hechingerreport.org/seeking-fresh-start-battered-profit-colleges-give-new-name/|publisher=hechingerreport.org|title=Seeking a fresh start, battered for-profit colleges give themselves a new name - The Hechinger Report|accessdate=February 18, 2017|date=June 6, 2016}}</ref> The [[Cato Institute]]'s [[Center for Educational Freedom]] also supports for-profit higher education.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/posteverything/wp/2015/01/13/even-for-profit-universities-are-better-than-americas-terrible-community-colleges/|title=Even for-profit universities are better than America's terrible community colleges|author=Neal McCluskey|date=January 13, 2015|work=Washington Post|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"stripes.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.stripes.com/opinion/how-for-profits-beat-community-colleges-1.324621 |accessdate=January 19, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150120151645/http://www.stripes.com/opinion/how-for-profits-beat-community-colleges-1.324621 |archivedate=January 20, 2015|title=How for-profits beat community colleges|website=Stars and Stripes|last=McCluskey|first=Neal|date=January 19, 2015 }}</ref> Political operatives with close ties to for-profit education have included [[Bill Clinton]],<ref name=\"insidehighered\">{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/quicktakes/2015/08/03/laureate-paid-bill-clinton-165-million|publisher=insidehighered.com|title=Laureate Paid Bill Clinton $16.5 Million|accessdate=February 18, 2017}}</ref>\n[[Lanny Davis]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/davidhalperin/which-for-profit-college_b_5040172.html|title=Which For-Profit College Lobbyist Are You?|work=The Huffington Post|accessdate=June 14, 2015|date=March 28, 2014}}</ref> [[Heather Podesta]],<ref name=\"theatlantic.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sunlightfoundation.com/blog/2011/03/10/regulations-lead-to-lobbying-surge-by-the-for-profit-college-industry/|title=Regulations Lead To Lobbying Surge By The For-Profit College Industry|work=Sunlight Foundation|accessdate=June 14, 2015|date=March 10, 2011}}</ref> [[Urban League]] President [[Marc Morial]],<ref name=\"articles.latimes.com\">{{cite web|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2013/may/31/business/la-fi-hiltzik-20130602|publisher=articles.latimes.com|title=Why would Leon Panetta, Marc Morial join for-profit Corinthian? - latimes|accessdate=February 18, 2017|date=May 31, 2013}}</ref> former Ted Kennedy aide [[Jane Oates]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.washingtonmonthly.com/college_guide/blog/jane_oates_sells_out.php|title=Jane Oates Sells Out|work=The Washington Monthly|accessdate=June 14, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150703003452/http://www.washingtonmonthly.com/college_guide/blog/jane_oates_sells_out.php|archive-date=July 3, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> former Defense Secretary [[Leon Panetta]],<ref name=\"articles.latimes.com\"/>\nand [[National Action Network]]'s civil rights activist [[Al Sharpton]].<ref>{{cite news|author= |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/gary-stager/education-nation-ideologi_b_739106.html |title=Education Nation & Ideological Blindness &#124; Gary Stager |publisher=Huffingtonpost.com |date=October 19, 2010 |accessdate=July 2, 2015}}</ref> In 2014, APSCU hired Michael Dakduk, former head of [[Student Veterans of America]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/davidhalperin/michael-dakduk_b_4221020.html|title=Head of Group Charged With Protecting Student Vets Joins For-Profit College Lobby|work=The Huffington Post|accessdate=June 14, 2015|date=November 5, 2013}}</ref> From 2010 to 2015, [[Bill Clinton]] received at least $17.5 million from [[Laureate Education]], the parent company of [[Walden University]].<ref name=\"politico\">{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2016/08/bill-clinton-laureate-for-profit-college-pay-226971|publisher=politico.com|title=Bill Clinton's pay at for-profit education company topped $17.5 million - POLITICO|accessdate=February 18, 2017}}</ref>In March 2017, Secretary of Education [[Betsy DeVos]] appointed Robert Eitel, a former Career Education Corporation and Bridgepoint executive, as a special advisor.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/17/business/education-for-profit-robert-eitel.html|title=Betsy DeVos's Hiring of For-Profit College Official Raises Impartiality Issues|first=Patricia|last=Cohen|date=March 17, 2017|publisher=|access-date=January 1, 2018|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref> In July 2018, DeVos delayed the implementation of a rule intended to help students receive debt forgiveness if they were cheated by their college.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/09/13/politics/betsy-devos-loses-lawsuit/index.html|title=Betsy DeVos loses lawsuit after delaying student loan protection rule|first=Katie|last=Lobosco|website=CNN}}</ref> In September 2018, the [[United States District Court for the District of Columbia|U. S. District Court for the District of Columbia]] ruled against DeVos, finding the delay of implementation to be unlawful.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/court-rules-against-education-secretary-betsy-devos-in-for-profit-college-case/|title=Court rules against Education Secretary Betsy DeVos in for-profit college case|website=www.cbsnews.com}}</ref>\n\n==Student debt groups==\nSeveral student debt groups have been created since 2014, after the [[Debt Collective]] paid off student loans for 3,700 [[Everest College]] students.<ref name=\"theguardian.com\"/> The groups include \"I Am Ai,\" a group that offers support and advocacy for student debtors who attended the Art Institutes.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/>\n\n==Recruiting, advertising, and lead generators==\nThe for-profit college industry has spent billions of dollars on student recruiting, advertising, and buying leads for recruitment.<ref name=\"chronicle.com\">{{cite web|url=http://chronicle.com/blogs/bottomline/u-of-phoenix-reboots-advertising-and-rebrands-in-the-process/|title=U. of Phoenix Reboots Advertising and Rebrands in the Process \u2013 Bottom Line - Blogs - The Chronicle of Higher Education|publisher=Chronicle.com|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/recruitment-profit-colleges-targeted-145346998.html|title=Recruitment by for-profit colleges targeted|date=April 18, 2012|work=Yahoo News|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref> In 2011, for example, [[University of Phoenix]], [[ITT Tech]], [[Devry]], and [[Capella University|Capella]] together spent more than $100,000,000 on Google Ads.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.academia.edu/8504554 |title=4Profits'R'Us |accessdate=January 15, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141117210304/http://www.academia.edu/8504554/4ProfitsRUs |archivedate=November 17, 2014 }}</ref> Several Wall Street-backed schools spend large amounts on advertisements on day time and late night television.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://chronicle.com/article/Calif-Accuses-Corinthian/142267/|title=Calif. Accuses Corinthian Colleges of False Placement Rates, Predatory Ads|journal=The Chronicle of Higher Education|accessdate=June 14, 2015|date=October 11, 2013}}</ref> In 2012, [[Apollo Group]], the parent company of [[University of Phoenix]], reportedly spent $665,000,000 on advertising and marketing.<ref name=\"chronicle.com\"/> The colleges' marketing departments rely heavily on Lead Generators, which are companies that find potential students (\"leads\") and provide their personal information and preferences to for-profit college.{{explain|reason=So what? Explain--in neutral and informative language.|date=October 2015}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nacacnet.org/media-center/Pages/Lead-Generators.aspx|title=Lead Generators: A Checklist for Reporters|publisher=Nacacnet.org|accessdate=June 14, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150121014654/http://www.nacacnet.org/media-center/Pages/Lead-Generators.aspx|archive-date=January 21, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://fortune.com/2014/11/19/business-school-rankings-lead-generation-marketing/|title=What's a goat farmer doing ranking business schools? - Fortune|work=Fortune|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfweekly.com/sanfrancisco/for-profit-colleges-predators-in-the-ivory-tower/Content?oid=2185880|title=For-Profit Colleges: Predators in the Ivory Tower|work=SF Weekly|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Structure of for-profit education==\n\n===Sources of capital and cash flow===\nThe main sources of initial capital for public for-profit colleges are institutional investors: international banks, hedge funds, institutional retirement funds, and state retirement funds.<ref name=\"huffingtonpost\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://nypost.com/2014/07/11/goldman-sachs-kkr-flunk-in-college-investment/|title=Goldman Sachs, KKR flunk in college investment|work=New York Post|accessdate=June 14, 2015|first=Josh|last=Kosman|date=July 12, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=E9KJWnyDk1sC&pg=PA53&lpg=PA53&dq=warburg+pincus+acquires+bridgepoint+education#v=onepage&q=warburg%20pincus%20acquires%20bridgepoint%20education&f=false|title=Corporations Are Not People|accessdate=June 14, 2015|isbn=9781609941079|last1=Clements|first1=Jeffrey D.|date=January 9, 2012}}</ref> [[Wells Fargo]] was a major funder of [[Corinthian Colleges]]<ref name=\"huffingtonpost2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/davidhalperin/who-owns-the-awful-corint_b_4101323.html|publisher=huffingtonpost.com|title=Who Owns The Awful Corinthian Colleges? Wells Fargo, Marc Morial, Pension Funds &#124; The Huffington Post|accessdate=February 18, 2017|date=October 15, 2013}}</ref> and [[Goldman Sachs]] provided a significant amount of capital to [[Education Management Corporation]].<ref name=\"edmc\">{{cite web|url=http://www.edmc.edu/About/History.aspx|publisher=edmc.edu|title=Education Management Corporation - History|accessdate=February 18, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503195751/http://www.edmc.edu/about/History.aspx|archive-date=May 3, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n====Title IV funds====\n\nThe main source of cash flow consists of US Department of Education [[Higher Education Act of 1965|Higher Education Act]] [[Title IV]] funds. Title IV funds include Federal Family Education Loans (FFEL), direct loans, Federal Perkins Loans, Federal [[Pell Grants]], Academic Competitiveness Grants (ACG), National SMART Grants, Federal Supplemental Educational Opportunity Grants (FSEOG), and Federal Work-Study (FWS).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://federalstudentaid.ed.gov/site/front2back/programs/programs/fb_03_01_0030.htm|title=What are Title IV Programs?|publisher=Federalstudentaid.ed.gov|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref> In the 1990s, Congress began requiring that for-profit schools receive at least 10% of their revenues from non-federal student aid sources, which include the GI Bill.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Bair|first1=Sheila|authorlink1=Sheila Bair|title=For-Profit Schools Are a Bad Deal for Both Investors and Taxpayers |journal=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]|date=January 1, 2015|volume=171|issue=1|page=39}}</ref>\n\n====GI Bill funds, Department of Defense Tuition Assistance and MyCAA====\nThe for-profit education industry also receives billions of dollars through VA benefits also known as the [[GI Bill]].<ref name=\"help.senate.gov\" /> In the 2010\u20132011 school year, more than $1 billion went to eight for-profit schools.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://chronicle.com/article/8-For-Profit-Colleges-Collect/129124/|title=8 For-Profit Colleges Collect More Than $1-Billion in Veterans' Education Benefits|journal=The Chronicle of Higher Education|accessdate=June 14, 2015|date=September 22, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|url=http://chronicle.com/article/For-Profit-Colleges-Still-Cash/147977/|title=For-Profit Colleges Still Cash In on Post-9/11 GI Bill, Harkin Report Says|journal=The Chronicle of Higher Education|accessdate=June 14, 2015|date=July 30, 2014}}</ref> In the 2012\u20132013 academic year, 31 percent of GI Bill funds went to for-profit colleges. Veteran participation in these schools, in effect, transferred $1.7 billion in post-9/11 GI Bill funds to these schools.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Zillman|first1=Claire|title=Obama's budget aims to eliminate for-profit colleges' GI Bill loophole|journal=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]|date=February 3, 2015|url=http://fortune.com/2015/02/03/gi-bill-for-profit-colleges-2/|accessdate=February 7, 2015}}</ref> According to a CBS News report in 2017, 40 percent of all GI Bill funds went to for-profit colleges.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/warrior-scholar-project-helps-veterans-transition-to-college-life/ |title = Warrior Scholar Project helps veterans transition from battlefield to classroom}}</ref>For-profit colleges receive money for servicemembers and their spouses attending college while still in the military.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://rebootcamp.militarytimes.com/news/education/2018/03/27/dod-review-0-of-schools-following-ta-rules/ |title = DoD review: 0% of schools following TA rules|date = March 27, 2018}}</ref> In fiscal year 2018, for-profit colleges received $181 million or 38 percent of all DOD TA funds. For-profit schools also receive money from DOD for education of military spouses.  The program is known as MyCAA.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.dodmou.com/ |title = Home}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.militarytimes.com/pay-benefits/2019/04/10/few-military-spouses-are-using-this-4000-benefit/ |title = Few military spouses are using this $4,000 benefit|date = April 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Other sources====\n\nThese corporations also obtain cash flow through student private loans, corporate loans, and the selling of assets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/CPRT-112SPRT74931/pdf/CPRT-112SPRT74931.pdf |title=For Profit Higher Education: The Failure to Safeguard the Federal Investment and Ensure Student Success |publisher=Gpo.gov |accessdate=July 4, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/rundown/new-report-shows-nearly-2-billion-of-gi-bill-funds-go-to-for-profit-colleges/|title=New report shows nearly $2 billion in GI Bill funds go to for-profit colleges|work=PBS NewsHour|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref> Problems with high-interest private loans to students at [[Corinthian Colleges]] (Genesis loans) and [[ITT Tech]] (PEAKS and CUSO loans) have gained scrutiny from the [[Consumer Financial Protection Bureau]] and the [[Securities and Exchange Commission]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.consumerfinance.gov/newsroom/cfpb-sues-for-profit-corinthian-colleges-for-predatory-lending-scheme/|title=CFPB Sues For-Profit Corinthian Colleges for Predatory Lending Scheme|publisher=Consumer Financial Protection Bureau|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/itt-educational-sinks-disclosing-sec-164532930.html|title=ITT Educational sinks after disclosing SEC probe|date=February 25, 2013|work=Yahoo Finance|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Arguments for and against for-profit colleges==\nAlthough supporters of for-profit higher education have argued that the [[profit motive]] encourages efficiency, the for-profit educational industry has received severe negative criticism because of its sales techniques, high costs, and poor student outcomes. In some cases operators of for-profit colleges have faced criminal charges or other legal sanctions.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2013/07/02/college-default-rates-higher-than-grad-rates/2480295/|title=College default rates higher than grad rates|author1=Mary Beth Marklein |author2=Jodi Upton |author3=Sandhya Kambhampati, USA TODAY|date=July 2, 2013|work=USA TODAY|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"digilib.gmu.edu\">{{cite web|url=http://digilib.gmu.edu/jspui/bitstream/1920/6273/1/Perini_thesis_2011.pdf |title=A Phoenix Still in Ashes : For-Profit Open Admissions and the Public Good |publisher=Digilib.gmu.edu |accessdate=July 4, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sites.duke.edu/acfp2012/2012/08/26/doonesbury-talks-for-profit-colleges/|title=Doonesbury Talks For-Profit Colleges - ACFP 2012|publisher=Sites.duke.edu|accessdate=June 14, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150706130158/http://sites.duke.edu/acfp2012/2012/08/26/doonesbury-talks-for-profit-colleges/|archive-date=July 6, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"huffingtonpost.com\">{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/tressie-mcmillan-cottom/for-profit-colleges-kaplan-university_b_1205464.html|title=Insider's View of For-Profit Colleges, Race, Class and Education Justice|work=The Huffington Post|accessdate=June 14, 2015|date=January 13, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://hs.boisestate.edu/nursing/files/2012/01/For-profit-degrees.pdf |title=Under Fire : Nursing Degrees from For-Profit Institutions |publisher=Hs.boisestate.edu |accessdate=July 4, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Benefits===\nHistorically, for-profit education has offered open admissions to non-traditional students, convenience of schedule and location, instructors with workplace knowledge, and real world vocational training rather than traditional training. Critics of [[Wall Street]]-backed for-profit educators, however, have questioned these perceived benefits.<ref name=\"huffingtonpost.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nacacnet.org/issues-action/LegislativeNews/Pages/For-Profit-Colleges.aspx|title=The Low-Down on For-Profit Colleges|publisher=Nacacnet.org|accessdate=June 14, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150120150425/http://www.nacacnet.org/issues-action/LegislativeNews/Pages/For-Profit-Colleges.aspx|archive-date=January 20, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2014/01/for-profit-college-student-debt|title=Screw U: How For-Profit Colleges Rip You Off|work=Mother Jones|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref>For-profit schools like [[University of Phoenix]] have been more inclusive, recruiting and graduating more African Americans than public higher education.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://americanradioworks.publicradio.org/features/tomorrows-college/phoenix/who-goes-to-university-of-phoenix.html|title=Who Goes to the University of Phoenix?|author=American Public Media|publisher=Americanradioworks.publicradio.org|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://urbanmecca.net/news/2008/12/06/more-minority-students-earn-degrees-from-university-of-phoenix/|title=More Minority Students Earn Degrees From University of Phoenix|work=Urbanmecca.com - African American News|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref> In 2012, [[The Journal of Blacks in Higher Education]] called University of Phoenix \"a pillar of [[African American]] higher education.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jbhe.com/2012/02/the-university-of-phoenix-is-a-pillar-of-african-american-higher-education/|title=The University of Phoenix Is a Pillar of African American Higher Education|work=The Journal of Blacks in Higher Education|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref> Through the Thurgood Marshall fund, students at 47 publicly supported [[historically Black colleges and universities]], may supplement their on-campus course loads with course programs using the University of Phoenix online platform.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jbhe.com/2014/11/university-of-phoenix-signs-agreement-to-offer-online-courses-to-hbcu-students/#comments|title=University of Phoenix Signs Agreement to Offer Online Courses to HBCU Students|work=The Journal of Blacks in Higher Education|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref> For-profit colleges have also been seen as a second chance for students who have performed poorly in the past.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eric.ed.gov/?id=EJ989048|title=ERIC - Choice of For-Profit College, Economics of Education Review, 2012-Dec|publisher=Eric.ed.gov|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref> It may be argued that for-profit colleges also created innovations that would force public higher education to be more responsive to student needs<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ecs.org/html/Document.asp?chouseid=1815 |title=Profit-Making or Profiteering? Proprietaries Target Teacher Education |publisher=Ecs.org |date= |accessdate=July 2, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150703025552/http://www.ecs.org/html/Document.asp?chouseid=1815 |archive-date=July 3, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> For-profit colleges have been compared favorably to [[community colleges]] in regards to graduation rates,<ref name=\"stripes.com\"/> but these comparisons may be offering misleading statistical comparisons<ref name=\"mediamatters.org\">{{cite web|url=http://mediamatters.org/research/2015/01/12/wsj-uses-bad-numbers-to-wipe-away-downside-of-f/202104 |title=WSJ Uses Bad Numbers To Wipe Away Downside Of For-Profit Colleges |accessdate=January 16, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150116122736/http://mediamatters.org/research/2015/01/12/wsj-uses-bad-numbers-to-wipe-away-downside-of-f/202104 |archivedate=January 16, 2015 }}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.icl-fi.org/english/wv/1052/ysp-education.html|title=Wall Street's For-Profit University Rip-Off|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=Icl-fi.org|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Drawbacks===\n\nA 2010 report by the [[Government Accountability Office]] (GAO) documented misleading sales and marketing tactics used by several for-profits.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/04/education/04education.html?ref=tamarlewin|work=The New York Times|first=Tamar|last=Lewin|title=For-Profit Colleges Mislead Students, Report Finds|date=August 3, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/12/09/education/09gao.html?ref=education|work=New York Times|first=Tamar|last=Lewin|title=U.S. Revises Report on Recruiting at For-Profit Colleges|date=December 8, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://eric.ed.gov/PDFS/ED511120.pdf |title=FOR-PROFIT COLLEGES Undercover Testing Finds Colleges Encouraged Fraud and Engaged in Deceptive and Questionable Marketing Practices |publisher=Eric.ed.gov |accessdate=July 4, 2015}}</ref> Critics have also pointed out that more than half of for-profits' revenues are either spent on marketing or extracted as profits, with less than half spent on instruction.<ref name=Harkin>{{cite web|title=For-Profit College Investigation|url=http://www.harkin.senate.gov/help/forprofitcolleges.cfm|publisher=U.S. Senate|accessdate=March 19, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130328220032/http://www.harkin.senate.gov/help/forprofitcolleges.cfm|archive-date=March 28, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Where Are Federal G.I. Bill Dollars Going?|url=http://www.harkin.senate.gov/documents/pdf/4eb2c45d86297.pdf|publisher=U.S. Senate|accessdate=March 19, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130317141912/http://www.harkin.senate.gov/documents/pdf/4eb2c45d86297.pdf|archive-date=March 17, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Senator Harkin's Findings Regarding Veterans and For\u2010Profit Colleges|url=http://www.harkin.senate.gov/documents/pdf/4f9ac62292704.pdf|publisher=U.S. Senate|accessdate=March 19, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130218044753/http://www.harkin.senate.gov/documents/pdf/4f9ac62292704.pdf|archive-date=February 18, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> A 2011 study by the [[National Bureau of Economic Research]], in Cambridge, Massachusetts, reported that students who attend for-profit education institutions are more likely to be unemployed, earn less, have higher debt levels, and are more likely to default on their student loans than similar students at non-profit educational institutions.<ref name=Goldin>David J. Deming, Claudia Goldin, and Lawrence F. Katz, \"[http://big.assets.huffingtonpost.com/forprofitpaper.pdf The For-Profit Postsecondary School Sector: Nimble Critters or Agile Predators?]\" National Bureau of Economic Research 2011.</ref> Although for-profits typically serve students who are poorer or more likely to be minorities, these differences do not explain the differences in employment, income, debt levels, and student loan defaults.<ref name=Goldin/> The [[Government Accountability Office]] has also found that graduates of for-profits are less likely to pass licensing exams, and that poor student performance cannot be explained by different student demographics.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Kelly Field|title= Demographics Do Not Explain For-Profit Colleges' Shortcomings on Student-Success Measures, GAO Says|journal=Chronicle of Higher Education|date=December 7, 2011|url=http://chronicle.com/article/article-content/130040/|publisher=Chronicle.com|accessdate=July 4, 2015}}</ref> The same year, ''[[The New York Times]]'' noted that for-profit higher education institutions often have much higher [[student loan default]] rates than non-profits.<ref>{{cite news|author=Tamar Lewin|title=Student Loan Default Rates Rise Sharply in Past Year|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=September 12, 2011|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/09/13/education/13loans.html|accessdate=July 4, 2015}}</ref> Two documentaries by ''[[Frontline (U.S. TV series)|Frontline]]'' have focused on alleged abuses in for profit higher education.<ref>{{cite AV media |people=[[Frontline (U.S. TV series)|Frontline]] |year=2010 |title=College, Inc. |medium=Television production |url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/collegeinc/ |accessdate=July 15, 2013 |publisher=[[PBS]] Distribution |isbn=9781608832835 |oclc=643117456}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/educating-sergeant-pantzke/ |title=Educating Sergeant Pantzke - Video &#124; FRONTLINE |publisher=Pbs.org |date= |accessdate=July 4, 2015}}</ref>Compared to community colleges, some for-profits may have higher completion rates for certificates and associate degree programs,<ref name=\"mediamatters.org\"/> but higher drop out rates for four-year bachelor's degrees.<ref name=Goldin/> However, studies suggest that one- and two-year programs often may not provide much economic benefit to students because the boost to wages is offset by increased debt. By contrast, four-year programs provide a large economic benefit.<ref name=Simkovic>Michael Simkovic, [http://ssrn.com/abstract=1941070 Risk-Based Student Loans] (2012)</ref>For-profits have been sued for allegedly using aggressive and deceptive sales and marketing practices.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/education/college-inc/lawsuits-address-recruitment-practices-at-for-profit-colleges/|title=Lawsuits Address Recruitment Practices at For-Profit Colleges|work=FRONTLINE|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref> Holly Petraeus, a high-ranking official at the [[Consumer Financial Protection Bureau]], has accused for-profits of preying on vulnerable military personnel.<ref>{{cite news|author=Hollister K. Petraeus|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/09/22/opinion/for-profit-colleges-vulnerable-gis.html|title= For-Profit Colleges, Vulnerable G.I.'s|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=September 21, 2011|accessdate=July 4, 2014}}</ref> Petraeus wrote:\"This gives for-profit colleges an incentive to see service members as nothing more than dollar signs in uniform, and to use aggressive marketing to draw them in and take out private loans...One of the most egregious reports of questionable marketing involved a college recruiter who visited a Marine barracks at [[Marine Corps Base Camp Lejeune|Camp Lejeune]], North Carolina. As the PBS program ''Frontline'' reported, the recruiter signed up Marines with serious brain injuries. The fact that some of them couldn\u2019t remember what courses they were taking was immaterial, as long as they signed on the dotted line.\" Opponents say that the fundamental purpose of an educational institution should be to educate, not to turn a profit. In 2000, Bob Chase, president of the [[National Education Association]], stated that \"educating children is very different from producing a product\".<ref name=\"BusinessWeek\">{{cite web|url=http://www.businessweek.com/2000/00_06/b3667001.htm|title=For-Profit Schools|accessdate=September 26, 2008|author=William C Symonds|date=February 7, 2000|work=BusinessWeek|publisher=The McGraw-Hill Companies, Inc.}}</ref> Certain postsecondary education programs at institutions of higher education are eligible for participation in the federal student aid programs, known as [[Title IV]] of the US [[Higher Education Act of 1965|Higher Education Act]] (HEA). These programs, which are offered by public and private not-for-profit institutions, postsecondary vocational institutions, and by for-profit proprietary institutions, should prepare students for [[gainful employment]]. For decades, the [[U.S. Department of Education]] (ED) had not established regulations that explicitly outlined what it means for a program to be properly preparing students for gainful employment. As pressing concerns about the quality of programs at for- profit institutions began to arise, the concerns about the level of student loan debt assumed by students did as well. Such issues led to new initiatives and rules to be set in place outlining the parameters for what should be mandated to help ensure gainful employment. The 2011 Senate HELP committee released data showing one in every four students who enroll at a for-profit school default on their loans within three years of leaving, with for-profit students accounting for almost half of all loan defaults.<ref name=\"Sessions, Jennifer 2011\">Sessions, Jennifer. (February 8, 2011). \"Harkin Calls on For-Profit Colleges to End Deceptive Recruiting Practices\". Senate HELP Committee. Accessed February 4, 2013.</ref> Most for-profit colleges charge enrollees much higher tuition rates than analogous programs at community colleges and state public universities despite credits being likely not eligible to be transferred to other institutions.<ref name=\"Sessions, Jennifer 2011\"/> In fact, 96% of students attending for-profit college apply for federal student loans compared to 13% at community colleges. During the 2009\u20132010 school years, for-profit colleges received almost $32 billion in grants and loans provided to students under federal student aid programs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gao.gov/products/GAO-12-150 |title=U.S. GAO - For-Profit Schools: Experiences of Undercover Students Enrolled in Online Classes at Selected Colleges |publisher=Gao.gov |date= |accessdate=July 4, 2015}}</ref> This staggering number means nearly all students at for-profit institutions acquire student loan debt, even when they do not earn the end product of a degree or accumulate increased earning power through their studies (Sessions, 2011). These statistics represent a large portion of for- profits, uncovering the serious need for greater accountability in ensuring students are making sound investments in such institutions. According to the [[Government Accountability Office]], enrollment in such institutions has increased faster than traditional higher-education institutions in recent years. With the student and federal interest in such programs growing, so has the concern with their productivity. Regrettably, this is not a simple matter to address, as the issue is multidimensional. For-profit institutions have become an increasingly visible portion of the U.S. higher education sector. For-profits also acquire the largest percentage of their overall revenue from federal student aid programs, highlighting tax dollars are potentially not being used efficiently.<ref>Deming, David. (February 2012). \"The For-Profit Postsecondary School Sector:\nNimble Critters or Agile Predators?\" Center for Analysis Postsecondary education and employment.</ref> Federal regulatory actions by the ED have attempted to address these issues in the Title IV of the Higher Education Act of 1965, as amended. These efforts were very contentious. For-profit institutions argue their sector is unfairly targeted and believe the Department of Education over stepped its boundaries in 2010 by implementing regulations specifying requirements for [[Gainful Employment]]. These rules outlined in a report by Congressional Research Service (CRS), aimed to hold for-profits accountable by creating standards which must be upheld and followed, which will in turn attempt create more opportunity for gainful employment amongst enrollees.<ref name=\"SmoleDavid\">Smole, David. (January 23, 2013). \"Department of Education Final Rules for Postsecondary Education Programs That Prepare Students for Gainful Employment in a Recognized Occupation\". Accessed February 4, 2013. Congressional Research Service Database.</ref> Through these regulations the ED believed that institutions will reinforce their educational programs to meet these higher standards, and relatively few programs will fail. Programs that offer a rewarding education at a reasonable price will succeed, and institutions will continue to innovate to assist students and taxpayers.<ref>Federal Registrar. 76 FR 34385. \"Program Integrity: Gainful Employment-Debt Measures\". Accessed February 2, 2013.</ref>The regulations mandated by the ED were to help regulate the for-profit sector and to combat the issue of gainful employment. However, the [[Association of Private Sector Colleges and Universities]], which endorses for-profits, challenged these regulations in court. On June 30, 2012 the U.S. District Court for the District of Columbia decided to vacate most aspects of the regulations.<ref name=\"SmoleDavid\" /> The court sustained that the ED had the authority to regulate gainful employment, yet it cited the ED had not provided rationale metrics or measures in the debt measures. At present, only the disclosure requirements of providing prospective students with placements rates, on time graduation rates and other similar information remain.<ref>Smole, David. (January 23, 2013). \"Department of Education Final Rules for Postsecondary Education Programs That Prepare Students for Gainful Employment in a Recognized Occupation\". Accessed February 4, 2013. Congressional Research Service Database</ref> On March 19, 2013 the judge ruled again in response to the ED's motion to reinstate the reporting requirements in order that it could implement the disclosure requirements of Gainful Employment. The judged denied the motion of the ED on the basis that the reporting requirements would violate the federal ban on the student unit record system. It is strongly debatable that the court's ruling negates the small amount of transparency and accountability mandated by the disclosure requirements, leaving the policy issue of for-profits being accountable for [[Gainful Employment]] unattended.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newamerica.net/taxonomy/term/1764 |title=Welcome to nginx! |publisher=Newamerica.net |date= |accessdate=July 4, 2015}}</ref> Some former students claim that for-profit colleges make them feel like they went to the flea market and bought themselves a degree.<ref>[https://www.cbsnews.com/video/watch/?id=6838088n CBS News Video, \"For-Profit Colleges Under Fire\"], September 18, 2010.</ref> According to James G. Andrews of the [[American Association of University Professors]], corporate models of education harm the mission of education.<ref>{{cite web|last=Andrews |first=James G. |url=http://www.aaup.org/AAUP/pubsres/academe/2006/MJ/feat/andr.htm |title=How We Can Resist Corporatization |publisher=AAUP |accessdate=March 19, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101222235655/http://www.aaup.org/AAUP/pubsres/academe/2006/MJ/feat/andr.htm |archivedate=December 22, 2010 }}</ref> Some critics have called for-profit education \"subprime education\", in an analogy with the [[subprime mortgage]]s bubble at the heart of the [[Great Recession]] \u2013 finding uninformed borrowers and loading them with debt they cannot afford, then securitizing and passing the loan onto third-party investors. Activist short seller [[Steve Eisman]] (famous for being a character in [[Michael Lewis]]'s ''[[The Big Short]]'') has described the accreditation situation regarding for-profits like ITT as follows: \"The scandal here is exactly akin to the rating agency role in subprime securitizations.\"<ref>[https://www.cnbc.com/id/37896158/Greenberg_For_Profit_Schools_Subprime_Redux Greenberg: For-Profit Schools ... Subprime Redux?] Herb Greenberg, June 24, 2010</ref>A two-year congressional investigation report\u2014from a committee chaired by Senator [[Tom Harkin]], D-Iowa\u2014examined enrollment numbers in selected for-profit higher education institutions. The committee found that $32 billion in federal funds were spent in 2009\u20132010 on for-profit colleges. The majority of students enrolled in the institutions left without a degree and carried post-schooling debt. Regarding the dropout rates, the report said 54% of students in bachelor's degree programs dropped out before degree completion and 63% of students in associate degree programs dropped out.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.help.senate.gov/imo/media/for_profit_report/Contents.pdf|title=''For Profit Higher Education: The Failure to Safeguard the Federal Investment and Ensure Student Success''|website=Senate.gov|access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref>In 2019, the Department of Education reported median student debt from for-profit colleges and found that among people pursuing a bachelor's degree, those who graduated from for-profits borrowed $43,600, compared to $27,900 for public college graduates and $32,500 for private nonprofit college graduates.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Schwartz |first1=Natalie |title=In shifting for-profit college market, borrowers are taking on more debt |url=https://www.educationdive.com/news/student-debt-grows-in-shifting-for-profit-college-market/558683/ |website=Education Dive |accessdate=July 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Accreditation and transfer-of-credits==\nMany for-profit institutions of [[higher education]] have [[Regional accreditation#Regional accreditation vs. national accreditation|national accreditation]] rather than [[regional accreditation]]. Regionally accredited schools are predominantly academically oriented, non-profit institutions.<ref name=\"usaed\"/><ref name=yahoo/> Nationally accredited schools are predominantly for-profit and offer vocational, career, or technical programs.<ref name=\"usaed\"/><ref name=\"yahoo\"/> Most regionally accredited schools will not accept transfer credits earned at a nationally accredited school because, except for some specialized areas such as nursing, the standards for regional accreditation are higher than those for national accreditation.<ref name=\"usaed\">{{cite web|url=http://www.useducation.com.pk/stpages/typesofaccreditation.html |title=''Types of Accreditation'', Education USA website |publisher=Useducation.com.pk |accessdate=March 19, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080424074806/http://www.useducation.com.pk/stpages/typesofaccreditation.html |archivedate=April 24, 2008 }}</ref><ref name=\"yahoo\">{{cite web|url=http://help.yahoo.com/l/us/yahoo/education/courses/distancelearn-09.html |title=''What is the Difference Between Regional and National Accreditation'', Yahoo! Education website |publisher=Help.yahoo.com |accessdate=March 19, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101205210641/http://help.yahoo.com/l/us/yahoo/education/courses/distancelearn-09.html |archivedate=December 5, 2010 }}</ref><ref name=\"demand\">{{cite web|author=Scott Jaschik|date=October 19, 2005|title=Demanding Credit|work=Insidehighered.com|url=http://www.insidehighered.com/news/2005/10/19/transfer|accessdate=July 4, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"tussle\">{{cite web|author=Doug Lederman|url=http://insidehighered.com/news/2007/02/26/transfer|title=Tussling Over Transfer of Credit|work=Insidehighered.com|date=February 26, 2007|accessdate=July 4, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2005 congressional discussions concerning reauthorization of the Higher Education Act and in the [[U.S. Secretary of Education]]'s [http://www.ed.gov/about/bdscomm/list/hiedfuture/index.html ''Commission on the Future of Higher Education''], there were proposals, ultimately unsuccessful, to mandate that regional accrediting agencies bar the schools they accredit from basing decisions on whether or not to accept credits for transfer ''solely'' on the accreditation of the \"sending\" school.<ref name=demand/><ref name=tussle/> They could still reject the credits, but they would have to have additional reasons.{{Citation needed|date=August 2008}} The American Commission of Career Schools and Colleges (ACCSC), a nonprofit accreditor for-profit schools, supported the proposed rule.<ref name=demand/><ref name=tussle/><ref name=agenda/> The ACCSC claims regionally accredited schools will not accept nationally accredited schools credits for purely arbitrary, prejudicial and/or anti-competitive reasons.<ref name=agenda/> It further stated that, since the Department of Education recognizes both national and regional accreditation, there is no reason for regionals to differentiate between the two and to do so amounts to an unwarranted denial of access.<ref name=demand/><ref name=tussle/><ref name=\"agenda\">{{cite web|url=http://www.accsc.org/Student-Corner/Transfer-of-Credit.aspx|publisher=accsc.org|title=Transfer of Credit |accessdate=February 18, 2017}}</ref> The position of the [[American Association of Collegiate Registrars and Admissions Officers]] (AACRAO) was that national accrediting standards were not as rigorous and, though they might be well-suited for vocational and career education, were ill-suited for academic institutions.<ref name=\"aacrao\">{{cite web|url=http://www.aacrao.org/federal_relations/transfer/FEDERALIZING_TRANSFER_OF_ACADEMIC_CREDIT.pdf |title=''Federalized Transfer of Academic Credit, Proposed Mandate Would Hurt Students'' AACRAO website |accessdate=March 19, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101226201419/http://www.aacrao.org/federal_relations/transfer/FEDERALIZING_TRANSFER_OF_ACADEMIC_CREDIT.pdf |archivedate=December 26, 2010 }}</ref> AACRAO alleged that this proposed rule was unnecessary and unjustified, could threaten the autonomy and potentially lower the standards of regionally accredited schools, and drive up their costs.<ref name=aacrao/> Furthermore, it stated the proposed rule was an attempt by the for-profits' \"well-funded lobbyists\" to obscure the difference between for-profits' \"lax academic criteria for accreditation\" and non-profits' higher standards.<ref name=aacrao/>\n\nSome for-profit schools have received regional accreditation, including [[American InterContinental University]], [[American Public University System]], [[Capella University]], [[DeVry University]], [[Kaplan University]], [[National American University]], [[Post University]], [[San Joaquin Valley College]], [[Strayer University]], [[University of Phoenix]], [[Universal Technical Institute]], and [[Walden University]].\n\nAccrediting agencies have gained some scrutiny and criticism for conflicts of interest. Because these agencies receive their funding from the institutions themselves, they may have a vested interest in not aggressively supervising these for-profit colleges.<ref name=\"huffingtonpost.com1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/09/19/for-profit-college-accreditation_n_3937079.html|title=How For-Profit Colleges Stay In Business Despite Terrible Track Record|work=The Huffington Post|accessdate=June 14, 2015|date=September 19, 2013}}</ref> According to Chris Kirkham and Kevin Short:\n\"Two accrediting bodies...collectively monitor nearly 60 percent of all American for-profit colleges. They preside over almost half of those schools with the nation's worst student loan default rates....Ten of the 15 board members supervising the ACICS are drawn from the industry, including executives from Corinthian, [[Education Corporation of America]] and [[ITT Technical Institute]]. On the ACCSC board, industry executives fill eight of the 13 slots, representing publicly traded companies such as [[Universal Technical Institute]] and [[Kaplan, Inc.|Kaplan]] Higher Education.\"<ref name=\"huffingtonpost.com1\"/>\n\nIn 2016, 12 Attorneys General asked the [[US Department of Education]] to stop the renewal of [[ACICS]], the [[Accrediting Council for Independent Colleges and Schools]]<ref name=\"propublica\">{{cite web|url=https://www.propublica.org/article/attorneys-general-come-down-on-accreditor-of-for-profit-colleges|publisher=propublica.org|title=Attorneys General Come Down on Accreditor of For-profit Colleges - ProPublica|accessdate=February 18, 2017|date=April 11, 2016}}</ref> The Department of Education deliberated on the fate of [[ACICS]] and its power to accredit schools for Title IV government funds.<ref name=\"wsj2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-for-profit-kill-zone-1466638683|publisher=wsj.com|title=The For-Profit Kill Zone - WSJ|accessdate=February 18, 2017}}</ref> On June 23, 2016, The National Advisory Committee on Institutional Quality and Integrity (NACIQI), voted to revoke ACICS's power to accredit schools.{{citation needed|date=October 2019}}\n\n==Business failures==\nNotable failures include [[Corinthian Colleges]] (2015), [[ITT Technical Institute]] (2016), [[Education Management Corporation]] (2017), [[Education Corporation of America]] (2018) and [[Vatterott College]] (2018).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2014/06/26/corinthians-failure-and-us-role-it-fuels-profit-critics|title=Corinthian's failure (and U.S. role in it) fuels for-profit critics |publisher=Insidehighered.com|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/business/2014/08/27/EDMC-debt-restructuring/stories/201408270182|title=EDMC announces debt restructuring; expects improved capital structure|work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|accessdate=June 14, 2015|date=August 27, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2018/12/06/closure-education-corporation-america-raises-questions-about-oversight-and-support|title=Closure of Education Corporation of America raises questions about oversight and support for students|website=www.insidehighered.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/quicktakes/2018/12/19/vatterott-educational-centers-close|title=Vatterott Educational Centers to Close &#124; Inside Higher Ed|website=www.insidehighered.com}}</ref> In 2010, [[Trump University]] was closed by the State of New York for operating without a license.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/10/16/us-trump-nyag-lawsuit-idUSKCN0I52MW20141016|title=New York judge finds Donald Trump liable for unlicensed school|work=Reuters|accessdate=June 14, 2015|date=October 16, 2014}}</ref> In 2014, FastTrain college closed after being raided by the FBI.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fbi.gov/miami/press-releases/2014/fast-train-owner-and-three-admissions-representatives-arrested-for-theft-of-federal-student-aid|title=FBI \u2014 Fast Train Owner and Three Admissions Representatives Arrested for Theft of Federal Student Aid|work=FBI|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref> In 2016, all campuses of [[Westwood College]] closed.<ref name=\"insidehighered.com\"/> In 2016, the US Department of Education stripped [[ACICS]], the accreditor of ITT Tech and many more colleges, of its accrediting power.{{Citation needed|date=January 2018}} The ACICS was given the power back under Secretary of Education Betsy DeVos.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/opinion/editorials/la-ed-devos-student-loans-20180831-story.html|title=Editorial: Betsy DeVos sides with predatory for-profit colleges over America's students|date=August 31, 2018|website=Los Angeles Times}}</ref> In 2018 and 2019, [[Dream Center]] Education Holdings faced a financial crisis with colleges with [[Art Institutes]], [[Argosy University]], and [[South University]] brands, which had been converted from for-profit to non-profit.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.post-gazette.com/business/career-workplace/2019/02/13/Financial-aid-Art-Institute-Dream-Center-Education-Holdings-EDMC-Mark-Dottore/stories/201902130104|title=$13 million in financial aid missing? Federal receiver tries to track down money from Art Institute owners|website=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette}}</ref>\n\n==Government scrutiny, criminal and civil investigations==\n\nAccording to A.J. Angulo, for-profit higher education in the US has been the subject of government scrutiny from the mid-1980s to the 2010s.<ref name=\"books.google.com\"/>\n\nIn August 2010, the [[Government Accountability Office]] reported on an investigation that randomly sampled student-recruiting practices of several for-profit institutions. Investigators posing as prospective students documented deceptive recruiting practices, including misleading information about costs and potential future earnings. They also reported that some recruiters urged them to provide false information on applications for financial aid.<ref>Daniel de Vise and Paul Kane, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/08/04/AR2010080403816.html GAO: 15 for-profit colleges used deceptive recruiting tactics], ''[[The Washington Post]]'', August 5, 2010</ref> Out of the fifteen sampled, all had engaged in deceptive practices, improperly promising unrealistically high pay for graduating students, and four engaged in outright [[fraud]], per a GAO report released at a hearing of the [[Health, Education, Labor and Pensions Committee]] on August 4, 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gao.gov/products/GAO-10-948T|title=U.S. GAO - For-Profit Colleges: Undercover Testing Finds Colleges Encouraged Fraud and Engaged in Deceptive and Questionable Marketing Practices|publisher=Gao.gov|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref> Examples of misconduct included:offering [[commission (remuneration)|commissions]] to admissions officers, employing deceptive marketing tactics by refusing to disclose total tuition cost to prospective students before signing a binding agreement, lying about accreditation, encouraging outright fraud by enticing students to take out student loans even when the applicant had $250,000 in savings, promising extravagant, unlikely high pay to students, failing to disclose graduation rate, and offering tuition cost equivalent to 9 months of credit hours per year, when total program length was 12 months. The GAO study found that 14 out of 15 times, the tuition at a for-profit sample was more expensive than its public counterpart, and 11 out of 15 times, it was more expensive than the private counterpart. Examples of the disparity in full tuition per program include: $14,000 for a certificate at the for-profit institution, when the same diploma cost $500 at a public college; $38,000 for an Associate's at the for-profit institution, when the comparable program at the public college cost $5,000; $61,000 for a Bachelor's at the for-profit institution, compared to $36,000 for the same degree at the public college.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gao.gov/new.items/d10948t.pdf|title=GAO-10-948T For-Profit Colleges: Undercover Testing Finds Colleges Encouraged Fraud and Engaged in Deceptive and Questionable Marketing Practices|date=August 4, 2010|accessdate=March 19, 2011}}</ref> This is counter to [[International Education Corporation]] CEO [[Fardad Fateri|Fardad Fateri's]] claims of the lack of use of unorthodox recruiting practices and a for-profit's \"value\" in an IEC open letter to Congress, the tuition cost of certificates and associate degrees being 28 and 6 times more than at a public college, respectively; Fateri writes, \"Credit should be given to non-profit universities that have been able to convince students and their sophisticated parents to pay approximately $400,000.00 for an undergraduate degree that will seldom lead to an academically related career.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iecglobal.com/Aug2710.asp|title=International Education Corporation : Newsroom|date=August 27, 2010|publisher=Iecglobal.com|accessdate=March 19, 2011}}</ref>The institutions identified in the Committee hearing in respect to the GAO report numeration included [[University of Phoenix]],Everest Institute, [[Kaplan]], [[Argosy University]], [[Anthem Institute]], and [[Westwood College]].\n \nIn 2010, students at for-profit institutions represented about 12% of all college students, but receive roughly 25% of all Federal Pell Grants and loans. They were also responsible for approximately 44% of all student loan defaults.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://projectonstudentdebt.org/files/pub/CDR_2014_NR.pdf |title=Despite Lower Rates, More Than 650,000 Defaulted on Federal Student Loans For-Profit Colleges Account for Nearly Half of all Defaults |publisher=Projectonstudentdebt.org |accessdate=July 4, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pewtrusts.org/news_room_detail.aspx?id=56473|title=New Default Rate Data for Federal Student Loans: 44% of Defaulters Attended For-Profit Institutions|publisher=Pew Charitable Trusts|date=December 15, 2009|accessdate=March 19, 2011}}</ref> University of Phoenix topped this list with Pell Grant revenue of $656.9 million with second and third place held by Everest Colleges at $256.6 million and Kaplan College at $202.1 million for the 2008\u20132009 fiscal year, respectively.<ref name=\"Chronicle of Higher Education\">[http://chronicle.com/article/Data-Points-For-Profit/63388 For-Profit Colleges Capitalize on Pell Grant Revenue], ''The Chronicle of Higher Education'', January 4, 2010.</ref> In 2003, a [[Government Accountability Office]] report estimated that overpayments of Pell Grants were running at about 3% annually, amounting to around $300 million per year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gao.gov/new.items/d03821.pdf|title=TAXPAYER INFORMATION: Increased Sharing and Verifying of Information Could Improve Education's Award Decisions|date=July 2003|publisher=[[Government Accountability Office]]}}</ref> Some of the universities that were top recipients of Pell Grants had low graduation rates, leaving students degreeless, and many graduating alumni found it excessively difficult to find gainful employment.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2010/08/06/degreed-and-jobless-for-p_n_673053.html|title=Degreed And Jobless, For-Profit College Graduate Turns To Stripping|publisher=Huffingtonpost.com|date=August 6, 2010|accessdate=March 19, 2011|first=Leah|last=Finnegan}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitaljournal.com/article/295688|title=Stripper says for-profit college degree 'worthless'|publisher=Digitaljournal.com|date=August 8, 2010|accessdate=March 19, 2011}}</ref> with their degrees, leading some former students to accuse recruiters of being \"duplicitous\", and bringing into serious question the effectiveness of awarding Pell Grants and other [[Title IV]] funds to for-profit colleges.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessweek.com/news/2010-05-05/for-profit-n-j-college-halts-recruiting-of-homeless-update1-.html|title=For-Profit N.J. College Halts Recruiting of Homeless (Update1)|publisher=Businessweek|date=May 5, 2010|accessdate=March 19, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Higher Ed Watch\">[http://higheredwatch.newamerica.net/blogs/2007/02/u_of_phoenix Fed Up at the University of Phoenix] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150122153909/http://higheredwatch.newamerica.net/blogs/2007/02/u_of_phoenix |date=January 22, 2015 }}, ''Higher Ed Watch'', February 27, 2007.</ref> University of Phoenix's graduation rate is 15%.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.phoenix.edu/content/dam/altcloud/doc/about_uopx/University-of-Phoenix-Consumer-Information-Guide-2009-2010.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=January 13, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100821102056/http://www.phoenix.edu/content/dam/altcloud/doc/about_uopx/University-of-Phoenix-Consumer-Information-Guide-2009-2010.pdf |archivedate=August 21, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/02/11/education/11phoenix.html|work=The New York Times|title=Troubles Grow for a University Built on Profits|first=Sam|last=Dillon|date=February 11, 2007}}</ref> [[Strayer University]], which reports its loan repayment rate to be 55%, only has a repayment rate of roughly 25%,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://archival.malformedxmlelement.com/For-Profit%20Colleges/Strayer%20ge-cumulative-rates.xls |title=Archived copy |accessdate=January 13, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110811171948/http://archival.malformedxmlelement.com/For-Profit%20Colleges/Strayer%20ge-cumulative-rates.xls |archivedate=August 11, 2011}}</ref> according to data released by the [[U.S. Department of Education]] on August 13, 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.ed.gov/policy/highered/reg/hearulemaking/2009/ge-cumulative-rates.xls |format=XLS |title=Cumulative Rates |publisher=2.ed.gov |accessdate=July 4, 2015}}</ref> The low repayment rate made [[Strayer]] ineligible for receiving further Title IV funds in accordance with new \"Gainful employment\" regulations brought forth by the Department of Education, which were to take effect in July 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.insidehighered.com/content/download/357892/4393975/file/Gainful%20Employment%20NPRM.pdf |title=gainful employment NPRM |accessdate=March 19, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101105052245/http://www.insidehighered.com/content/download/357892/4393975/file/Gainful%20Employment%20NPRM.pdf |archivedate=November 5, 2010 }}</ref> If passed, the minimum loan repayment requirement for any institution receiving Title IV funds, subject to suspension and expulsion if not compliant, will be 45%.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/14/education/14college.html|work=The New York Times|title=Data Show Low Loan Repayment at For-Profit Schools|first=Tamar|last=Lewin|date=August 13, 2010}}</ref> In an August 4, 2010 Health, Education, Labor and Pensions Committee hearing, Gregory Kutz of the [[GAO]] stated that the fraudulent practices may be widespread in the For-Profit industry, noting a University of Phoenix executive chart that encouraged deceptive practices.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.c-spanvideo.org/program/294901-1|title=For-Profit College Financial Aid, Government Panel|publisher=C-SPAN|date=August 4, 2010|accessdate=March 19, 2011}}</ref> Joshua Pruyn, a former admissions representative, disclosed to the committee hearing several internal emails distributed among admissions officers in March 2008 which encouraged applications and enrollments through the use of a commissions reward system.\nDuring a congressional hearing to present the report, Pruyn's testimony was disproven by tapes of conversations, and it was reported that Pruyn's comments were written by attorneys who were suing Westwood,{{citation needed|date=October 2019}} and inappropriately coached by Chairman of the committee Senator [[Thomas Harkin]] staffers who organized the hearing.<ref name=07-21-2011>{{cite news|last=Strong|first=Jonathan|title=Dem Senator Accused of Witness Tampering|url=http://nation.foxnews.com/tom-harkin/2011/07/21/dem-senator-accused-witness-tampering|date=July 21, 2011|newspaper=Fox News|accessdate=July 4, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116132027/http://nation.foxnews.com/tom-harkin/2011/07/21/dem-senator-accused-witness-tampering|archive-date=January 16, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> Sen. Harkin noted the [[conflict of interest]] due to the ACCSC, a national accrediting agency that accredits many for-profit colleges nationwide,<ref name=\"accsc\">{{cite web|url=http://www.accsc.org/Content/CommissionActions/documents/STBCListAugust2010.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100917065411/http://accsc.org/Content/CommissionActions/documents/STBCListAugust2010.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 17, 2010 |publisher=accsc.org|title=404 |accessdate=February 18, 2017}}</ref> receiving compensation directly from the institutions to which it awards accreditation. The [[Inspector General]] issued an assessment in late 2009 recommending the limiting and possible suspension or expulsion of the [[Higher Learning Commission]] of the [[North Central Association of Colleges and Schools]] due to conflicts in the manner in which the accrediting agency reviews credit hours and program length for online-colleges, specifically [[American InterContinental University]], a for-profit college.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lloyd|first=Marion|url=http://chronicle.com/article/Inspector-Generals-Warning-to/63206/|title=Inspector General's Warning to Accreditor Raises Fears Among For-Profit Institutions|publisher=Chronicle of Higher Education|date=December 17, 2009|accessdate=March 19, 2011}}</ref> The NCA HLC accredits the [[University of Phoenix]] and Everest in Phoenix, Arizona. On November 30, 2010, the GAO issued a revised report, softening several examples from an undercover investigation and changing some key passages, but stood by its central finding that colleges had encouraged fraud and misled potential applicants.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/12/07/AR2010120706803.html|title=GAO revises its report critical of practices at for-profit schools|work=The Washington Post|first=Nick|last=Anderson|date=December 8, 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, a criminal investigation of [[Corinthian Colleges]] was initiated.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-corinthian-colleges-20140814-story.html|title=Corinthian Colleges tells investors it is facing a criminal probe|author=Los Angeles Times|date=August 13, 2014|work=latimes.com|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nUntil 2015, The US Attorney General and at least eleven states maintained an $11 billion lawsuit against [[Education Management Corporation]]\n<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/local/city/2014/05/06/Judge-says-lawsuit-against-Education-Management-can-continue/stories/201405060222|title=Judge says lawsuit against Education Management can continue|work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|accessdate=June 14, 2015|date=May 6, 2014}}</ref> The US [[Consumer Financial Protection Bureau]] also has a suit against ITT Educational Services, parent company of [[ITT Tech]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.republicreport.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/cfpb_complaint_ITT.pdf |title=Consumer Financial Protection Bureau v. ITT Educational Services, Inc. |publisher=Republicreport.org |accessdate=July 4, 2015}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.consumerfinance.gov/newsroom/cfpb-sues-for-profit-college-chain-itt-for-predatory-lending/|title=CFPB Sues For-Profit College Chain ITT For Predatory Lending|work=Consumer Financial Protection Bureau|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref>\nIn 2016, Alejandro Amor, the founder of FastTrain, was sentenced to eight years in federal prison for fraud.<ref name=\"npr\">{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/ed/2016/05/12/477655591/jail-time-for-a-for-profit-college-founder|publisher=npr.org|title=As Feds Crack Down On For-Profit College, A Founder Heads To Prison For Fraud : NPR Ed : NPR|accessdate=February 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Attempts to regulate and deregulate the industry==\nThe [[US Department of Education]] (DoED) has proposed rules, \"gainful employment regulations\", that would provide more transparency and accountability to institutions that offer professional and technical training. According to DoED, this regulation is an attempt to \"protect borrowers and taxpayers.\"<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Obama Administration Announces Final Rules to Protect Students from Poor-Performing Career College Programs |url= http://www.ed.gov/news/press-releases/obama-administration-announces-final-rules-protect-students-poor-performing-care|location= |publisher= [[United States Department of Education]] |agency= |date= October 30, 2014 |accessdate=January 16, 2015}}</ref> In his 2015 budget proposal, President Obama recommended greater regulation of for-profit education, including a closure of the loophole that exempted GI Bill money from being used in the 90-10 formula.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2015/02/03/obama-seeks-boost-higher-education-spending-and-proposes-some-loan-reforms-have|title=Obama seeks to boost higher education spending and proposes some loan reforms that have bipartisan appeal - InsideHigherEd|publisher=Insidehighered.com|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref>In 2017, the US Department of Education held public hearings were held in order to determine whether the government had overstepped regulation efforts, particularly with [[gainful employment]] and [[defense to repayment]] rules.<ref>https://www.usnews.com/news/education-news/articles/2017-07-10/trump-administration-begins-rewriting-for-profit-regulations</ref>\nIn August 2017, Secretary of Education Betsy DeVos instituted policies to loosen regulations on for-profit colleges.<ref name=\"consumerist.com\"/> In September 2017, the Trump Administration proposed to remove conflict of interest rules between VA officials and for-profit colleges.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/09/29/business/veterans-affairs-ethics.html|title=Veterans Agency Seeks to Scrap Ethics Law on For-Profit Colleges|first=Patricia|last=Cohen|date=September 29, 2017|publisher=|access-date=January 1, 2018|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref> In March 2018, the House Subcommittee on Labor, Health and Human Services, Education and Related Agencies began reviewing problems related to for-profit colleges and student loan debt.<ref name=courthousenews/>Lobbyists for the for-profit higher education industry have taken several steps to stop regulation and to fight against transparency and accountability.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/quicktakes/2014/11/07/profit-groups-sue-block-gainful-employment-rules|title=For-Profit Groups Sue to Block Gainful Employment Rules |publisher=Insidehighered.com|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref> They have also supported at least two lawsuits to squash gainful employment regulations.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.career.org/news-and-media/press-releases/upload/APSCU-v-Duncan-DDC-2014-11-06-Plaintiff-s-Complaint.pdf |title=Association of Private Sector Colleges and Universities v. Arne Duncan |publisher=Career.org |accessdate=July 4, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150329192846/http://www.career.org/news-and-media/press-releases/upload/APSCU-v-Duncan-DDC-2014-11-06-Plaintiff-s-Complaint.pdf |archive-date=March 29, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxbusiness.com/markets/2014/11/07/for-profit-colleges-file-lawsuit-to-halt-new-obama-administration-regulations/|title=For-profit colleges file lawsuit to halt new Obama administration regulations|work=Fox Business|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.apscu.org/news-and-media/press-releases/upload/APSCU-v-Duncan-DDC-2015-02-06-Plaintiff-s-Motion-for-Summary-Judgment2.pdf |title=Association of Private Sector Colleges and Universities v. Arne Duncan |publisher=Apscu.org |accessdate=July 4, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150209223722/http://www.apscu.org/news-and-media/press-releases/upload/APSCU-v-Duncan-DDC-2015-02-06-Plaintiff-s-Motion-for-Summary-Judgment2.pdf |archive-date=February 9, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==For-profit colleges transitioning to nonprofit colleges==\nAt least three colleges or universities have transitioned to nonprofit status: [[Keiser University]], [[Remington College]], and [[Herzing University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chronicle.com/blogs/ticker/for-profit-herzing-u-converts-to-nonprofit-status/91695|title=For-Profit Herzing U. Converts to Nonprofit Status \u2013 The Ticker - Blogs - The Chronicle of Higher Education|publisher=Chronicle.com|accessdate=June 14, 2015|date=January 5, 2015}}</ref> Journalists argue that these transitions are strategies to reduce state and federal regulations and to obtain more [[Title IV]] funds, as well as to improve reputations as for-profit education now has a stigma to the public.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/davidhalperin/if-a-for-profit-college-b_b_2661788.html|title=If a For-Profit College Becomes a Non-Profit, Is That Good? Not Necessarily|work=The Huffington Post|accessdate=June 14, 2015|date=February 11, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jsonline.com/business/herzing-university-becomes-a-nonprofit-organization-b99419151z1-287365131.html|title=Herzing University becomes a nonprofit organization|author=Rick Romell|publisher=Jsonline.com|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref> In 2014 [[Grand Canyon University]] considered a transition to nonprofit status.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2014-11-13/grand-canyon-eyes-2-billion-exit-from-for-profit-college-stigma.html|title=Grand Canyon Eyes $2 Billion Exit From For-Profit College Stigma|author=Michael McDonald|date=November 13, 2014|work=Bloomberg.com|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref> In 2016, Grand Canyon's regional accreditation body, [[The Higher Learning Commission]], formally rejected the university's petition for conversion to non-profit status. The commission's board of directors stated that the school did not meet all five criteria for \"such a conversion\".<ref name=\"www.hlcommission.org\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hlcommission.org/download/_PublicDisclosureNotices/Grand%20Canyon%20University%20PDN.pdf|title=Public Disclosure Notice|website=HLCommission.org|access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"ktar.com\">{{cite web|url=http://ktar.com/story/946879/grand-canyon-university-denied-switch-to-nonprofit-status/|publisher=ktar.com|title=Grand Canyon University denied switch to nonprofit status|accessdate=February 18, 2017|date=March 4, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"www.abc15.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.abc15.com/news/region-phoenix-metro/central-phoenix/grand-canyon-university-denied-request-to-switch-to-nonprofit-status|publisher=abc15.com|title=Grand Canyon University denied request to switch to nonprofit status - ABC15 Arizona|accessdate=February 18, 2017|date=March 4, 2016}}</ref> In 2017, [[Kaplan University]] was sold to [[Purdue University]] and became [[Purdue University Global]] in 2018. Kaplan, however, became the servicer for the institution and the Higher Learning Commission continued to accredit the school.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.purdue.edu/newsroom/releases/2018/Q1/purdue-announces-name-for-new-public-university-purdue-university-global-to-serve-working-adults,-online.html |title = Purdue announces name for new public university: Purdue University Global to serve working adults, online}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.jconline.com/story/news/2018/09/10/regulators-purdue-campus-review-purdue-global-deal/1252718002/ |title = Regulators return to Purdue campus to review Purdue Global deal}}</ref> In 2018, [[Grand Canyon University]] and [[Ashford University]] petitioned for non-profit status.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2018/03/13/ashford-university-latest-big-profit-attempt-nonprofit-conversion|title=Ashford University is latest big for-profit to attempt nonprofit conversion|author=|date=|website=insidehighered.com}}</ref> In 2018, Grand Canyon University attempted to regain its non-profit status<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/news/local/arizona-education/2018/07/02/grand-canyon-university-regains-its-non-profit-status/747376002/|title=It's official: Grand Canyon University has its non-profit status back|first=Rachel|last=Leingang|website=azcentral}}</ref> but the [[U.S. Department of Education]] denied that change in 2019, and continues to classify the university as for-profit.<ref name=CollegeNavigator>{{cite web |url=https://nces.ed.gov/collegenavigator/?id=104717 |title=College Navigator |publisher=[[National Center for Education Statistics]] |date=2019 |accessdate=September 30, 2019}}</ref><ref name=IHE_for-profit>{{cite web |url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2019/11/07/education-department-calls-grand-canyon-profit-raising-questions-about-conversion |title=Surprise for Grand Canyon's Nonprofit Conversion |first=Paul |last=Fain |publisher=[[Inside Higher Ed]] |date=November 7, 2019 |accessdate=November 7, 2019}}</ref> In 2019, the [[Internal Revenue Service]] granted [[Ashford University]] non-profit tax status. Ashford University was the major source of revenue for [[Bridgepoint Education]], now known as [[Zovio]].<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.educationdive.com/news/irs-approval-brings-ashford-u-a-step-closer-to-nonprofit-status/548718/ |title = IRS approval brings Ashford U a step closer to nonprofit status}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Business college]]\n* [[Career college]]\n* [[Diploma mill]]\n* [[Higher education in the United States]]\n* [[List of for-profit universities and colleges]]\n* [[List of unaccredited institutions of higher education]]\n* [[Online program manager]]\n* [[Privatization in the United States]]\n* [[Student debt]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Schools}}\n\n[[Category:School types]]\n[[Category:For-profit universities and colleges in the United States| ]]\n[[Category:Higher education in the United States]]\n[[Category:Education policy in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Consists of higher education educational institutions operated by profit-seeking businesses}}\n{{Use American English|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Education in the U.S.}}\n'''For-profit higher education in the United States''' has typically consisted of [[higher education]] [[educational institution]]s operated by [[Profit (economics)|profit]]-seeking [[business]]es.  However, with the blurring of public and private over the last four decades,\n<ref>{{cite book |last1=Mettler |first1=Suzanne |title=Degrees of Inequality: How the Politics of Higher Education Sabotaged the American Dream |date=2014 |publisher=Basic Books |location=New York, NY |isbn=978-0-465-04496-2 |pages=120-122 |edition=1st |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KJzSDQAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=degrees+of+inequality+mettler&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjtxOjXncfoAhWSl3IEHeU7CLMQ6AEwAHoECAAQAg#v=onepage&q=degrees%20of%20inequality%20mettler&f=false |accessdate=1 April 2020 |ref=Google Books}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite book |last1=Roth |first1=Gary |title=The Educated Underclass: Students and the Promise of Social Mobility |date=2019 |publisher=Pluto Press |location=London |isbn=9780745339221 |pages=68\u201369 |edition=1st}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/ccap/2012/01/26/are-state-universities-being-privatized/#5042a3741db5 |title = Are State Universities Being Privatized?}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.edsurge.com/news/2019-05-30-is-there-still-a-meaningful-difference-between-for-profit-and-public-higher-ed |title = Is There Still a Meaningful Difference Between For-Profit and Public Higher Ed? - EdSurge News|date = May 30, 2019}}</ref> for-profit higher education also includes for-profit mechanisms such as [[Financial endowment|endowment]] money managers,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nonprofitquarterly.org/large-university-endowments-and-investment-fees-under-fire/|title=Large University Endowments and Investment Fees Under Fire|date=August 21, 2015|website=Non Profit News &#124; Nonprofit Quarterly}}</ref> for-profit fees for service,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/digital-learning/article/2017/10/25/opms-fee-service-growing-revenue-share-models-dominate|title=OPMs: Fee for service is growing, but revenue-share models dominate &#124; Inside Higher Ed|website=www.insidehighered.com}}</ref> for-profit marketing, enrollment services and lead generation,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2014/09/15/lead-generation-more-information-and-fewer-leads|title=Lead generation with more information and fewer leads|website=www.insidehighered.com}}</ref>\nprivatized campus services,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailycal.org/2019/03/10/uc-santa-cruz-student-parents-protest-shift-to-privatized-child-care-services/|title=UC Santa Cruz student-parents protest shift to privatized child care services|first=Sabina |last=Mahavni |date=March 11, 2019|website=The Daily Californian}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailynebraskan.com/news/colleges-experience-mixed-results-in-health-center-outsourcing/article_652e77b4-091c-11e2-95a6-001a4bcf6878.html|title=Colleges experience mixed results in health center outsourcing|first=Conor|last=Dunn|website=The Daily Nebraskan}}</ref> for-profit [[online program manager]]s (OPMs),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/digital-learning/blogs/technology-and-learning/opms-are-losing-battle-hearts-and-minds|title=OPMs Are Losing the Battle for Hearts and Minds &#124; Inside Higher Ed|website=www.insidehighered.com}}</ref><ref>https://www.insidehighered.com/digital-learning/article/2018/06/04/shakeout-coming-online-program-management-companies,</ref> privatized housing,<ref>https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-06-07/texas-a-m-and-oklahoma-luxury-dorms-stumble-amid-sticker-shock</ref> private student loans, student loan servicers, and [[Human Capital Contract]]s, also known as [[income share agreement]]s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.edsurge.com/news/2018-08-21-income-share-agreement-providers-want-to-woo-higher-ed-but-will-it-work|title=Income-Share Agreement Providers Want to Woo Higher Ed. But Will It Work? - EdSurge News|date=August 21, 2018|website=EdSurge}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.edsurge.com/news/2019-04-05-wall-street-wants-in-on-income-share-agreements | title=Wall Street Wants in on Income-Share Agreements - EdSurge News| date=April 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==For-profit colleges==\n\nFor-profit colleges have frequently offered career-oriented curricula including [[Cooking school|culinary arts]], business and technology (including [[coding bootcamp]]s), and health care. These institutions have a long history in the US, and grew rapidly from 1972 to 2009, until their current enrollment and revenue declines.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2017/12/20/national-enrollments-decline-sixth-straight-year-slower-rate |title = National enrollments decline for sixth straight year, but at slower rate}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://nces.ed.gov/programs/coe/indicator_cha.asp |title = The Condition of Education - Postsecondary Education - Postsecondary Students - Undergraduate Enrollment - Indicator May (2019)}}</ref> Approximately 40 percent of all for-profit college campuses have closed since 2010.<ref name=\"theintercept.com\">{{Cite web | url=https://theintercept.com/2019/04/12/betsy-devos-for-profit-colleges/ |title = Betsy DeVos Quietly Making It Easier for Dying For-Profit Schools to Rip off a Few More Students on the Way Out|date = April 12, 2019}}</ref>\nFor-profit colleges received less government scrutiny by the Republican-controlled Senate after 2014, but were recognized as a problem by the US House Subcommittee on Labor, Health and Human Services, Education and Related Agencies in 2019.<ref name=courthousenews>{{Cite web | url=https://www.courthousenews.com/house-panel-takes-up-oversight-of-for-profit-schools |title = House Panel Takes up Oversight of For-Profit Schools|date = March 12, 2019}}</ref> Significant business failures and closings from 2015 to 2019 include [[Corinthian Colleges]], [[ITT Technical Institute]], [[Education Management Corporation]], and [[Education Corporation of America]].<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://campustechnology.com/articles/2019/03/01/murray-wants-higher-ed-act-reauthorization-to-tackle-affordability.aspx | title=Murray Wants Higher ed Act Reauthorization to Tackle Affordability -}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2019/03/01/senator-patty-murray-says-higher-education-legislation-must-focus-college | title=Senator Patty Murray says higher education legislation must focus on college affordability}}</ref> The [[Dream Center]]'s collapse in 2018-2019 also included schools that had historically been for-profit institutions.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{Cite journal | url=https://www.chronicle.com/article/The-Nightmarish-End-of-the/245855 |title = The Nightmarish End of the Dream Center's Higher-Ed Empire|journal = The Chronicle of Higher Education|date = March 9, 2019}}</ref><ref>https://nonprofitquarterly.org/2015/02/26/blurred-lines-structural-movements-of-universities-between-for-profit-nonprofit-and-other-hybrids/</ref>Since 2015, [[student loan debt]] groups, including the [[Debt Collective]] and I Am Ai, have provided advocacy and support for students and former students of failing schools.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/><ref name=\"theguardian.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/money/2014/sep/17/occupy-activists-student-debt-corinthian-colleges|title=Occupy activists abolish $3.85m in Corinthian Colleges students' loan debt|first=Jana|last=Kasperkevic|date=September 17, 2014|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref>\n\n==Blurring between for-profit and non-profit==\n\nPublic colleges and universities have increasingly relied on for-profit businesses for a number of products and services, including food service. For example, Sodexo and Aramark are two major for-profit food servicers. As for-profit colleges face declining enrollment, there has been a blurring between for-profit and non-profit colleges.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2015/02/23/nonprofit-university-becomes-benefit-corporation-further-blurring-profit-divide|title=Nonprofit university becomes a 'benefit corporation,' further blurring for-profit divide|website=www.insidehighered.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cappsonline.org/higher-ed-for-profit-or-not-the-lines-are-blurring/|title=Higher Ed: For Profit or Not? The Lines Are Blurring \u2026 \u2013 CAPPS}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/digital-learning/article/2019/01/09/purdue-prepares-online-expansion-support-newly-acquired-profit|title=Purdue prepares online expansion with support from newly acquired for-profit &#124; Inside Higher Ed|website=www.insidehighered.com}}</ref> For-profit Online Program Managers (OPMs) include [[2U (company)|2U]], [[Academic Partnerships]], [[Bisk Education(company)|Bisk Education]], [[Noodle Partners]], [[Pearson Education]] (Embanet), and [[Wiley (publisher)]](Education Solutions).\n<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/education/archive/2016/06/for-profit-companies-nonprofit-colleges/485930/|title=How Five Companies Are Gaining Millions in Profit Off Education at Nonprofit Schools|first=Derek|last=Newton|date=June 7, 2016|website=The Atlantic}}</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceC\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/digital-learning/article/2018/06/04/shakeout-coming-online-program-management-companies|title=Is a shakeout coming for online program management companies? &#124; Inside Higher Ed|website=www.insidehighered.com}}</ref> In 2018, there were more than two dozen OPMs.<ref name=\"ReferenceC\"/> Human capital contracts, also known as [[Income Share Agreement]]s (ISAs) may also be seen as for-profit vehicles.<ref>http://www.aei.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/Students-Future-as-Investments.pdf</ref>\n\n==History of for-profit higher education==\n\n===Origins===\nFor-profit colleges in the US have their origins in the Colonial Era.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=B0UGX-10hrcC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Higher+ed.+inc.#v=onepage&q=Higher%20ed.%20inc.&f=false|title=Higher Ed, Inc.|accessdate=June 14, 2015|isbn=9780801874475|last1=Ruch|first1=Richard S.|date=August 11, 2003}}</ref><ref name=\"jhu\">{{cite web|url=https://jhupbooks.press.jhu.edu/content/diploma-mills|publisher=jhupbooks.press.jhu.edu|title=Diploma Mills|accessdate=February 18, 2017}}</ref>According to AJ Angulo, 19th century for-profit colleges offering practical skills expanded across the United States, meeting a demand for practical job training. In the 1830s and 1840s, proprietary business schools in Boston, Brooklyn, and Philadelphia offered penmanship and accounting classes. The expansion continued in the 1850s and 1860s, to Chicago, New Orleans, Memphis, and San Jose. Angulo estimated that there were 2,000 for-profit colleges with more than 240,000 students during the period, if fly-by-night schools were included.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.processhistory.org/angulo-for-profit-colleges/|title=For-Profit Colleges in American History|date=June 20, 2017}}</ref> The [[Bryant & Stratton]] Chain School grew to about 50 schools by 1864.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ohiohistorycentral.org/w/Bryant_%26_Stratton_Chain_of_Business_Schools|title=Bryant & Stratton Chain of Business Schools - Ohio History Central|website=ohiohistorycentral.org}}</ref>The decline of proprietary colleges was aided by the [[Smith-Hughes Act]] of 1917. Also known as the National Vocational Education Act, this legislation funded public vocational education.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.google.com/search?q=isbn:1475826079|title=isbn:1475826079 - Google Search|website=www.google.com}}</ref>\n\n===Growth: (1940s to 2009)===\nIn the 1940s, \"fly-by-night commercial vocational 'schools' sprang up to collect veterans' tuition grants\" due to the newly created [[GI Bill]]'s lax requirements and limited oversight to prevent such abuses.<ref name=\"prospect\">{{cite web|url=http://prospect.org/article/delivering-young-families-resonance-gi-bill|publisher=prospect.org|title=Delivering for Young Families: The Resonance of the GI Bill|accessdate=February 18, 2017}}</ref>For-profit colleges grew significantly from 1972 to 1976, after the [[Higher Education Act of 1965]], part of [[President Lyndon Johnson]]'s \"[[Great Society]]\" of progressive reforms, was amended so that for-profit colleges could receive US government funds, to include [[Pell Grants]] and federal student loans.<ref name=\"digilib.gmu.edu\"/><ref name=\"scholarship.law.duke.edu\">{{cite web|url=http://scholarship.law.duke.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=3355&context=dlj |format=PDF |title=SUBPRIME EDUCATION: FOR-PROFIT COLLEGES AND THE PROBLEM WITH TITLE IV FEDERAL STUDENT AID |publisher=Scholarship.law.duke.edu |accessdate=July 4, 2015}}</ref> From 1974 to 1986, for-profit colleges share of Pell Grants rose from 7 percent to 21 percent, even though for-profit colleges only enrolled 5 percent of all higher education students.<ref name=\"books.google.com\"/> In the 1980s, public higher education was also becoming increasingly privatized. In the late 1980s, Secretary of Education [[William Bennett]] hired an outside firm, Pelavin and Associates, to investigate the problems with for-profit higher education. The investigators found widespread abuses across the industry.<ref name=\"books.google.com\"/>  \n\nFrom 1989 to the mid-1990s, Stephen Blair, a former Department of Education official, led for-profit college industry's lobbying campaign in Washington, DC. Blair gathered funds to combat the Pelavin report. Blair recruited politicians [[Bob Beckel]], Patty Sullivan, and [[Haley Barbour]] to sell their cause to Democrats and Republicans.<ref name=\"books.google.com\"/> In 1992, the Higher Education Act was amended to include the 85\u201315 rule, which limited federal funding to 85 percent of a school's funding. Supporters of the 85\u201315 rule argued that the measure was necessary to stem fraudulent and abusive practices at for-profit colleges, and that it might restore some market incentive to education.<ref name=\"congressionalresearch\">{{cite web|url=http://congressionalresearch.com/RL32182/document.php?study=Institutional+Eligibility+and+the+Higher+Education+Act+Legislative+History+of+the+90%20percent2F10+Rule+and+Its+Current+Status|publisher=congressionalresearch.com|title=Institutional Eligibility and the Higher Education Act: Legislative History of the 90/10 Rule and Its Current Status|accessdate=February 18, 2017}}</ref> At the time, former Career College Association lobbyist Patty Sullivan estimated that 35 or 40 percent of for-profit colleges engaged in fraud.<ref name=\"books.google.com\"/> In 1993, the 85\u201315 rule was shelved after complaints were made to the Department of Education.<ref name=\"edweek\">{{cite web|url=http://www.edweek.org/ew/articles/1993/12/08/14aid.h13.html|title=Planned Higher-Ed. Rules Shelved After Complaints |work=Education Week|accessdate=February 18, 2017}}</ref> In 1994, the US House of Representatives voted to allow a one-year delay in regulations scheduled to halt federal student aid for many trade schools. Tony Calandro, vice president of government affairs for the [[Career College Association]] (CCA), said that enforcement of the 85\u201315 rule would have forced 30 percent of the nation's 4,000 private trade schools to close.<ref name=\"nytimes\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/06/30/us/trade-schools-win-reprieve-on-aid-cutoff.html|title=Trade Schools Win Reprieve on Aid Cutoff |work=New York Times|accessdate=February 18, 2017}}</ref>From the late 1980s to the mid-1990s, Senator [[Sam Nunn]] led for more scrutiny of for-profit colleges. The General Accounting Office also found that 135 for-profit colleges contributed to 54% of all student loan defaults. According to the US Department of Education, the number of for-profit colleges rose from about 200 in 1986 to nearly 1,000 in 2007.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=nVM3tUhQeqUC&pg=PA68&dq=for-profot+colleges+and+universities#v=onepage&q=for-profot%20colleges%20and%20universities&f=false|title=For-Profit Colleges and Universities|accessdate=June 14, 2015|isbn=9781579225285|last1=Hentschke|first1=Guilbert C.|last2=Lechuga|first2=Vicente M.|last3=Tierney|first3=William G.|date=March 12, 2012}}</ref> \n\nFrom 1990 to 2009, for-profit colleges gained significant ground over public colleges, growing to 11.8 percent of all undergraduates.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2010/08/26/enroll|title=3 Million and Counting|work=Inside Higher Ed|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref> For-profit college enrollment grew between 1998 and 2009, after the 1998 reauthorization of the Higher Education Act resulted in more deregulation. Secretary of Education [[Richard W. Riley]] appointed former Career College's Association President Stephen J. Blair as the Liaison for Proprietary Institutions.<ref name=\"ed2\">{{cite web|url=https://ifap.ed.gov/eannouncements/doc0984_bodyoftext.htm|publisher=ifap.ed.gov|title=eannouncements/doc0984_bodyoftext|accessdate=February 18, 2017}}</ref> The industry also grew in the wake of state budget cuts, stagnation, and austerity in higher education funding that grew more visible in the 1980s and 1990s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news.cornell.edu/stories/2014/04/suzanne-mettler-sees-higher-ed-caste-system|title=Suzanne Mettler sees higher ed 'caste system' |work=Cornell Chronicle|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref> In the wake of deregulation and the growth of for-profit colleges, [[initial public offerings]] of [[Devry]], [[ITT Educational Services]], [[Apollo Education Group]], [[Corinthian Colleges]], and [[Career Education Corporation]] occurred between 1991 and 1998. For-profit colleges had become \"the darlings of Wall Street.\"<ref name=\"books.google.com\"/> Also the advent of the [[Internet]] in the 1990s has helped increase enrollment as many of the for-profit colleges were pioneers in [[online education]].<ref name=\"books.google.com\"/> In 2005, Department of Education Inspector General John B. Higgins reported that 74% of all institutional fraud investigations were for-profit colleges.<ref name=\"books.google.com\"/> The ''Los Angeles Times'' briefly described the role of Wall Street money in the growth of for-profit colleges.<ref name=\"latimes\">{{cite web|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2003/sep/15/business/fi-corinthian15|work=Los Angeles Times|title=Operating Career College Lucrative Vocation for CEO |accessdate=February 18, 2017|date=September 15, 2003}}</ref> Increased capitalization of for-profit colleges occurred after banks such as [[Goldman Sachs]] and [[Wells Fargo]] and investment firms and hedge funds such as [[Blum Capital Partners]] and [[Warburg Pincus]] became large institutional investors in this industry.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/10/14/goldman-sachs-for-profit-college_n_997409.html|title=With Goldman's Foray Into Higher Education, A Predatory Pursuit Of Students And Revenues|work=The Huffington Post|accessdate=June 14, 2015|date=October 14, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"huffingtonpost\">{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/davidhalperin/who-owns-the-awful-corint_b_4101323.html|title=Who Owns The Awful Corinthian Colleges? Wells Fargo, Marc Morial, Pension Funds|work=The Huffington Post|accessdate=June 14, 2015|date=October 15, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sandiegoreader.com/weblogs/news-ticker/2012/jul/14/bridgepoint-huge-profits-but-possibly-no-future/#|title=Bridgepoint: Huge Profits, but Possibly No Future|publisher=Sandiegoreader.com|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"educationdive.com\">{{Cite web | url=https://www.educationdive.com/news/private-equitys-role-in-the-rise-and-fall-of-for-profit-colleges/554077/ |title = Private equity's role in the rise \u2014 and fall \u2014 of for-profit colleges}}</ref> Private equity in for-profit education has been associated with higher costs to students and declining outcomes: less spent on education, more [[student loan debt]] and lower student loan repayment rates, lower graduation rates, and lower earnings for graduates.<ref name=\"educationdive.com\"/>\n\n====2009\u20132016====\nIn the 2009\u20132010 academic year, for-profit higher education corporations received $32 billion in [[Title IV]] funding\u2014more than 20% of all federal aid.<ref name=\"scholarship.law.duke.edu\"/> For-profit colleges get approximately 70% of their funds from Title IV programs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://projectonstudentdebt.org/files/pub/90-10_Q_and_A_Oct_2013_Update.pdf |title=Search |publisher=Projectonstudentdebt.org|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref> However, some colleges got more than 80% of their funds from Title IV.<ref name=\"help.senate.gov\"/> In 2010, as America's largest university, [[University of Phoenix]], had an enrollment of 470,000 students and annual revenues approaching $5 billion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://investors.apollo.edu/phoenix.zhtml?c=79624&p=irol-reportsannual|title=Annual Reports &#124; Apollo Education Group}}</ref>\n\n===Decline in enrollment, revenues, and employees (2010\u2013present)===\n\n{| class=\"For-profit enrollment in US higher education (National Center for Education Statistics)\"\n|-\n! Fall/Year !!!!!! Enrollment !!!!Revenues!!!! Employees!!!! \n|-\n| 2010   |||||| 2,430,657||||29,603,059,000|||| 295,476\n|-\n| 2011   |||||| 2,368,440 ||||33,889,758,000|||| 288,882\n|-\n| 2012   |||||| 2,174,457 |||| 32,196111,000 |||| 295,887\n|-\n| 2013   ||||||2,000,883||||29,643,714,000 |||| 258,098\n|-\n| 2014   ||||||1,883,199 ||||27,310,167,000 |||| 241,134\n|-\n| 2015   ||||||1,629,393||||24,007,022,000 |||| 214,656\n|-\n| 2016   ||||||1,437,452||||20,804,128,000|||| 191,083\n|-\n| 2017   ||||||1,345,633||||19,446,382,000|||| 176,441\n|}\n\nUnder the Obama administration (2009\u20132017), for-profit colleges received greater scrutiny and negative attention from the US government. State Attorneys General, the media, and scholars also investigated these schools.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Armour|first1=Stephanie|last2=Zibel|first2=Alan|title=For-Profit College Probe Expands|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052702303819704579318872286744010|accessdate=January 15, 2015|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|date=January 13, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"theatlantic.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/education/archive/2014/04/how-higher-ed-contributes-to-inequality/360407/|title=How Higher Ed Contributes to Inequality|work=The Atlantic|accessdate=June 14, 2015|date=April 9, 2014}}</ref> For-profit school enrollment reached its peak in 2009 and showed major declines by 2011.<ref name=\"ed3\">{{cite web|url=http://nces.ed.gov/programs/coe/indicator_cha.asp|publisher=nces.ed.gov|title=The Condition of Education - Participation in Education - Postsecondary - Undergraduate Enrollment - Indicator May (2016)|accessdate=February 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Fain|first1=Paul|title=More Selective For-Profits|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2011/11/11/enrollments-tumble-profit-colleges|work=[[Inside Higher Ed]]|accessdate=January 15, 2015|date=November 11, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2014/05/15/new-data-show-slowing-national-enrollment-decline|title=New data show slowing national enrollment decline |work=Inside Higher Ed|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.educationdive.com/news/how-might-these-6-for-profit-institutions-fare-in-2015/346788/|title=How might these 6 for-profit institutions fare in 2015?|date=December 31, 2014|work=Education Dive|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref> Two companies, [[Corinthian Colleges]] (which included [[Heald College]], [[Everest College]], and [[Wyotech]]) and [[Education Management Corporation]] (which included the [[Art Institutes]], [[Argosy University]], and [[South University]]) faced enrollment declines and major financial trouble in 2014 and 2015;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/ed/2014/12/24/370979991/an-update-on-for-profit-colleges|title=An Update On For-Profit Colleges|date=December 24, 2014|publisher=NPR|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref> Corinthian Colleges and Education Management are out of business (closed). [[University of Phoenix]], a subsidiary of [[Apollo Global Management]], has also seen a 70% drop in enrollment since its peak.{{citation needed|date=October 2019}}\n\nAccording to the 2012 Harkin Report and ''[[The New York Times]]'', students at for-profit colleges made up \"13 percent of the nation's college enrollment, but account for about 47 percent of the defaults on loans. About 96 percent of students at for-profit schools take out loans, compared with about 13 percent at community colleges and 48 percent at four-year public universities.\"<ref name=\"nytimes2\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/07/30/education/harkin-report-condemns-for-profit-colleges.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0 |title=Harkin Report Condemns For-Profit Colleges |access-date=February 18, 2017 |newspaper=The New York Times |date=July 29, 2012 |last1=Lewin |first1=Tamar}}</ref><ref name=\"help.senate.gov\">{{cite web|url=http://www.help.senate.gov/imo/media/for_profit_report/PartI-PartIII-SelectedAppendixes.pdf |title=For Profit Higher Education: The Failure to Safeguard the Federal Investment and Ensure Student Success |publisher=Help.senate.gov |accessdate=July 4, 2015}}</ref> [[Gary Trudeau]] satirized for-profit education in his comic strip ''[[Doonesbury]]'', by showing corruption at a fictionalized school, [[Walden College]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.insidehighered.com/blogs/technology-and-learning/doonesbury-profit-higher-ed |title=Doonesbury on For-Profit Higher ed |work=Inside Higher Ed}}</ref>\n\nA 2014 report by The Institute for College Access and Success showed that the likelihood of a student defaulting was three times more likely at a for-profit college than a 4-year public or non-profit college and almost four times more likely than a community college.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://ticas.org/content/pub/despite-lower-rates-more-650000-defaulted-federal-student-loans-0 |title=Despite Lower Rates, More Than 650,000 Defaulted on Federal Student Loans &#124; The Institute For College Access and Success |publisher=Ticas.org |date=September 24, 2014 |accessdate=July 4, 2015}}</ref> The [[United States Department of Veterans Affairs|Department of Veterans Affairs]] reported that veterans using the [[GI Bill]] for education submitted more complaints about for-profit colleges, particularly [[University of Phoenix]], [[ITT Technical Institute]], [[Devry University]], and [[Colorado Technical University]], than their public or private non-profit counterparts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.benefits.va.gov/GIBILL/docs/Overview_GI+Bill_Feedback+System_CY14.pdf|title=404 - Page Not Found - Veterans Benefits Administration|website=www.benefits.va.gov}}</ref> In September 2014, on his TV show ''Last Week Tonight'', [[John Oliver]] discussed [[student debt]] and for-profit colleges, calling them \"a first-class education in the depths of human depravity.\"<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/09/08/john-oliver-student-debt_n_5784266.html | title=John Oliver on For-Profit Schools: 'A First-Class Education in the Depths of Human Depravity'| date=September 8, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, [[Corinthian Colleges]] filed for bankruptcy and all of its [[Heald College]] campuses were closed.<ref name=\"latimes2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-corinthian-shutdown-20150427-story.html|work=Los Angeles Times|title=Corinthian closing its last schools; 10,000 California students displaced |accessdate=February 18, 2017|date=April 27, 2015}}</ref> In 2016, all [[Westwood College]] campuses were closed.<ref name=\"insidehighered.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/quicktakes/2016/01/29/profit-westwood-college-announces-closing|work=Inside Higher Ed|title=For-Profit Westwood College Announces Closing|accessdate=February 18, 2017}}</ref> [[Le Cordon Bleu]] was also in the process of closing all of its campuses.<ref name=\"insidehighered2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/quicktakes/2015/12/17/career-ed-closing-down-le-cordon-bleu-operations|work=Inside Higher Ed|title=Career Ed Closing Down Le Cordon Bleu Operations|accessdate=February 18, 2017}}</ref> [[ITT Technical Institute]]<ref name=\"insidehighered3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/quicktakes/2015/10/19/itt-tech-suspends-enrollment-several-campuses|work=Inside Higher Ed|title=ITT Tech Suspends Enrollment at Several Campuses|accessdate=February 18, 2017}}</ref> and [[Devry]]<ref name=\"chicagotribune\">{{cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/business/ct-devry-closings-0425-biz-20150424-story.html|title=DeVry to close some out-of-state campuses |work=Chicago Tribune|accessdate=February 18, 2017}}</ref> also closed multiple campuses. In November 2015, the CBS drama [[The Good Wife]], addressed students at Colosseum University, a fictionalized for-profit college that used deceptive recruiting tactics. The episode included mention of accreditation and the 90\u201310 rule.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2015/11/03/good-wife-tackles-profit-colleges-and-student-debt |title='The Good Wife' tackles for-profit colleges and student debt|work=Inside Higher Ed}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' reported that more than 180 for-profit college campuses had closed between 2014 and 2016.<ref name=\"wsj\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/obama-empties-innovative-classrooms-1466635226|work=The Wall Street Journal|author=Finley, Alyssa|title=Obama Empties Innovative Classrooms|date=June 22, 2016|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20160625094259/http://www.wsj.com/articles/obama-empties-innovative-classrooms-1466635226|archivedate=June 25, 2016|accessdate=February 18, 2017}}</ref> For-profit college enrollment dropped about 15% in 2016, a 165,000 decline.<ref name=\"hechingerreport2\">{{cite web|url=http://hechingerreport.org/college-university-enrollment-fifth-straight-year/|title=College and university enrollment is down for fifth straight year |work=The Hechinger Report|accessdate=February 18, 2017|date=December 19, 2016}}</ref> Enrollment at University of Phoenix chain fell 22%, which was a 70% loss since 2010. [[DeVry University]] reported a 23% decline in 2016. Hondros College, a nursing school chain, dropped 14%.<ref name=\"chicagotribune2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/business/ct-for-profit-colleges-enrollment-slide-20160922-story.html|title=Amid scrutiny, for-profit colleges see enrollment slide |work=Chicago Tribune|accessdate=February 18, 2017}}</ref> In June 2016, Education Management announced that it was planning to close all 25 [[Brown Mackie College]] campuses. In September 2016, [[ITT Technical Institute]] closed all of its campuses. In September 2016, the [[US Department of Education]] stripped [[ACICS]] of its accreditation powers. Research by [[United States Department of the Treasury|Treasury Department]] economist Nicholas Turner and [[George Washington University]] economist Stephanie Riegg Cellini found that students who attended for-profit colleges would have been better off not going to college at all, or attending a [[community college]] (which are non-profit); put differently, the for-profit colleges left students worse off than they were when they started. The [[National Bureau of Economic Research]] paper was based on an analysis of 567,000 students who attended for-profit colleges from 2006 to 2008. More than 80% carried [[student loan debt]].<ref name=\"washingtonpost\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/wonk/wp/2016/05/31/a-popular-college-investment-promised-students-a-career-but-didnt-pay-off/|title=A popular college investment promised students a career, but didn't pay off |work=The Washington Post|accessdate=February 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====2017\u20132019====\nIn 2017, the advocacy group the [[Debt Collective]] created its own, unofficial \"Defense to Repayment App\" that allows former students of schools accused of fraud to pursue debt cancellation.<ref name=\"herokuapp\">{{cite web|url=https://debt-is.herokuapp.com/defense-to-repayment|publisher=debt-is.herokuapp.com|title=The Debt Collective|accessdate=February 18, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160131074022/http://debt-is.herokuapp.com/defense-to-repayment|archive-date=January 31, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> The applications generated through the Debt Collective's online form were cited by the Department of Education in a Federal Register notice, which said that \"a need for a clearer process for potential claimants\" arose due to the submission of over 1000 defense to repayment claims by \"a building debt activism movement\".<ref name=\"ed\">{{cite web|url=https://studentaid.ed.gov/sa/repay-loans/forgiveness-cancellation#closed-school|publisher=studentaid.ed.gov|title=Forgiveness, Cancellation, and Discharge &#124; Federal Student Aid|accessdate=February 18, 2017}}</ref> In October 2017, [[Strayer University]] and [[Capella University]] agreed to merge as Strategic Education,<ref name=\"insidehighered.com1\"/> officially completing the merger in August 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.startribune.com/capella-and-strayer-complete-1-2-billion-merger-take-new-name-as-strategic-education/489752481/|title=Capella and Strayer complete merger, shares soar nearly 12 percent on strong Q2 results|website=Star Tribune}}</ref> Since 2017, the [[Donald Trump administration]] and Secretary of Education [[Betsy DeVos]] have accused the government of regulatory overreach and have loosened regulations.<ref name=\"consumerist.com\">{{cite web|url=https://consumerist.com/2017/08/17/education-secretary-betsy-devos-will-allow-for-profit-schools-to-continue-offering-programs-that-dont-meet-standards/|title=Education Secretary Betsy DeVos Will Allow For-Profit Schools To Continue Offering Programs That Don't Meet Standards|date=August 17, 2017|website=Consumerist.com|access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref> Donald Trump once opened a for profit college, the [[Trump University]]. It came under investigation for criminal activity, faced multiple lawsuits, and failed within five years.\n\nIn 2017 and 2018, all [[Le Cordon Bleu]] schools were in the process of closing.<ref name=\"sec2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1046568/000156459016027351/ceco-10q_20160930.htm|publisher=sec.gov|title=ceco-10q_20160930.htm|accessdate=February 18, 2017}}</ref> At least 19 Art Institutes were also expected to close.<ref name=\"wtae\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wtae.com/article/many-art-institute-employees-laid-off-in-pittsburgh/7479864|publisher=wtae.com|title=Many Art Institute employees laid off in Pittsburgh|date=May 5, 2016|accessdate=February 18, 2017}}</ref> Education Management Corporation sold its remaining schools to the non-profit Dream Foundation and [[Purdue University]] proposed purchasing Kaplan University.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/mollyhensleyclancy/for-1-purdue-university-will-acquire-a-massive-for-profit|title=Here's Why Purdue University Is Buying A Massive For-Profit College For $1|website=Buzzfeed|access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref> Atalem sold its declining DeVry University and the Keller School of Management to Cogswell Education, a division of Palm Ventures.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/mollyhensleyclancy/devry-university-will-be-sold-to-a-tiny-college-company|title=Troubled DeVry University Gets Sold Off For A Pittance|first=Molly|last=Hensley-Clancy|website=BuzzFeed|access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref> In 2018, the [[National Center for Education Statistics]] reported that the 12-year [[student loan default]] rate for-profit colleges was 52 percent.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/business/ct-biz-for-profit-college-loan-default0-20171005-story.html|title=More than half of students at for-profit colleges defaulted on loans, study finds|first=Maria|last=Danilova|website=ChicagoTribune.com|access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref> The 12-year student loan default rate for [[African Americans]] going to for-profit colleges was reported to be 65.7 percent.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-10-11/black-americans-twice-as-likely-as-whites-to-default-on-student-debt|title=Black Americans Twice as Likely as Whites to Default on Student Debt|date=October 11, 2017|access-date=January 1, 2018|publisher=Bloomberg}}</ref> In 2018, the documentary Fail State chronicled the boom and bust of for-profit colleges, highlighting the abuses that led to their downfall.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.texasobserver.org/fail-state-delves-shadowy-world-profit-colleges/|title='Fail State' Delves into the Shadowy World of For-Profit Colleges|author=|date=October 27, 2017|website=Texas Observer}}</ref> In June 2018, Inside Higher Education published \"A Tipping Point for OPM?\" which stated that most experts thought a \"shakeout\" would be occurring among Online Program Managers.<ref name=\"ReferenceC\"/> On August 10, 2018, US Education Secretary Betsy Devos scrapped a rule issued by the US Department of Education in 2010 which would have forced for-profit colleges to prove that the students they enroll are able to attain \"gainful employment.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/grade-point/wp/2018/08/10/trumps-education-department-moves-to-rescind-rule-aimed-at-for-profit-schools/|title=Trump's Education Department moves to rescind rule aimed at for-profit schools|website=Washington Post}}</ref><ref name=july2019>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/10/us/politics/betsy-devos-for-profit-colleges.html|title=DeVos Ends Obama-Era Safeguards Aimed at Abuses by For-Profit Colleges|first=Erica L.|last=Green|date=August 10, 2018|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/08/10/politics/devos-obama-for-profit-college-rule/index.html|title=Betsy DeVos' rollback of Obama's for-profit college rules is almost complete|first=Katie|last=Lobosco|website=CNN}}</ref> The gainful employment policy will expire on July 1, 2019.<ref name=july2019 /><ref>https://www.10news.com/newsy/betsy-devos-wants-to-end-rules-meant-to-curb-abuse-by-some-colleges</ref> In the 30-day period before its expiration, however, the Department of Education will gather public input.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/nation/devos-proposes-rollback-of-for-profit-college-rule|title=DeVos proposes rollback of for-profit college rule|date=August 10, 2018|website=PBS NewsHour}}</ref> In September 2018, [[Education Corporation of America]] announced that they would be closing 26 campuses, which included several [[Virginia College]] campuses.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2018/09/12/profit-chain-will-close-dozens-campuses|title=For-profit chain will close dozens of campuses|website=www.insidehighered.com}}</ref> The school closed all of its schools by the end of the year.<ref name=\"usatoday.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/education/2019/03/26/how-to-choose-a-college-argosy-university-college-closing/3211480002/|title=A college closed, leaving thousands without a degree. How to keep it from happening to you|first=Chris|last=Quintana|website=USA TODAY}}</ref> In November 2018, the US Department of Education restored [[Accrediting Council for Independent Colleges and Schools]] (ACICS) as a higher education accreditor. The organization had lost its authority during the Obama administration.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2018/11/26/devos-restores-authority-profit-accreditor|title=DeVos restores authority of for-profit accreditor|website=www.insidehighered.com}}</ref>\n\nFrom December 2018 to March 2019, [[Dream Center]] Education Holdings began closing and selling off schools. DCEH was the parent company of the [[Art Institutes]], [[Argosy University]], and [[South University]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/07/business/argosy-college-art-insititutes-south-university.html|title=A College Chain Crumbles, and Millions in Student Loan Cash Disappears|first1=Stacy|last1=Cowley|first2=Erica L.|last2=Green|date=March 7, 2019|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> The [[National Student Clearinghouse]] reported that their for-profit college enrollment numbers for Fall 2018 had declined 15.1 percent from Fall 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.studentclearinghouse.org/nscblog/fall-2018-overall-postsecondary-enrollments-decreased-1-7-percent-from-last-fall/|title=Fall 2018 Overall Postsecondary Enrollments Decreased 1.7 Percent from Last Fall|first=N. S. C.|last=Blog|date=December 13, 2018}}</ref> In 2019, Argosy University closed all of its campuses. ''[[USA Today]]'' articles in March 2019 portrayed the collapse of the school as part of a trend, highlighting the losses of other for-profit colleges: [[Brown Mackie College]] (2017), [[Le Cordon Bleu]] (2017), [[Brightwood College]] (2018), [[Vatterott College]] (2018), and [[Virginia College]] (2018).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/education/2019/03/26/for-profit-college-closing-argosy-university/3271813002/|title=Trouble at for-profit colleges in 5 graphs: Here's what's happening|first=Lindsay|last=Huth|website=USA TODAY}}</ref><ref name=\"usatoday.com\" /> In a 2019 Brookings Institution report, students taking online courses at for-profit colleges were attracted to the programs for their ease of enrollment and help obtaining financial aid, but \"disappointed with the poor quality of education.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.educationdive.com/news/for-profit-online-students-drawn-by-convenience-but-left-disappointed/551721/|title=For-profit online students drawn by convenience but left 'disappointed'|website=Education Dive}}</ref><ref>https://www.brookings.edu/wp-content/uploads/2019/03/The-Failings-of-Online-For-profit-Colleges.pdf</ref> On March 16, 2019, [[National American University]] announced that ground campuses would be closed, except for Ellsworth Air Force Base and King's Bay Naval Submarine Base.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rapidcityjournal.com/news/local/nau-closing-rapid-city-other-campuses/article_617c7935-3b52-51b9-bbb1-b2a5a9b76874.html|title=NAU closing Rapid City, other campuses|first=Arielle Zionts Journal|last=staff|website=Rapid City Journal Media Group}}</ref> In April 2019, [[2U (company)|2U]] purchased Trilogy, a [[coding bootcamp]] provider, for $750 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2019/04/09/2u-buy-boot-camp-provider-trilogy-750-million|title=2U to buy boot-camp provider Trilogy for $750 million|website=www.insidehighered.com}}</ref> On April 12, 2019, Betsy DeVos was criticized for allowing five failing for-profit colleges to avoid posting a letter of credit.<ref name=\"theintercept.com\" /> On April 14, 2019, NBC News Investigates reported on for-profit colleges that target veterans. The online version mentioned [[Full Sail University]], [[Ashford University]], [[Colorado Technical University]], and [[University of Phoenix]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/politics-news/veterans-could-be-first-pay-devos-rolls-back-profit-college-n985891|title=Veterans could be first to pay as DeVos rolls back for-profit college oversight|website=NBC News}}</ref> In 2019, Accreditor WASC approved Ashford University's conversion to a non-profit. Its parent company, Zovio, however, continued to be a publicly traded for-profit college company.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Busta |first1=Hallie |title=Accreditor approves Ashford U's nonprofit conversion |url=https://www.educationdive.com/news/accreditor-approves-ashford-us-nonprofit-conversion/558781/ |website=Education Dive |accessdate=July 16, 2019}}</ref> In July 2019, 2U shares dropped more than 50 percent when it lowered its growth expectations.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Millward |first1=Wade Tyler |title=2U Stock Tumbles 54% After Company Lowers Growth Expectations for 2019 |url=https://www.edsurge.com/news/2019-07-31-2u-stock-tumbles-after-online-degree-company-lowers-growth-expectations-for-2019 |website=edsurge.com |accessdate=August 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==List of for-profit corporations and their brands==\n{{See also|List of for-profit universities and colleges}}\n\nAccording to the [[National Center for Education Statistics]], there were approximately 3,200 for-profit institutions in the US in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nces.ed.gov/pubs2016/2016112.pdf |title=Postsecondary Institutions and Cost of Attendance in 2015-16; Degrees and Other Awards Conferred, 2014\u201315; and 12-Month Enrollment, 2014\u201315 |author1=Scott A. Ginder |author2=Janice E. Kelly-Reid |author3=Farrah B. Man |date=July 2016 |access-date= February 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\nMany for-profit institutions are subsidiaries of larger companies. The following is a list of for-profit companies in the higher education sector:\n* [[Adtalem Global Education]] (owner of Chamberlain Nursing, Ross University Medical School, Ross University School of Veterinary Medicine) \n* [[Ancora Education]] (owner of Arizona Automotive Institute, Berks Technical Institute, Edge Tech Academy, International Schools, McCann School of Business & Technology, [[Miller-Motte Technical College]], [[Platt College (Oklahoma)|Platt College]], and South Texas Vocational Technical Institute)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ancoraeducation.com/our-brands|title=Our Brands :: Ancora Education|website=www.ancoraeducation.com}}</ref>\n* [[Apollo Education Group]] (a subsidiary of [[Apollo Global Management]] and parent company of [[University of Phoenix]])\n* [[American Public Education]] (owner of [[American Public University]] and [[American Military University]])\n* [[Career Education Corporation]] (includes [[Colorado Technical University]] and [[American Intercontinental University]])\n* [[Center for Excellence in Higher Education]] (includes [[CollegeAmerica]], [[Stevens-Henager College]], [[California College San Diego]], and [[Independence University]])\n* [[Connections Academy]] (a subsidiary of [[Pearson Education]])\n* [[Education Affiliates]] (includes [[Fortis College]] and Fortis Institutes)\n* [[Global University Systems]]\n* [[Graham Holdings]] (subsidiary Kaplan Higher Education is the servicer of [[Purdue University Global]])\n* [[International Education Corporation]] owns [[UEI College]], [[United Education Institute]], [[Florida Career College]] and [[US Colleges]].\n* [[JLL Partners]] (owner of [[Education Affiliates]] and [[Ross Medical Education Center]]) \n* [[K12 (company)|K12]]\n* [[Laureate Education]] (owner of [[Walden University]] and OPM for [[University of Miami]])\n* [[Lincoln Group of Schools]]\n* [[Linden Education Group]]\n* [[Nemo Investor Aggregator]] owner of [[Cortiva Institute brand]]\n*Ochsner Health System: Ochsner Clinical School\n* [[Palm Ventures]] (owner of [[DeVry University]])\n* [[Premier Education Group]] (owner of American College for Medical Careers, Branford Hall Career Institute, Harris Casel Institute, [[Harris School of Business]], Salter College, The Salter School, Salter School of Nursing, Seacoast Career Schools)\n* [[Quad Partners]] (owns [[Beckfield College]], [[Blue Cliff College]], [[Pacific College of Oriental Medicine]], [[Swedish Institute]], and [[Trillium College]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.quadpartners.com/portfolio/|title=Portfolio of Our Investments in Education &#124; Private Equity Investors}}</ref>\n* [[Strategic Education]] (merged [[Strayer]] and [[Capella University]])<ref name=\"insidehighered.com1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2017/10/30/strayer-and-capella-two-publicly-traded-profit-providers-merge|title=Strayer and Capella, two publicly traded for-profit providers, to merge|website=InsideHigherEd.com|access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[TA Associates]] (owner of [[Full Sail University]])\n* [[Universal Technical Institute]]\n* [[Zovio]] (Owner of [[Ashford University]] and [[Fullstack Academy]], contract with [[University of San Diego]] for cybersecurity bootcamp)\n\n[[Laureate Education]]<ref name=\"bloomberg\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2014-01-06/clinton-pitches-kkr-backed-college-chain-amid-controversy|title=Clinton Pitches KKR-Backed College Chain Amid Controversy|author=Mina Kimes|date=February 4, 2014|work=Bloomberg.com|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref> and [[Apollo Education Group]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.apollo.edu/about/our-history|title=Our History - Apollo Education Group|publisher=Apollo.edu|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref> have become powerful international education corporations. Apollo Education Group is now part of Apollo Global Management. Laureate, the largest US-based for-profit higher educator, was once reported to have more than one million students worldwide, in North America, Latin America, Europe, the Middle East, Africa, and Asia Pacific.<ref name=\"sec\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/912766/000104746916013340/a2227130zs-1a.htm|publisher=sec.gov|title=Archives/edgar/data/912766/000104746916013340/a2227130zs-1a|accessdate=February 18, 2017}}</ref> Former President of the United States [[Bill Clinton]] was an honorary Chancellor of the for-profit enterprise.\n\n==For-profit marketing, enrollment and lead generators==\nFor-profit colleges use lead generation companies to target potential students and to take their personal information.<ref>https://www.ftc.gov/system/files/documents/public_comments/2015/10/00016-98214.pdf</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/military-branded-websites_b_9131742|title=Military-Branded Websites Push Veterans to Troubled For-Profit Colleges|date=February 1, 2016|website=HuffPost}}</ref> However, as competition has heated up in US higher education, traditional schools have also employed them.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/views/2016/04/18/too-much-being-spent-higher-education-marketing-assault-essay|title=Too much is being spent on a higher education marketing assault (essay) &#124; Inside Higher Ed|website=www.insidehighered.com}}</ref> Lead generators use multiple strategies to find and enroll students. There are hundreds of sites on the internet that gather information for schools.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.noodle.com/articles/list-of-lead-generation-sites|title=Noodle|website=www.noodle.com}}</ref> Two of the most notable lead generators are QuinStreet and Education Dynamics.\n\n==For-profit online program managers (OPMs)==\n[[Online program manager]]s (OPMs) play an significant role in online education.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.montanakaimin.com/news/over-half-of-online-tuition-could-go-to-private-company/article_5c75ac14-5b0e-11e9-a1c9-9747a7a1d138.html|title=Over half of online tuition could go to private company|first=Cameron Kia Weix / Montana|last=Kaimin|website=Montana Kaimin}}</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceC\"/> However,the industry is feeling a great deal of economic pressure.<ref>{{cite web |last1=McKenzie |first1=Lindsay |title=A Reckoning for 2U, and OPMs? |url=http://www.insidehighered.com/digital-learning/article/2019/08/01/bad-day-2u-highlights-vulnerability-online-program-management |website=insidehighered.com |accessdate=August 3, 2019}}</ref> The largest OPM's are: 2U, Academic Partnerships, Bisk Education, Pearson Learning and Wiley Education Solutions. <ref>{{cite web |last1=Schwartz |first1=Natalie |title=Democratic congressional inquiry targets OPMs |url=https://www.educationdive.com/news/congressional-inquiry-targets-online-program-managers/571275/ |website=www.educationdive.com |accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===List of for-profit online program managers and the schools they service===\n* [[2U (company)|2U]] (services programs at [[American University]], [[Baylor University]], [[George Washington University]], [[Harvard University]], [[Pepperdine University]], [[Rice University]], [[Syracuse University]], [[University of California, Berkeley]], [[University of North Carolina]], [[University of Southern California]], and [[Washington University]].<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://2u.com/partners/ | title=Our Partners &#124; 2U}}</ref>\n* [[Academic Partnerships]] (servicer of [[University of Texas at Arlington]] and [[Florida International University]])\n* [[Bisk Education(company)|Bisk]] ([[University Alliance (US)]] is a division of Bisk, servicing [[Villanova University]], [[University of Notre Dame]]\u2019s Mendoza College of Business, [[Michigan State University]], [[Florida Institute of Technology]], [[Jacksonville University]], [[University of South Florida]], and [[New England College]]. \n* [[Cintas]] serves [[Arizona State University]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Wilen |first1=Holden |title=Former Laureate CEO Doug Becker launches another education startup |url=https://www.bizjournals.com/baltimore/news/2019/08/27/former-laureate-ceo-doug-becker-launches-another.html?ana=yahoo&yptr=yahoo |website=bizjournals.com |accessdate=September 12, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Collegis Education]]\n* [[Grand Canyon Education]] serves [[Grand Canyon University]].\n* [[HotChalk]]\n* [[iDesign]]\n* [[InStride]] (OPM for Arizona State University)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/blogs/digital-tweed/introducing-instride-asu%E2%80%99s-profit-preferred-provider-strategy-growing-online|title=Introducing InStride, ASU's For-Profit, Preferred Provider Strategy for Growing Online Enrollments &#124; Inside Higher Ed|website=www.insidehighered.com}}</ref>\n* [[Kaplan Higher Education]] (servicer of [[Purdue University Global]] and the [[Purdue University]] system)\n* [[Laureate Education]] serves University of Miami graduate programs.\n* [[Noodle Partners]] servicing University of Michigan (Ross and Nursing), Harvard (Kennedy School), University of Pittsburgh (Health Informatics and Physical Therapy), Boston College, Tulane, University of Virginia, Southern Methodist University, New York University, Virginia Commonwealth University, and University of Tennessee.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kim |first1=Joshua |title=Getting My Head Around Noodle Partners |url=http://www.insidehighered.com/blogs/technology-and-learning/getting-my-head-around-noodle-partners |website=Inside Higher Education |accessdate=November 11, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Pearson Education]] (Embanet) partner schools include [[University of Southern California]], [[Vanderbilt University]] School of Nursing, [[Wake Forest University]], [[Brandeis University]], [[Wake Forest University]], [[Case Western Reserve]], [[George Washington University]], [[Boston University]], [[Pepperdine University]], [[University of Florida]], [[Northeastern University]], [[Howard University]], [[Washington State University]], [[University of San Francisco]], [[Ohio University]], [[University of Arizona]], [[New Jersey Institute of Technology]], [[University of Alabama, Birmingham]], [[University of Cincinnati]], [[University of Illinois, Chicago]], [[Marysville University]], [[Kent State University]], and [[Portland State University]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Our Partners |website=http://ec.cratco.com/our-partners/our-academic-partners |publisher=Pearson |accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Wiley (publisher)]](Education Solutions) servicing Northern Illinois University,<ref>https://seekingalpha.com/article/4269667-john-wiley-and-sons-inc-jw-ceo-brian-napack-q4-2019-results-earnings-call-transcript?part=single</ref> Michigan State University<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://seekingalpha.com/news/3444852-wiley-in-deal-michigan-state-for-online-programs|title=Wiley in deal with Michigan State for online programs|first=Jason|last=Aycock|date=March 21, 2019|website=Seeking Alpha}}</ref>\n\n==Coding bootcamps==\nIn 2019, [[coding bootcamp]]s remain popular. However, there may already be an oversupply of graduates and some coding bootcamps have already closed.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/24/technology/coding-boot-camps-close.html |title = As Coding Boot Camps Close, the Field Faces a Reality Check|newspaper = The New York Times|date = August 24, 2017|last1 = Lohr|first1 = Steve}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"cnbc.com\">{{Cite web | url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/04/08/suzy-welch-the-only-2-reasons-you-should-learn-to-code.html |title = Suzy Welch: The only 2 reasons you should drop everything and learn to code|date = April 9, 2019}}</ref>\n<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://techcrunch.com/2018/10/04/as-some-pricey-coding-camps-fade-away-codecademy-barrels-ahead-with-affordable-paid-offerings-and-a-new-mobile-app/ |title = As some pricey coding camps fade away, Codecademy barrels ahead with affordable paid offerings and a new mobile app}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=http://hackeducation.com/2017/07/22/bootcamp-bust |title = Why Are Coding Bootcamps Going Out of Business?|date = July 22, 2017}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"cnbc.com\"/>\n\n==Student loan servicers==\nFor-profit student loan servicers have included [[Sallie Mae]], [[Navient]], and [[Nelnet]].\n\n==Politics and political lobbying==\nPolitics and lobbying play a significant part in the history of US for-profit school growth.<ref name=\"republicreport\">{{cite web|url=https://www.republicreport.org/2016/friends-in-high-places-who-endorses-americas-troubled-for-profit-colleges/|publisher=republicreport.org|title=Friends In High Places: Who Endorses America's Troubled For-Profit Colleges? &#8211; Republic Report|accessdate=February 18, 2017|date=June 21, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"books.google.com\">{{cite book|title=Diploma Mills: How For-Profit Colleges Stiffed Students, Taxpayers, and the American Dream|author=Angulo, A.J.|date=2016|publisher=Johns Hopkins University Press|isbn=9781421420073|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Q8qnCwAAQBAJ&pg=PR4|accessdate=February 18, 2017}}</ref> The for-profit education industry has spent more than $40 million on lobbying from 2007 to 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/08/30/for-profit-colleges-lobbying_n_1842507.html|title=For-Profit Colleges Spending Millions On Lobbying, Nearly $40 Million Since 2007|work=The Huffington Post|accessdate=June 14, 2015|date=August 30, 2012}}</ref> and $36 million since 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.opensecrets.org/industries/lobbying.php?cycle=2014&ind=H5300 |title=For-profit Education: Lobbying, 2014 |publisher=OpenSecrets.org |date= |accessdate=July 2, 2015}}</ref> For-profit education lobbying grew from $83,000 in 1990 to approximately $4.5 million in its peak year of 2012.<ref name=\"opensecrets\">{{cite web|url=https://www.opensecrets.org/industries/totals.php?cycle=2016&ind=H5300|publisher=opensecrets.org|title=For-profit Education: Long-Term Contribution Trends &#124; OpenSecrets|accessdate=February 18, 2017}}</ref>The most significant industry lobby is Career Education Colleges and Universities (CECU), previously known as The [[Association of Private Sector Colleges and Universities]] (ASPCU). Before 2010, the organization was known as the [[Career College Association]].<ref name=\"hechingerreport\">{{cite web|url=http://hechingerreport.org/seeking-fresh-start-battered-profit-colleges-give-new-name/|publisher=hechingerreport.org|title=Seeking a fresh start, battered for-profit colleges give themselves a new name - The Hechinger Report|accessdate=February 18, 2017|date=June 6, 2016}}</ref> The [[Cato Institute]]'s [[Center for Educational Freedom]] also supports for-profit higher education.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/posteverything/wp/2015/01/13/even-for-profit-universities-are-better-than-americas-terrible-community-colleges/|title=Even for-profit universities are better than America's terrible community colleges|author=Neal McCluskey|date=January 13, 2015|work=Washington Post|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"stripes.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.stripes.com/opinion/how-for-profits-beat-community-colleges-1.324621 |accessdate=January 19, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150120151645/http://www.stripes.com/opinion/how-for-profits-beat-community-colleges-1.324621 |archivedate=January 20, 2015|title=How for-profits beat community colleges|website=Stars and Stripes|last=McCluskey|first=Neal|date=January 19, 2015 }}</ref> Political operatives with close ties to for-profit education have included [[Bill Clinton]],<ref name=\"insidehighered\">{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/quicktakes/2015/08/03/laureate-paid-bill-clinton-165-million|publisher=insidehighered.com|title=Laureate Paid Bill Clinton $16.5 Million|accessdate=February 18, 2017}}</ref>\n[[Lanny Davis]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/davidhalperin/which-for-profit-college_b_5040172.html|title=Which For-Profit College Lobbyist Are You?|work=The Huffington Post|accessdate=June 14, 2015|date=March 28, 2014}}</ref> [[Heather Podesta]],<ref name=\"theatlantic.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sunlightfoundation.com/blog/2011/03/10/regulations-lead-to-lobbying-surge-by-the-for-profit-college-industry/|title=Regulations Lead To Lobbying Surge By The For-Profit College Industry|work=Sunlight Foundation|accessdate=June 14, 2015|date=March 10, 2011}}</ref> [[Urban League]] President [[Marc Morial]],<ref name=\"articles.latimes.com\">{{cite web|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2013/may/31/business/la-fi-hiltzik-20130602|publisher=articles.latimes.com|title=Why would Leon Panetta, Marc Morial join for-profit Corinthian? - latimes|accessdate=February 18, 2017|date=May 31, 2013}}</ref> former Ted Kennedy aide [[Jane Oates]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.washingtonmonthly.com/college_guide/blog/jane_oates_sells_out.php|title=Jane Oates Sells Out|work=The Washington Monthly|accessdate=June 14, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150703003452/http://www.washingtonmonthly.com/college_guide/blog/jane_oates_sells_out.php|archive-date=July 3, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> former Defense Secretary [[Leon Panetta]],<ref name=\"articles.latimes.com\"/>\nand [[National Action Network]]'s civil rights activist [[Al Sharpton]].<ref>{{cite news|author= |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/gary-stager/education-nation-ideologi_b_739106.html |title=Education Nation & Ideological Blindness &#124; Gary Stager |publisher=Huffingtonpost.com |date=October 19, 2010 |accessdate=July 2, 2015}}</ref> In 2014, APSCU hired Michael Dakduk, former head of [[Student Veterans of America]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/davidhalperin/michael-dakduk_b_4221020.html|title=Head of Group Charged With Protecting Student Vets Joins For-Profit College Lobby|work=The Huffington Post|accessdate=June 14, 2015|date=November 5, 2013}}</ref> From 2010 to 2015, [[Bill Clinton]] received at least $17.5 million from [[Laureate Education]], the parent company of [[Walden University]].<ref name=\"politico\">{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2016/08/bill-clinton-laureate-for-profit-college-pay-226971|publisher=politico.com|title=Bill Clinton's pay at for-profit education company topped $17.5 million - POLITICO|accessdate=February 18, 2017}}</ref>In March 2017, Secretary of Education [[Betsy DeVos]] appointed Robert Eitel, a former Career Education Corporation and Bridgepoint executive, as a special advisor.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/17/business/education-for-profit-robert-eitel.html|title=Betsy DeVos's Hiring of For-Profit College Official Raises Impartiality Issues|first=Patricia|last=Cohen|date=March 17, 2017|publisher=|access-date=January 1, 2018|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref> In July 2018, DeVos delayed the implementation of a rule intended to help students receive debt forgiveness if they were cheated by their college.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/09/13/politics/betsy-devos-loses-lawsuit/index.html|title=Betsy DeVos loses lawsuit after delaying student loan protection rule|first=Katie|last=Lobosco|website=CNN}}</ref> In September 2018, the [[United States District Court for the District of Columbia|U. S. District Court for the District of Columbia]] ruled against DeVos, finding the delay of implementation to be unlawful.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/court-rules-against-education-secretary-betsy-devos-in-for-profit-college-case/|title=Court rules against Education Secretary Betsy DeVos in for-profit college case|website=www.cbsnews.com}}</ref>\n\n==Student debt groups==\nSeveral student debt groups have been created since 2014, after the [[Debt Collective]] paid off student loans for 3,700 [[Everest College]] students.<ref name=\"theguardian.com\"/> The groups include \"I Am Ai,\" a group that offers support and advocacy for student debtors who attended the Art Institutes.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/>\n\n==Recruiting, advertising, and lead generators==\nThe for-profit college industry has spent billions of dollars on student recruiting, advertising, and buying leads for recruitment.<ref name=\"chronicle.com\">{{cite web|url=http://chronicle.com/blogs/bottomline/u-of-phoenix-reboots-advertising-and-rebrands-in-the-process/|title=U. of Phoenix Reboots Advertising and Rebrands in the Process \u2013 Bottom Line - Blogs - The Chronicle of Higher Education|publisher=Chronicle.com|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/recruitment-profit-colleges-targeted-145346998.html|title=Recruitment by for-profit colleges targeted|date=April 18, 2012|work=Yahoo News|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref> In 2011, for example, [[University of Phoenix]], [[ITT Tech]], [[Devry]], and [[Capella University|Capella]] together spent more than $100,000,000 on Google Ads.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.academia.edu/8504554 |title=4Profits'R'Us |accessdate=January 15, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141117210304/http://www.academia.edu/8504554/4ProfitsRUs |archivedate=November 17, 2014 }}</ref> Several Wall Street-backed schools spend large amounts on advertisements on day time and late night television.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://chronicle.com/article/Calif-Accuses-Corinthian/142267/|title=Calif. Accuses Corinthian Colleges of False Placement Rates, Predatory Ads|journal=The Chronicle of Higher Education|accessdate=June 14, 2015|date=October 11, 2013}}</ref> In 2012, [[Apollo Group]], the parent company of [[University of Phoenix]], reportedly spent $665,000,000 on advertising and marketing.<ref name=\"chronicle.com\"/> The colleges' marketing departments rely heavily on Lead Generators, which are companies that find potential students (\"leads\") and provide their personal information and preferences to for-profit college.{{explain|reason=So what? Explain--in neutral and informative language.|date=October 2015}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nacacnet.org/media-center/Pages/Lead-Generators.aspx|title=Lead Generators: A Checklist for Reporters|publisher=Nacacnet.org|accessdate=June 14, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150121014654/http://www.nacacnet.org/media-center/Pages/Lead-Generators.aspx|archive-date=January 21, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://fortune.com/2014/11/19/business-school-rankings-lead-generation-marketing/|title=What's a goat farmer doing ranking business schools? - Fortune|work=Fortune|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfweekly.com/sanfrancisco/for-profit-colleges-predators-in-the-ivory-tower/Content?oid=2185880|title=For-Profit Colleges: Predators in the Ivory Tower|work=SF Weekly|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Structure of for-profit education==\n\n===Sources of capital and cash flow===\nThe main sources of initial capital for public for-profit colleges are institutional investors: international banks, hedge funds, institutional retirement funds, and state retirement funds.<ref name=\"huffingtonpost\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://nypost.com/2014/07/11/goldman-sachs-kkr-flunk-in-college-investment/|title=Goldman Sachs, KKR flunk in college investment|work=New York Post|accessdate=June 14, 2015|first=Josh|last=Kosman|date=July 12, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=E9KJWnyDk1sC&pg=PA53&lpg=PA53&dq=warburg+pincus+acquires+bridgepoint+education#v=onepage&q=warburg%20pincus%20acquires%20bridgepoint%20education&f=false|title=Corporations Are Not People|accessdate=June 14, 2015|isbn=9781609941079|last1=Clements|first1=Jeffrey D.|date=January 9, 2012}}</ref> [[Wells Fargo]] was a major funder of [[Corinthian Colleges]]<ref name=\"huffingtonpost2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/davidhalperin/who-owns-the-awful-corint_b_4101323.html|publisher=huffingtonpost.com|title=Who Owns The Awful Corinthian Colleges? Wells Fargo, Marc Morial, Pension Funds &#124; The Huffington Post|accessdate=February 18, 2017|date=October 15, 2013}}</ref> and [[Goldman Sachs]] provided a significant amount of capital to [[Education Management Corporation]].<ref name=\"edmc\">{{cite web|url=http://www.edmc.edu/About/History.aspx|publisher=edmc.edu|title=Education Management Corporation - History|accessdate=February 18, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503195751/http://www.edmc.edu/about/History.aspx|archive-date=May 3, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n====Title IV funds====\n\nThe main source of cash flow consists of US Department of Education [[Higher Education Act of 1965|Higher Education Act]] [[Title IV]] funds. Title IV funds include Federal Family Education Loans (FFEL), direct loans, Federal Perkins Loans, Federal [[Pell Grants]], Academic Competitiveness Grants (ACG), National SMART Grants, Federal Supplemental Educational Opportunity Grants (FSEOG), and Federal Work-Study (FWS).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://federalstudentaid.ed.gov/site/front2back/programs/programs/fb_03_01_0030.htm|title=What are Title IV Programs?|publisher=Federalstudentaid.ed.gov|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref> In the 1990s, Congress began requiring that for-profit schools receive at least 10% of their revenues from non-federal student aid sources, which include the GI Bill.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Bair|first1=Sheila|authorlink1=Sheila Bair|title=For-Profit Schools Are a Bad Deal for Both Investors and Taxpayers |journal=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]|date=January 1, 2015|volume=171|issue=1|page=39}}</ref>\n\n====GI Bill funds, Department of Defense Tuition Assistance and MyCAA====\nThe for-profit education industry also receives billions of dollars through VA benefits also known as the [[GI Bill]].<ref name=\"help.senate.gov\" /> In the 2010\u20132011 school year, more than $1 billion went to eight for-profit schools.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://chronicle.com/article/8-For-Profit-Colleges-Collect/129124/|title=8 For-Profit Colleges Collect More Than $1-Billion in Veterans' Education Benefits|journal=The Chronicle of Higher Education|accessdate=June 14, 2015|date=September 22, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|url=http://chronicle.com/article/For-Profit-Colleges-Still-Cash/147977/|title=For-Profit Colleges Still Cash In on Post-9/11 GI Bill, Harkin Report Says|journal=The Chronicle of Higher Education|accessdate=June 14, 2015|date=July 30, 2014}}</ref> In the 2012\u20132013 academic year, 31 percent of GI Bill funds went to for-profit colleges. Veteran participation in these schools, in effect, transferred $1.7 billion in post-9/11 GI Bill funds to these schools.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Zillman|first1=Claire|title=Obama's budget aims to eliminate for-profit colleges' GI Bill loophole|journal=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]|date=February 3, 2015|url=http://fortune.com/2015/02/03/gi-bill-for-profit-colleges-2/|accessdate=February 7, 2015}}</ref> According to a CBS News report in 2017, 40 percent of all GI Bill funds went to for-profit colleges.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/warrior-scholar-project-helps-veterans-transition-to-college-life/ |title = Warrior Scholar Project helps veterans transition from battlefield to classroom}}</ref>For-profit colleges receive money for servicemembers and their spouses attending college while still in the military.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://rebootcamp.militarytimes.com/news/education/2018/03/27/dod-review-0-of-schools-following-ta-rules/ |title = DoD review: 0% of schools following TA rules|date = March 27, 2018}}</ref> In fiscal year 2018, for-profit colleges received $181 million or 38 percent of all DOD TA funds. For-profit schools also receive money from DOD for education of military spouses.  The program is known as MyCAA.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.dodmou.com/ |title = Home}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.militarytimes.com/pay-benefits/2019/04/10/few-military-spouses-are-using-this-4000-benefit/ |title = Few military spouses are using this $4,000 benefit|date = April 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Other sources====\n\nThese corporations also obtain cash flow through student private loans, corporate loans, and the selling of assets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gpo.gov/fdsys/pkg/CPRT-112SPRT74931/pdf/CPRT-112SPRT74931.pdf |title=For Profit Higher Education: The Failure to Safeguard the Federal Investment and Ensure Student Success |publisher=Gpo.gov |accessdate=July 4, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/rundown/new-report-shows-nearly-2-billion-of-gi-bill-funds-go-to-for-profit-colleges/|title=New report shows nearly $2 billion in GI Bill funds go to for-profit colleges|work=PBS NewsHour|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref> Problems with high-interest private loans to students at [[Corinthian Colleges]] (Genesis loans) and [[ITT Tech]] (PEAKS and CUSO loans) have gained scrutiny from the [[Consumer Financial Protection Bureau]] and the [[Securities and Exchange Commission]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.consumerfinance.gov/newsroom/cfpb-sues-for-profit-corinthian-colleges-for-predatory-lending-scheme/|title=CFPB Sues For-Profit Corinthian Colleges for Predatory Lending Scheme|publisher=Consumer Financial Protection Bureau|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/itt-educational-sinks-disclosing-sec-164532930.html|title=ITT Educational sinks after disclosing SEC probe|date=February 25, 2013|work=Yahoo Finance|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Arguments for and against for-profit colleges==\nAlthough supporters of for-profit higher education have argued that the [[profit motive]] encourages efficiency, the for-profit educational industry has received severe negative criticism because of its sales techniques, high costs, and poor student outcomes. In some cases operators of for-profit colleges have faced criminal charges or other legal sanctions.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2013/07/02/college-default-rates-higher-than-grad-rates/2480295/|title=College default rates higher than grad rates|author1=Mary Beth Marklein |author2=Jodi Upton |author3=Sandhya Kambhampati, USA TODAY|date=July 2, 2013|work=USA TODAY|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"digilib.gmu.edu\">{{cite web|url=http://digilib.gmu.edu/jspui/bitstream/1920/6273/1/Perini_thesis_2011.pdf |title=A Phoenix Still in Ashes : For-Profit Open Admissions and the Public Good |publisher=Digilib.gmu.edu |accessdate=July 4, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sites.duke.edu/acfp2012/2012/08/26/doonesbury-talks-for-profit-colleges/|title=Doonesbury Talks For-Profit Colleges - ACFP 2012|publisher=Sites.duke.edu|accessdate=June 14, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150706130158/http://sites.duke.edu/acfp2012/2012/08/26/doonesbury-talks-for-profit-colleges/|archive-date=July 6, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"huffingtonpost.com\">{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/tressie-mcmillan-cottom/for-profit-colleges-kaplan-university_b_1205464.html|title=Insider's View of For-Profit Colleges, Race, Class and Education Justice|work=The Huffington Post|accessdate=June 14, 2015|date=January 13, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://hs.boisestate.edu/nursing/files/2012/01/For-profit-degrees.pdf |title=Under Fire : Nursing Degrees from For-Profit Institutions |publisher=Hs.boisestate.edu |accessdate=July 4, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Benefits===\nHistorically, for-profit education has offered open admissions to non-traditional students, convenience of schedule and location, instructors with workplace knowledge, and real world vocational training rather than traditional training. Critics of [[Wall Street]]-backed for-profit educators, however, have questioned these perceived benefits.<ref name=\"huffingtonpost.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nacacnet.org/issues-action/LegislativeNews/Pages/For-Profit-Colleges.aspx|title=The Low-Down on For-Profit Colleges|publisher=Nacacnet.org|accessdate=June 14, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150120150425/http://www.nacacnet.org/issues-action/LegislativeNews/Pages/For-Profit-Colleges.aspx|archive-date=January 20, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2014/01/for-profit-college-student-debt|title=Screw U: How For-Profit Colleges Rip You Off|work=Mother Jones|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref>For-profit schools like [[University of Phoenix]] have been more inclusive, recruiting and graduating more African Americans than public higher education.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://americanradioworks.publicradio.org/features/tomorrows-college/phoenix/who-goes-to-university-of-phoenix.html|title=Who Goes to the University of Phoenix?|author=American Public Media|publisher=Americanradioworks.publicradio.org|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://urbanmecca.net/news/2008/12/06/more-minority-students-earn-degrees-from-university-of-phoenix/|title=More Minority Students Earn Degrees From University of Phoenix|work=Urbanmecca.com - African American News|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref> In 2012, [[The Journal of Blacks in Higher Education]] called University of Phoenix \"a pillar of [[African American]] higher education.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jbhe.com/2012/02/the-university-of-phoenix-is-a-pillar-of-african-american-higher-education/|title=The University of Phoenix Is a Pillar of African American Higher Education|work=The Journal of Blacks in Higher Education|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref> Through the Thurgood Marshall fund, students at 47 publicly supported [[historically Black colleges and universities]], may supplement their on-campus course loads with course programs using the University of Phoenix online platform.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jbhe.com/2014/11/university-of-phoenix-signs-agreement-to-offer-online-courses-to-hbcu-students/#comments|title=University of Phoenix Signs Agreement to Offer Online Courses to HBCU Students|work=The Journal of Blacks in Higher Education|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref> For-profit colleges have also been seen as a second chance for students who have performed poorly in the past.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eric.ed.gov/?id=EJ989048|title=ERIC - Choice of For-Profit College, Economics of Education Review, 2012-Dec|publisher=Eric.ed.gov|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref> It may be argued that for-profit colleges also created innovations that would force public higher education to be more responsive to student needs<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ecs.org/html/Document.asp?chouseid=1815 |title=Profit-Making or Profiteering? Proprietaries Target Teacher Education |publisher=Ecs.org |date= |accessdate=July 2, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150703025552/http://www.ecs.org/html/Document.asp?chouseid=1815 |archive-date=July 3, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> For-profit colleges have been compared favorably to [[community colleges]] in regards to graduation rates,<ref name=\"stripes.com\"/> but these comparisons may be offering misleading statistical comparisons<ref name=\"mediamatters.org\">{{cite web|url=http://mediamatters.org/research/2015/01/12/wsj-uses-bad-numbers-to-wipe-away-downside-of-f/202104 |title=WSJ Uses Bad Numbers To Wipe Away Downside Of For-Profit Colleges |accessdate=January 16, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150116122736/http://mediamatters.org/research/2015/01/12/wsj-uses-bad-numbers-to-wipe-away-downside-of-f/202104 |archivedate=January 16, 2015 }}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.icl-fi.org/english/wv/1052/ysp-education.html|title=Wall Street's For-Profit University Rip-Off|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=Icl-fi.org|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Drawbacks===\n\nA 2010 report by the [[Government Accountability Office]] (GAO) documented misleading sales and marketing tactics used by several for-profits.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/04/education/04education.html?ref=tamarlewin|work=The New York Times|first=Tamar|last=Lewin|title=For-Profit Colleges Mislead Students, Report Finds|date=August 3, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/12/09/education/09gao.html?ref=education|work=New York Times|first=Tamar|last=Lewin|title=U.S. Revises Report on Recruiting at For-Profit Colleges|date=December 8, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://eric.ed.gov/PDFS/ED511120.pdf |title=FOR-PROFIT COLLEGES Undercover Testing Finds Colleges Encouraged Fraud and Engaged in Deceptive and Questionable Marketing Practices |publisher=Eric.ed.gov |accessdate=July 4, 2015}}</ref> Critics have also pointed out that more than half of for-profits' revenues are either spent on marketing or extracted as profits, with less than half spent on instruction.<ref name=Harkin>{{cite web|title=For-Profit College Investigation|url=http://www.harkin.senate.gov/help/forprofitcolleges.cfm|publisher=U.S. Senate|accessdate=March 19, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130328220032/http://www.harkin.senate.gov/help/forprofitcolleges.cfm|archive-date=March 28, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Where Are Federal G.I. Bill Dollars Going?|url=http://www.harkin.senate.gov/documents/pdf/4eb2c45d86297.pdf|publisher=U.S. Senate|accessdate=March 19, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130317141912/http://www.harkin.senate.gov/documents/pdf/4eb2c45d86297.pdf|archive-date=March 17, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Senator Harkin's Findings Regarding Veterans and For\u2010Profit Colleges|url=http://www.harkin.senate.gov/documents/pdf/4f9ac62292704.pdf|publisher=U.S. Senate|accessdate=March 19, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130218044753/http://www.harkin.senate.gov/documents/pdf/4f9ac62292704.pdf|archive-date=February 18, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> A 2011 study by the [[National Bureau of Economic Research]], in Cambridge, Massachusetts, reported that students who attend for-profit education institutions are more likely to be unemployed, earn less, have higher debt levels, and are more likely to default on their student loans than similar students at non-profit educational institutions.<ref name=Goldin>David J. Deming, Claudia Goldin, and Lawrence F. Katz, \"[http://big.assets.huffingtonpost.com/forprofitpaper.pdf The For-Profit Postsecondary School Sector: Nimble Critters or Agile Predators?]\" National Bureau of Economic Research 2011.</ref> Although for-profits typically serve students who are poorer or more likely to be minorities, these differences do not explain the differences in employment, income, debt levels, and student loan defaults.<ref name=Goldin/> The [[Government Accountability Office]] has also found that graduates of for-profits are less likely to pass licensing exams, and that poor student performance cannot be explained by different student demographics.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Kelly Field|title= Demographics Do Not Explain For-Profit Colleges' Shortcomings on Student-Success Measures, GAO Says|journal=Chronicle of Higher Education|date=December 7, 2011|url=http://chronicle.com/article/article-content/130040/|publisher=Chronicle.com|accessdate=July 4, 2015}}</ref> The same year, ''[[The New York Times]]'' noted that for-profit higher education institutions often have much higher [[student loan default]] rates than non-profits.<ref>{{cite news|author=Tamar Lewin|title=Student Loan Default Rates Rise Sharply in Past Year|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=September 12, 2011|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/09/13/education/13loans.html|accessdate=July 4, 2015}}</ref> Two documentaries by ''[[Frontline (U.S. TV series)|Frontline]]'' have focused on alleged abuses in for profit higher education.<ref>{{cite AV media |people=[[Frontline (U.S. TV series)|Frontline]] |year=2010 |title=College, Inc. |medium=Television production |url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/collegeinc/ |accessdate=July 15, 2013 |publisher=[[PBS]] Distribution |isbn=9781608832835 |oclc=643117456}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/educating-sergeant-pantzke/ |title=Educating Sergeant Pantzke - Video &#124; FRONTLINE |publisher=Pbs.org |date= |accessdate=July 4, 2015}}</ref>Compared to community colleges, some for-profits may have higher completion rates for certificates and associate degree programs,<ref name=\"mediamatters.org\"/> but higher drop out rates for four-year bachelor's degrees.<ref name=Goldin/> However, studies suggest that one- and two-year programs often may not provide much economic benefit to students because the boost to wages is offset by increased debt. By contrast, four-year programs provide a large economic benefit.<ref name=Simkovic>Michael Simkovic, [http://ssrn.com/abstract=1941070 Risk-Based Student Loans] (2012)</ref>For-profits have been sued for allegedly using aggressive and deceptive sales and marketing practices.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/education/college-inc/lawsuits-address-recruitment-practices-at-for-profit-colleges/|title=Lawsuits Address Recruitment Practices at For-Profit Colleges|work=FRONTLINE|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref> Holly Petraeus, a high-ranking official at the [[Consumer Financial Protection Bureau]], has accused for-profits of preying on vulnerable military personnel.<ref>{{cite news|author=Hollister K. Petraeus|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/09/22/opinion/for-profit-colleges-vulnerable-gis.html|title= For-Profit Colleges, Vulnerable G.I.'s|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=September 21, 2011|accessdate=July 4, 2014}}</ref> Petraeus wrote:\"This gives for-profit colleges an incentive to see service members as nothing more than dollar signs in uniform, and to use aggressive marketing to draw them in and take out private loans...One of the most egregious reports of questionable marketing involved a college recruiter who visited a Marine barracks at [[Marine Corps Base Camp Lejeune|Camp Lejeune]], North Carolina. As the PBS program ''Frontline'' reported, the recruiter signed up Marines with serious brain injuries. The fact that some of them couldn\u2019t remember what courses they were taking was immaterial, as long as they signed on the dotted line.\" Opponents say that the fundamental purpose of an educational institution should be to educate, not to turn a profit. In 2000, Bob Chase, president of the [[National Education Association]], stated that \"educating children is very different from producing a product\".<ref name=\"BusinessWeek\">{{cite web|url=http://www.businessweek.com/2000/00_06/b3667001.htm|title=For-Profit Schools|accessdate=September 26, 2008|author=William C Symonds|date=February 7, 2000|work=BusinessWeek|publisher=The McGraw-Hill Companies, Inc.}}</ref> Certain postsecondary education programs at institutions of higher education are eligible for participation in the federal student aid programs, known as [[Title IV]] of the US [[Higher Education Act of 1965|Higher Education Act]] (HEA). These programs, which are offered by public and private not-for-profit institutions, postsecondary vocational institutions, and by for-profit proprietary institutions, should prepare students for [[gainful employment]]. For decades, the [[U.S. Department of Education]] (ED) had not established regulations that explicitly outlined what it means for a program to be properly preparing students for gainful employment. As pressing concerns about the quality of programs at for- profit institutions began to arise, the concerns about the level of student loan debt assumed by students did as well. Such issues led to new initiatives and rules to be set in place outlining the parameters for what should be mandated to help ensure gainful employment. The 2011 Senate HELP committee released data showing one in every four students who enroll at a for-profit school default on their loans within three years of leaving, with for-profit students accounting for almost half of all loan defaults.<ref name=\"Sessions, Jennifer 2011\">Sessions, Jennifer. (February 8, 2011). \"Harkin Calls on For-Profit Colleges to End Deceptive Recruiting Practices\". Senate HELP Committee. Accessed February 4, 2013.</ref> Most for-profit colleges charge enrollees much higher tuition rates than analogous programs at community colleges and state public universities despite credits being likely not eligible to be transferred to other institutions.<ref name=\"Sessions, Jennifer 2011\"/> In fact, 96% of students attending for-profit college apply for federal student loans compared to 13% at community colleges. During the 2009\u20132010 school years, for-profit colleges received almost $32 billion in grants and loans provided to students under federal student aid programs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gao.gov/products/GAO-12-150 |title=U.S. GAO - For-Profit Schools: Experiences of Undercover Students Enrolled in Online Classes at Selected Colleges |publisher=Gao.gov |date= |accessdate=July 4, 2015}}</ref> This staggering number means nearly all students at for-profit institutions acquire student loan debt, even when they do not earn the end product of a degree or accumulate increased earning power through their studies (Sessions, 2011). These statistics represent a large portion of for- profits, uncovering the serious need for greater accountability in ensuring students are making sound investments in such institutions. According to the [[Government Accountability Office]], enrollment in such institutions has increased faster than traditional higher-education institutions in recent years. With the student and federal interest in such programs growing, so has the concern with their productivity. Regrettably, this is not a simple matter to address, as the issue is multidimensional. For-profit institutions have become an increasingly visible portion of the U.S. higher education sector. For-profits also acquire the largest percentage of their overall revenue from federal student aid programs, highlighting tax dollars are potentially not being used efficiently.<ref>Deming, David. (February 2012). \"The For-Profit Postsecondary School Sector:\nNimble Critters or Agile Predators?\" Center for Analysis Postsecondary education and employment.</ref> Federal regulatory actions by the ED have attempted to address these issues in the Title IV of the Higher Education Act of 1965, as amended. These efforts were very contentious. For-profit institutions argue their sector is unfairly targeted and believe the Department of Education over stepped its boundaries in 2010 by implementing regulations specifying requirements for [[Gainful Employment]]. These rules outlined in a report by Congressional Research Service (CRS), aimed to hold for-profits accountable by creating standards which must be upheld and followed, which will in turn attempt create more opportunity for gainful employment amongst enrollees.<ref name=\"SmoleDavid\">Smole, David. (January 23, 2013). \"Department of Education Final Rules for Postsecondary Education Programs That Prepare Students for Gainful Employment in a Recognized Occupation\". Accessed February 4, 2013. Congressional Research Service Database.</ref> Through these regulations the ED believed that institutions will reinforce their educational programs to meet these higher standards, and relatively few programs will fail. Programs that offer a rewarding education at a reasonable price will succeed, and institutions will continue to innovate to assist students and taxpayers.<ref>Federal Registrar. 76 FR 34385. \"Program Integrity: Gainful Employment-Debt Measures\". Accessed February 2, 2013.</ref>The regulations mandated by the ED were to help regulate the for-profit sector and to combat the issue of gainful employment. However, the [[Association of Private Sector Colleges and Universities]], which endorses for-profits, challenged these regulations in court. On June 30, 2012 the U.S. District Court for the District of Columbia decided to vacate most aspects of the regulations.<ref name=\"SmoleDavid\" /> The court sustained that the ED had the authority to regulate gainful employment, yet it cited the ED had not provided rationale metrics or measures in the debt measures. At present, only the disclosure requirements of providing prospective students with placements rates, on time graduation rates and other similar information remain.<ref>Smole, David. (January 23, 2013). \"Department of Education Final Rules for Postsecondary Education Programs That Prepare Students for Gainful Employment in a Recognized Occupation\". Accessed February 4, 2013. Congressional Research Service Database</ref> On March 19, 2013 the judge ruled again in response to the ED's motion to reinstate the reporting requirements in order that it could implement the disclosure requirements of Gainful Employment. The judged denied the motion of the ED on the basis that the reporting requirements would violate the federal ban on the student unit record system. It is strongly debatable that the court's ruling negates the small amount of transparency and accountability mandated by the disclosure requirements, leaving the policy issue of for-profits being accountable for [[Gainful Employment]] unattended.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newamerica.net/taxonomy/term/1764 |title=Welcome to nginx! |publisher=Newamerica.net |date= |accessdate=July 4, 2015}}</ref> Some former students claim that for-profit colleges make them feel like they went to the flea market and bought themselves a degree.<ref>[https://www.cbsnews.com/video/watch/?id=6838088n CBS News Video, \"For-Profit Colleges Under Fire\"], September 18, 2010.</ref> According to James G. Andrews of the [[American Association of University Professors]], corporate models of education harm the mission of education.<ref>{{cite web|last=Andrews |first=James G. |url=http://www.aaup.org/AAUP/pubsres/academe/2006/MJ/feat/andr.htm |title=How We Can Resist Corporatization |publisher=AAUP |accessdate=March 19, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101222235655/http://www.aaup.org/AAUP/pubsres/academe/2006/MJ/feat/andr.htm |archivedate=December 22, 2010 }}</ref> Some critics have called for-profit education \"subprime education\", in an analogy with the [[subprime mortgage]]s bubble at the heart of the [[Great Recession]] \u2013 finding uninformed borrowers and loading them with debt they cannot afford, then securitizing and passing the loan onto third-party investors. Activist short seller [[Steve Eisman]] (famous for being a character in [[Michael Lewis]]'s ''[[The Big Short]]'') has described the accreditation situation regarding for-profits like ITT as follows: \"The scandal here is exactly akin to the rating agency role in subprime securitizations.\"<ref>[https://www.cnbc.com/id/37896158/Greenberg_For_Profit_Schools_Subprime_Redux Greenberg: For-Profit Schools ... Subprime Redux?] Herb Greenberg, June 24, 2010</ref>A two-year congressional investigation report\u2014from a committee chaired by Senator [[Tom Harkin]], D-Iowa\u2014examined enrollment numbers in selected for-profit higher education institutions. The committee found that $32 billion in federal funds were spent in 2009\u20132010 on for-profit colleges. The majority of students enrolled in the institutions left without a degree and carried post-schooling debt. Regarding the dropout rates, the report said 54% of students in bachelor's degree programs dropped out before degree completion and 63% of students in associate degree programs dropped out.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.help.senate.gov/imo/media/for_profit_report/Contents.pdf|title=''For Profit Higher Education: The Failure to Safeguard the Federal Investment and Ensure Student Success''|website=Senate.gov|access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref>In 2019, the Department of Education reported median student debt from for-profit colleges and found that among people pursuing a bachelor's degree, those who graduated from for-profits borrowed $43,600, compared to $27,900 for public college graduates and $32,500 for private nonprofit college graduates.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Schwartz |first1=Natalie |title=In shifting for-profit college market, borrowers are taking on more debt |url=https://www.educationdive.com/news/student-debt-grows-in-shifting-for-profit-college-market/558683/ |website=Education Dive |accessdate=July 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Accreditation and transfer-of-credits==\nMany for-profit institutions of [[higher education]] have [[Regional accreditation#Regional accreditation vs. national accreditation|national accreditation]] rather than [[regional accreditation]]. Regionally accredited schools are predominantly academically oriented, non-profit institutions.<ref name=\"usaed\"/><ref name=yahoo/> Nationally accredited schools are predominantly for-profit and offer vocational, career, or technical programs.<ref name=\"usaed\"/><ref name=\"yahoo\"/> Most regionally accredited schools will not accept transfer credits earned at a nationally accredited school because, except for some specialized areas such as nursing, the standards for regional accreditation are higher than those for national accreditation.<ref name=\"usaed\">{{cite web|url=http://www.useducation.com.pk/stpages/typesofaccreditation.html |title=''Types of Accreditation'', Education USA website |publisher=Useducation.com.pk |accessdate=March 19, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080424074806/http://www.useducation.com.pk/stpages/typesofaccreditation.html |archivedate=April 24, 2008 }}</ref><ref name=\"yahoo\">{{cite web|url=http://help.yahoo.com/l/us/yahoo/education/courses/distancelearn-09.html |title=''What is the Difference Between Regional and National Accreditation'', Yahoo! Education website |publisher=Help.yahoo.com |accessdate=March 19, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101205210641/http://help.yahoo.com/l/us/yahoo/education/courses/distancelearn-09.html |archivedate=December 5, 2010 }}</ref><ref name=\"demand\">{{cite web|author=Scott Jaschik|date=October 19, 2005|title=Demanding Credit|work=Insidehighered.com|url=http://www.insidehighered.com/news/2005/10/19/transfer|accessdate=July 4, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"tussle\">{{cite web|author=Doug Lederman|url=http://insidehighered.com/news/2007/02/26/transfer|title=Tussling Over Transfer of Credit|work=Insidehighered.com|date=February 26, 2007|accessdate=July 4, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2005 congressional discussions concerning reauthorization of the Higher Education Act and in the [[U.S. Secretary of Education]]'s [http://www.ed.gov/about/bdscomm/list/hiedfuture/index.html ''Commission on the Future of Higher Education''], there were proposals, ultimately unsuccessful, to mandate that regional accrediting agencies bar the schools they accredit from basing decisions on whether or not to accept credits for transfer ''solely'' on the accreditation of the \"sending\" school.<ref name=demand/><ref name=tussle/> They could still reject the credits, but they would have to have additional reasons.{{Citation needed|date=August 2008}} The American Commission of Career Schools and Colleges (ACCSC), a nonprofit accreditor for-profit schools, supported the proposed rule.<ref name=demand/><ref name=tussle/><ref name=agenda/> The ACCSC claims regionally accredited schools will not accept nationally accredited schools credits for purely arbitrary, prejudicial and/or anti-competitive reasons.<ref name=agenda/> It further stated that, since the Department of Education recognizes both national and regional accreditation, there is no reason for regionals to differentiate between the two and to do so amounts to an unwarranted denial of access.<ref name=demand/><ref name=tussle/><ref name=\"agenda\">{{cite web|url=http://www.accsc.org/Student-Corner/Transfer-of-Credit.aspx|publisher=accsc.org|title=Transfer of Credit |accessdate=February 18, 2017}}</ref> The position of the [[American Association of Collegiate Registrars and Admissions Officers]] (AACRAO) was that national accrediting standards were not as rigorous and, though they might be well-suited for vocational and career education, were ill-suited for academic institutions.<ref name=\"aacrao\">{{cite web|url=http://www.aacrao.org/federal_relations/transfer/FEDERALIZING_TRANSFER_OF_ACADEMIC_CREDIT.pdf |title=''Federalized Transfer of Academic Credit, Proposed Mandate Would Hurt Students'' AACRAO website |accessdate=March 19, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101226201419/http://www.aacrao.org/federal_relations/transfer/FEDERALIZING_TRANSFER_OF_ACADEMIC_CREDIT.pdf |archivedate=December 26, 2010 }}</ref> AACRAO alleged that this proposed rule was unnecessary and unjustified, could threaten the autonomy and potentially lower the standards of regionally accredited schools, and drive up their costs.<ref name=aacrao/> Furthermore, it stated the proposed rule was an attempt by the for-profits' \"well-funded lobbyists\" to obscure the difference between for-profits' \"lax academic criteria for accreditation\" and non-profits' higher standards.<ref name=aacrao/>\n\nSome for-profit schools have received regional accreditation, including [[American InterContinental University]], [[American Public University System]], [[Capella University]], [[DeVry University]], [[Kaplan University]], [[National American University]], [[Post University]], [[San Joaquin Valley College]], [[Strayer University]], [[University of Phoenix]], [[Universal Technical Institute]], and [[Walden University]].\n\nAccrediting agencies have gained some scrutiny and criticism for conflicts of interest. Because these agencies receive their funding from the institutions themselves, they may have a vested interest in not aggressively supervising these for-profit colleges.<ref name=\"huffingtonpost.com1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/09/19/for-profit-college-accreditation_n_3937079.html|title=How For-Profit Colleges Stay In Business Despite Terrible Track Record|work=The Huffington Post|accessdate=June 14, 2015|date=September 19, 2013}}</ref> According to Chris Kirkham and Kevin Short:\n\"Two accrediting bodies...collectively monitor nearly 60 percent of all American for-profit colleges. They preside over almost half of those schools with the nation's worst student loan default rates....Ten of the 15 board members supervising the ACICS are drawn from the industry, including executives from Corinthian, [[Education Corporation of America]] and [[ITT Technical Institute]]. On the ACCSC board, industry executives fill eight of the 13 slots, representing publicly traded companies such as [[Universal Technical Institute]] and [[Kaplan, Inc.|Kaplan]] Higher Education.\"<ref name=\"huffingtonpost.com1\"/>\n\nIn 2016, 12 Attorneys General asked the [[US Department of Education]] to stop the renewal of [[ACICS]], the [[Accrediting Council for Independent Colleges and Schools]]<ref name=\"propublica\">{{cite web|url=https://www.propublica.org/article/attorneys-general-come-down-on-accreditor-of-for-profit-colleges|publisher=propublica.org|title=Attorneys General Come Down on Accreditor of For-profit Colleges - ProPublica|accessdate=February 18, 2017|date=April 11, 2016}}</ref> The Department of Education deliberated on the fate of [[ACICS]] and its power to accredit schools for Title IV government funds.<ref name=\"wsj2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-for-profit-kill-zone-1466638683|publisher=wsj.com|title=The For-Profit Kill Zone - WSJ|accessdate=February 18, 2017}}</ref> On June 23, 2016, The National Advisory Committee on Institutional Quality and Integrity (NACIQI), voted to revoke ACICS's power to accredit schools.{{citation needed|date=October 2019}}\n\n==Business failures==\nNotable failures include [[Corinthian Colleges]] (2015), [[ITT Technical Institute]] (2016), [[Education Management Corporation]] (2017), [[Education Corporation of America]] (2018) and [[Vatterott College]] (2018).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2014/06/26/corinthians-failure-and-us-role-it-fuels-profit-critics|title=Corinthian's failure (and U.S. role in it) fuels for-profit critics |publisher=Insidehighered.com|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/business/2014/08/27/EDMC-debt-restructuring/stories/201408270182|title=EDMC announces debt restructuring; expects improved capital structure|work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|accessdate=June 14, 2015|date=August 27, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2018/12/06/closure-education-corporation-america-raises-questions-about-oversight-and-support|title=Closure of Education Corporation of America raises questions about oversight and support for students|website=www.insidehighered.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/quicktakes/2018/12/19/vatterott-educational-centers-close|title=Vatterott Educational Centers to Close &#124; Inside Higher Ed|website=www.insidehighered.com}}</ref> In 2010, [[Trump University]] was closed by the State of New York for operating without a license.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/10/16/us-trump-nyag-lawsuit-idUSKCN0I52MW20141016|title=New York judge finds Donald Trump liable for unlicensed school|work=Reuters|accessdate=June 14, 2015|date=October 16, 2014}}</ref> In 2014, FastTrain college closed after being raided by the FBI.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fbi.gov/miami/press-releases/2014/fast-train-owner-and-three-admissions-representatives-arrested-for-theft-of-federal-student-aid|title=FBI \u2014 Fast Train Owner and Three Admissions Representatives Arrested for Theft of Federal Student Aid|work=FBI|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref> In 2016, all campuses of [[Westwood College]] closed.<ref name=\"insidehighered.com\"/> In 2016, the US Department of Education stripped [[ACICS]], the accreditor of ITT Tech and many more colleges, of its accrediting power.{{Citation needed|date=January 2018}} The ACICS was given the power back under Secretary of Education Betsy DeVos.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/opinion/editorials/la-ed-devos-student-loans-20180831-story.html|title=Editorial: Betsy DeVos sides with predatory for-profit colleges over America's students|date=August 31, 2018|website=Los Angeles Times}}</ref> In 2018 and 2019, [[Dream Center]] Education Holdings faced a financial crisis with colleges with [[Art Institutes]], [[Argosy University]], and [[South University]] brands, which had been converted from for-profit to non-profit.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.post-gazette.com/business/career-workplace/2019/02/13/Financial-aid-Art-Institute-Dream-Center-Education-Holdings-EDMC-Mark-Dottore/stories/201902130104|title=$13 million in financial aid missing? Federal receiver tries to track down money from Art Institute owners|website=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette}}</ref>\n\n==Government scrutiny, criminal and civil investigations==\n\nAccording to A.J. Angulo, for-profit higher education in the US has been the subject of government scrutiny from the mid-1980s to the 2010s.<ref name=\"books.google.com\"/>\n\nIn August 2010, the [[Government Accountability Office]] reported on an investigation that randomly sampled student-recruiting practices of several for-profit institutions. Investigators posing as prospective students documented deceptive recruiting practices, including misleading information about costs and potential future earnings. They also reported that some recruiters urged them to provide false information on applications for financial aid.<ref>Daniel de Vise and Paul Kane, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/08/04/AR2010080403816.html GAO: 15 for-profit colleges used deceptive recruiting tactics], ''[[The Washington Post]]'', August 5, 2010</ref> Out of the fifteen sampled, all had engaged in deceptive practices, improperly promising unrealistically high pay for graduating students, and four engaged in outright [[fraud]], per a GAO report released at a hearing of the [[Health, Education, Labor and Pensions Committee]] on August 4, 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gao.gov/products/GAO-10-948T|title=U.S. GAO - For-Profit Colleges: Undercover Testing Finds Colleges Encouraged Fraud and Engaged in Deceptive and Questionable Marketing Practices|publisher=Gao.gov|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref> Examples of misconduct included:offering [[commission (remuneration)|commissions]] to admissions officers, employing deceptive marketing tactics by refusing to disclose total tuition cost to prospective students before signing a binding agreement, lying about accreditation, encouraging outright fraud by enticing students to take out student loans even when the applicant had $250,000 in savings, promising extravagant, unlikely high pay to students, failing to disclose graduation rate, and offering tuition cost equivalent to 9 months of credit hours per year, when total program length was 12 months. The GAO study found that 14 out of 15 times, the tuition at a for-profit sample was more expensive than its public counterpart, and 11 out of 15 times, it was more expensive than the private counterpart. Examples of the disparity in full tuition per program include: $14,000 for a certificate at the for-profit institution, when the same diploma cost $500 at a public college; $38,000 for an Associate's at the for-profit institution, when the comparable program at the public college cost $5,000; $61,000 for a Bachelor's at the for-profit institution, compared to $36,000 for the same degree at the public college.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gao.gov/new.items/d10948t.pdf|title=GAO-10-948T For-Profit Colleges: Undercover Testing Finds Colleges Encouraged Fraud and Engaged in Deceptive and Questionable Marketing Practices|date=August 4, 2010|accessdate=March 19, 2011}}</ref> This is counter to [[International Education Corporation]] CEO [[Fardad Fateri|Fardad Fateri's]] claims of the lack of use of unorthodox recruiting practices and a for-profit's \"value\" in an IEC open letter to Congress, the tuition cost of certificates and associate degrees being 28 and 6 times more than at a public college, respectively; Fateri writes, \"Credit should be given to non-profit universities that have been able to convince students and their sophisticated parents to pay approximately $400,000.00 for an undergraduate degree that will seldom lead to an academically related career.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iecglobal.com/Aug2710.asp|title=International Education Corporation : Newsroom|date=August 27, 2010|publisher=Iecglobal.com|accessdate=March 19, 2011}}</ref>The institutions identified in the Committee hearing in respect to the GAO report numeration included [[University of Phoenix]],Everest Institute, [[Kaplan]], [[Argosy University]], [[Anthem Institute]], and [[Westwood College]].\n \nIn 2010, students at for-profit institutions represented about 12% of all college students, but receive roughly 25% of all Federal Pell Grants and loans. They were also responsible for approximately 44% of all student loan defaults.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://projectonstudentdebt.org/files/pub/CDR_2014_NR.pdf |title=Despite Lower Rates, More Than 650,000 Defaulted on Federal Student Loans For-Profit Colleges Account for Nearly Half of all Defaults |publisher=Projectonstudentdebt.org |accessdate=July 4, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pewtrusts.org/news_room_detail.aspx?id=56473|title=New Default Rate Data for Federal Student Loans: 44% of Defaulters Attended For-Profit Institutions|publisher=Pew Charitable Trusts|date=December 15, 2009|accessdate=March 19, 2011}}</ref> University of Phoenix topped this list with Pell Grant revenue of $656.9 million with second and third place held by Everest Colleges at $256.6 million and Kaplan College at $202.1 million for the 2008\u20132009 fiscal year, respectively.<ref name=\"Chronicle of Higher Education\">[http://chronicle.com/article/Data-Points-For-Profit/63388 For-Profit Colleges Capitalize on Pell Grant Revenue], ''The Chronicle of Higher Education'', January 4, 2010.</ref> In 2003, a [[Government Accountability Office]] report estimated that overpayments of Pell Grants were running at about 3% annually, amounting to around $300 million per year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gao.gov/new.items/d03821.pdf|title=TAXPAYER INFORMATION: Increased Sharing and Verifying of Information Could Improve Education's Award Decisions|date=July 2003|publisher=[[Government Accountability Office]]}}</ref> Some of the universities that were top recipients of Pell Grants had low graduation rates, leaving students degreeless, and many graduating alumni found it excessively difficult to find gainful employment.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2010/08/06/degreed-and-jobless-for-p_n_673053.html|title=Degreed And Jobless, For-Profit College Graduate Turns To Stripping|publisher=Huffingtonpost.com|date=August 6, 2010|accessdate=March 19, 2011|first=Leah|last=Finnegan}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitaljournal.com/article/295688|title=Stripper says for-profit college degree 'worthless'|publisher=Digitaljournal.com|date=August 8, 2010|accessdate=March 19, 2011}}</ref> with their degrees, leading some former students to accuse recruiters of being \"duplicitous\", and bringing into serious question the effectiveness of awarding Pell Grants and other [[Title IV]] funds to for-profit colleges.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessweek.com/news/2010-05-05/for-profit-n-j-college-halts-recruiting-of-homeless-update1-.html|title=For-Profit N.J. College Halts Recruiting of Homeless (Update1)|publisher=Businessweek|date=May 5, 2010|accessdate=March 19, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Higher Ed Watch\">[http://higheredwatch.newamerica.net/blogs/2007/02/u_of_phoenix Fed Up at the University of Phoenix] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150122153909/http://higheredwatch.newamerica.net/blogs/2007/02/u_of_phoenix |date=January 22, 2015 }}, ''Higher Ed Watch'', February 27, 2007.</ref> University of Phoenix's graduation rate is 15%.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.phoenix.edu/content/dam/altcloud/doc/about_uopx/University-of-Phoenix-Consumer-Information-Guide-2009-2010.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=January 13, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100821102056/http://www.phoenix.edu/content/dam/altcloud/doc/about_uopx/University-of-Phoenix-Consumer-Information-Guide-2009-2010.pdf |archivedate=August 21, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/02/11/education/11phoenix.html|work=The New York Times|title=Troubles Grow for a University Built on Profits|first=Sam|last=Dillon|date=February 11, 2007}}</ref> [[Strayer University]], which reports its loan repayment rate to be 55%, only has a repayment rate of roughly 25%,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://archival.malformedxmlelement.com/For-Profit%20Colleges/Strayer%20ge-cumulative-rates.xls |title=Archived copy |accessdate=January 13, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110811171948/http://archival.malformedxmlelement.com/For-Profit%20Colleges/Strayer%20ge-cumulative-rates.xls |archivedate=August 11, 2011}}</ref> according to data released by the [[U.S. Department of Education]] on August 13, 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.ed.gov/policy/highered/reg/hearulemaking/2009/ge-cumulative-rates.xls |format=XLS |title=Cumulative Rates |publisher=2.ed.gov |accessdate=July 4, 2015}}</ref> The low repayment rate made [[Strayer]] ineligible for receiving further Title IV funds in accordance with new \"Gainful employment\" regulations brought forth by the Department of Education, which were to take effect in July 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.insidehighered.com/content/download/357892/4393975/file/Gainful%20Employment%20NPRM.pdf |title=gainful employment NPRM |accessdate=March 19, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101105052245/http://www.insidehighered.com/content/download/357892/4393975/file/Gainful%20Employment%20NPRM.pdf |archivedate=November 5, 2010 }}</ref> If passed, the minimum loan repayment requirement for any institution receiving Title IV funds, subject to suspension and expulsion if not compliant, will be 45%.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/14/education/14college.html|work=The New York Times|title=Data Show Low Loan Repayment at For-Profit Schools|first=Tamar|last=Lewin|date=August 13, 2010}}</ref> In an August 4, 2010 Health, Education, Labor and Pensions Committee hearing, Gregory Kutz of the [[GAO]] stated that the fraudulent practices may be widespread in the For-Profit industry, noting a University of Phoenix executive chart that encouraged deceptive practices.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.c-spanvideo.org/program/294901-1|title=For-Profit College Financial Aid, Government Panel|publisher=C-SPAN|date=August 4, 2010|accessdate=March 19, 2011}}</ref> Joshua Pruyn, a former admissions representative, disclosed to the committee hearing several internal emails distributed among admissions officers in March 2008 which encouraged applications and enrollments through the use of a commissions reward system.\nDuring a congressional hearing to present the report, Pruyn's testimony was disproven by tapes of conversations, and it was reported that Pruyn's comments were written by attorneys who were suing Westwood,{{citation needed|date=October 2019}} and inappropriately coached by Chairman of the committee Senator [[Thomas Harkin]] staffers who organized the hearing.<ref name=07-21-2011>{{cite news|last=Strong|first=Jonathan|title=Dem Senator Accused of Witness Tampering|url=http://nation.foxnews.com/tom-harkin/2011/07/21/dem-senator-accused-witness-tampering|date=July 21, 2011|newspaper=Fox News|accessdate=July 4, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116132027/http://nation.foxnews.com/tom-harkin/2011/07/21/dem-senator-accused-witness-tampering|archive-date=January 16, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> Sen. Harkin noted the [[conflict of interest]] due to the ACCSC, a national accrediting agency that accredits many for-profit colleges nationwide,<ref name=\"accsc\">{{cite web|url=http://www.accsc.org/Content/CommissionActions/documents/STBCListAugust2010.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100917065411/http://accsc.org/Content/CommissionActions/documents/STBCListAugust2010.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 17, 2010 |publisher=accsc.org|title=404 |accessdate=February 18, 2017}}</ref> receiving compensation directly from the institutions to which it awards accreditation. The [[Inspector General]] issued an assessment in late 2009 recommending the limiting and possible suspension or expulsion of the [[Higher Learning Commission]] of the [[North Central Association of Colleges and Schools]] due to conflicts in the manner in which the accrediting agency reviews credit hours and program length for online-colleges, specifically [[American InterContinental University]], a for-profit college.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lloyd|first=Marion|url=http://chronicle.com/article/Inspector-Generals-Warning-to/63206/|title=Inspector General's Warning to Accreditor Raises Fears Among For-Profit Institutions|publisher=Chronicle of Higher Education|date=December 17, 2009|accessdate=March 19, 2011}}</ref> The NCA HLC accredits the [[University of Phoenix]] and Everest in Phoenix, Arizona. On November 30, 2010, the GAO issued a revised report, softening several examples from an undercover investigation and changing some key passages, but stood by its central finding that colleges had encouraged fraud and misled potential applicants.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/12/07/AR2010120706803.html|title=GAO revises its report critical of practices at for-profit schools|work=The Washington Post|first=Nick|last=Anderson|date=December 8, 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, a criminal investigation of [[Corinthian Colleges]] was initiated.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-corinthian-colleges-20140814-story.html|title=Corinthian Colleges tells investors it is facing a criminal probe|author=Los Angeles Times|date=August 13, 2014|work=latimes.com|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nUntil 2015, The US Attorney General and at least eleven states maintained an $11 billion lawsuit against [[Education Management Corporation]]\n<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/local/city/2014/05/06/Judge-says-lawsuit-against-Education-Management-can-continue/stories/201405060222|title=Judge says lawsuit against Education Management can continue|work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|accessdate=June 14, 2015|date=May 6, 2014}}</ref> The US [[Consumer Financial Protection Bureau]] also has a suit against ITT Educational Services, parent company of [[ITT Tech]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.republicreport.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/cfpb_complaint_ITT.pdf |title=Consumer Financial Protection Bureau v. ITT Educational Services, Inc. |publisher=Republicreport.org |accessdate=July 4, 2015}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.consumerfinance.gov/newsroom/cfpb-sues-for-profit-college-chain-itt-for-predatory-lending/|title=CFPB Sues For-Profit College Chain ITT For Predatory Lending|work=Consumer Financial Protection Bureau|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref>\nIn 2016, Alejandro Amor, the founder of FastTrain, was sentenced to eight years in federal prison for fraud.<ref name=\"npr\">{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/ed/2016/05/12/477655591/jail-time-for-a-for-profit-college-founder|publisher=npr.org|title=As Feds Crack Down On For-Profit College, A Founder Heads To Prison For Fraud : NPR Ed : NPR|accessdate=February 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Attempts to regulate and deregulate the industry==\nThe [[US Department of Education]] (DoED) has proposed rules, \"gainful employment regulations\", that would provide more transparency and accountability to institutions that offer professional and technical training. According to DoED, this regulation is an attempt to \"protect borrowers and taxpayers.\"<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Obama Administration Announces Final Rules to Protect Students from Poor-Performing Career College Programs |url= http://www.ed.gov/news/press-releases/obama-administration-announces-final-rules-protect-students-poor-performing-care|location= |publisher= [[United States Department of Education]] |agency= |date= October 30, 2014 |accessdate=January 16, 2015}}</ref> In his 2015 budget proposal, President Obama recommended greater regulation of for-profit education, including a closure of the loophole that exempted GI Bill money from being used in the 90-10 formula.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2015/02/03/obama-seeks-boost-higher-education-spending-and-proposes-some-loan-reforms-have|title=Obama seeks to boost higher education spending and proposes some loan reforms that have bipartisan appeal - InsideHigherEd|publisher=Insidehighered.com|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref>In 2017, the US Department of Education held public hearings were held in order to determine whether the government had overstepped regulation efforts, particularly with [[gainful employment]] and [[defense to repayment]] rules.<ref>https://www.usnews.com/news/education-news/articles/2017-07-10/trump-administration-begins-rewriting-for-profit-regulations</ref>\nIn August 2017, Secretary of Education Betsy DeVos instituted policies to loosen regulations on for-profit colleges.<ref name=\"consumerist.com\"/> In September 2017, the Trump Administration proposed to remove conflict of interest rules between VA officials and for-profit colleges.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/09/29/business/veterans-affairs-ethics.html|title=Veterans Agency Seeks to Scrap Ethics Law on For-Profit Colleges|first=Patricia|last=Cohen|date=September 29, 2017|publisher=|access-date=January 1, 2018|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref> In March 2018, the House Subcommittee on Labor, Health and Human Services, Education and Related Agencies began reviewing problems related to for-profit colleges and student loan debt.<ref name=courthousenews/>Lobbyists for the for-profit higher education industry have taken several steps to stop regulation and to fight against transparency and accountability.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/quicktakes/2014/11/07/profit-groups-sue-block-gainful-employment-rules|title=For-Profit Groups Sue to Block Gainful Employment Rules |publisher=Insidehighered.com|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref> They have also supported at least two lawsuits to squash gainful employment regulations.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.career.org/news-and-media/press-releases/upload/APSCU-v-Duncan-DDC-2014-11-06-Plaintiff-s-Complaint.pdf |title=Association of Private Sector Colleges and Universities v. Arne Duncan |publisher=Career.org |accessdate=July 4, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150329192846/http://www.career.org/news-and-media/press-releases/upload/APSCU-v-Duncan-DDC-2014-11-06-Plaintiff-s-Complaint.pdf |archive-date=March 29, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxbusiness.com/markets/2014/11/07/for-profit-colleges-file-lawsuit-to-halt-new-obama-administration-regulations/|title=For-profit colleges file lawsuit to halt new Obama administration regulations|work=Fox Business|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.apscu.org/news-and-media/press-releases/upload/APSCU-v-Duncan-DDC-2015-02-06-Plaintiff-s-Motion-for-Summary-Judgment2.pdf |title=Association of Private Sector Colleges and Universities v. Arne Duncan |publisher=Apscu.org |accessdate=July 4, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150209223722/http://www.apscu.org/news-and-media/press-releases/upload/APSCU-v-Duncan-DDC-2015-02-06-Plaintiff-s-Motion-for-Summary-Judgment2.pdf |archive-date=February 9, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==For-profit colleges transitioning to nonprofit colleges==\nAt least three colleges or universities have transitioned to nonprofit status: [[Keiser University]], [[Remington College]], and [[Herzing University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chronicle.com/blogs/ticker/for-profit-herzing-u-converts-to-nonprofit-status/91695|title=For-Profit Herzing U. Converts to Nonprofit Status \u2013 The Ticker - Blogs - The Chronicle of Higher Education|publisher=Chronicle.com|accessdate=June 14, 2015|date=January 5, 2015}}</ref> Journalists argue that these transitions are strategies to reduce state and federal regulations and to obtain more [[Title IV]] funds, as well as to improve reputations as for-profit education now has a stigma to the public.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/davidhalperin/if-a-for-profit-college-b_b_2661788.html|title=If a For-Profit College Becomes a Non-Profit, Is That Good? Not Necessarily|work=The Huffington Post|accessdate=June 14, 2015|date=February 11, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jsonline.com/business/herzing-university-becomes-a-nonprofit-organization-b99419151z1-287365131.html|title=Herzing University becomes a nonprofit organization|author=Rick Romell|publisher=Jsonline.com|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref> In 2014 [[Grand Canyon University]] considered a transition to nonprofit status.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2014-11-13/grand-canyon-eyes-2-billion-exit-from-for-profit-college-stigma.html|title=Grand Canyon Eyes $2 Billion Exit From For-Profit College Stigma|author=Michael McDonald|date=November 13, 2014|work=Bloomberg.com|accessdate=June 14, 2015}}</ref> In 2016, Grand Canyon's regional accreditation body, [[The Higher Learning Commission]], formally rejected the university's petition for conversion to non-profit status. The commission's board of directors stated that the school did not meet all five criteria for \"such a conversion\".<ref name=\"www.hlcommission.org\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hlcommission.org/download/_PublicDisclosureNotices/Grand%20Canyon%20University%20PDN.pdf|title=Public Disclosure Notice|website=HLCommission.org|access-date=January 1, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"ktar.com\">{{cite web|url=http://ktar.com/story/946879/grand-canyon-university-denied-switch-to-nonprofit-status/|publisher=ktar.com|title=Grand Canyon University denied switch to nonprofit status|accessdate=February 18, 2017|date=March 4, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"www.abc15.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.abc15.com/news/region-phoenix-metro/central-phoenix/grand-canyon-university-denied-request-to-switch-to-nonprofit-status|publisher=abc15.com|title=Grand Canyon University denied request to switch to nonprofit status - ABC15 Arizona|accessdate=February 18, 2017|date=March 4, 2016}}</ref> In 2017, [[Kaplan University]] was sold to [[Purdue University]] and became [[Purdue University Global]] in 2018. Kaplan, however, became the servicer for the institution and the Higher Learning Commission continued to accredit the school.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.purdue.edu/newsroom/releases/2018/Q1/purdue-announces-name-for-new-public-university-purdue-university-global-to-serve-working-adults,-online.html |title = Purdue announces name for new public university: Purdue University Global to serve working adults, online}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.jconline.com/story/news/2018/09/10/regulators-purdue-campus-review-purdue-global-deal/1252718002/ |title = Regulators return to Purdue campus to review Purdue Global deal}}</ref> In 2018, [[Grand Canyon University]] and [[Ashford University]] petitioned for non-profit status.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2018/03/13/ashford-university-latest-big-profit-attempt-nonprofit-conversion|title=Ashford University is latest big for-profit to attempt nonprofit conversion|author=|date=|website=insidehighered.com}}</ref> In 2018, Grand Canyon University attempted to regain its non-profit status<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/news/local/arizona-education/2018/07/02/grand-canyon-university-regains-its-non-profit-status/747376002/|title=It's official: Grand Canyon University has its non-profit status back|first=Rachel|last=Leingang|website=azcentral}}</ref> but the [[U.S. Department of Education]] denied that change in 2019, and continues to classify the university as for-profit.<ref name=CollegeNavigator>{{cite web |url=https://nces.ed.gov/collegenavigator/?id=104717 |title=College Navigator |publisher=[[National Center for Education Statistics]] |date=2019 |accessdate=September 30, 2019}}</ref><ref name=IHE_for-profit>{{cite web |url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2019/11/07/education-department-calls-grand-canyon-profit-raising-questions-about-conversion |title=Surprise for Grand Canyon's Nonprofit Conversion |first=Paul |last=Fain |publisher=[[Inside Higher Ed]] |date=November 7, 2019 |accessdate=November 7, 2019}}</ref> In 2019, the [[Internal Revenue Service]] granted [[Ashford University]] non-profit tax status. Ashford University was the major source of revenue for [[Bridgepoint Education]], now known as [[Zovio]].<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.educationdive.com/news/irs-approval-brings-ashford-u-a-step-closer-to-nonprofit-status/548718/ |title = IRS approval brings Ashford U a step closer to nonprofit status}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Business college]]\n* [[Career college]]\n* [[Diploma mill]]\n* [[Higher education in the United States]]\n* [[List of for-profit universities and colleges]]\n* [[List of unaccredited institutions of higher education]]\n* [[Online program manager]]\n* [[Privatization in the United States]]\n* [[Student debt]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Schools}}\n\n[[Category:School types]]\n[[Category:For-profit universities and colleges in the United States| ]]\n[[Category:Higher education in the United States]]\n[[Category:Education policy in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "CollegeMeltdown", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFor-profit online program managers (OPMs)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/For-profit_higher_education_in_the_United_States"}
